\section{Lecture 1}

\subsection{Course overview}

This course studies stochastic processes, namely random objects indexed by time:
\[
(X_t : t\in T).
\]

There are two basic choices for the time index set:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item \textbf{Discrete time:} for example \(T=\mathbb N=\{0,1,2,\dots\}\);
    \item \textbf{Continuous time:} for example \(T=\mathbb R_+=[0,\infty)\).
\end{itemize}

There are also different choices for the state space:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item \textbf{Discrete state space:} finite or countably infinite;
    \item \textbf{Continuous state space:} for example \(\mathbb R\) or \(\mathbb R^d\).
\end{itemize}

The main topics of the course are:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item \textbf{Markov chains / Markov processes,} where the future depends on the present state;
    \item \textbf{Martingales,} which model ``fair game'' phenomena;
    \item \textbf{Brownian motion and stochastic calculus.}
\end{itemize}

Lecture 1 begins with the simplest setting: \textbf{discrete-time, discrete-state, time-homogeneous Markov chains}.

\subsection{Definition of a discrete-time Markov chain}

Let \(S\) be a finite or countably infinite set. A discrete-time Markov chain is a stochastic process
\[
(X_0,X_1,X_2,\dots), \qquad X_t\in S,
\]
specified by the following three ingredients.

\begin{definition}[Discrete-time, discrete-state, time-homogeneous Markov chain]
A process \((X_t)_{t\ge 0}\) on \(S\) is called a Markov chain if:
\begin{enumerate}[label=(\roman*)]
    \item \textbf{State space:} \(S\) is finite or countably infinite.
    
    \item \textbf{Initial distribution:} there is a probability vector
    \[
    \nu=(\nu_i)_{i\in S},
    \qquad
    \nu_i=\mathbb P(X_0=i),
    \]
    with
    \[
    \nu_i\ge 0,
    \qquad
    \sum_{i\in S}\nu_i=1.
    \]
    
    \item \textbf{Transition probabilities:} there is a matrix
    \[
    P=(p_{ij})_{i,j\in S},
    \]
    where
    \[
    p_{ij}=\mathbb P(X_{t+1}=j\mid X_t=i),
    \qquad i,j\in S,
    \]
    and for each fixed \(i\),
    \[
    p_{ij}\ge 0,
    \qquad
    \sum_{j\in S} p_{ij}=1.
    \]
\end{enumerate}
Moreover, the chain satisfies the \emph{Markov property}
\[
\mathbb P(X_{t+1}=j\mid X_0=i_0,X_1=i_1,\dots,X_t=i)
=
\mathbb P(X_{t+1}=j\mid X_t=i)
=
p_{ij}.
\]
\end{definition}

The word \emph{time-homogeneous} means that the transition law does \emph{not} depend on \(t\). In other words, the same matrix \(P\) is used at every step.

\subsection{The Markov property}

Informally, the Markov property says:

\begin{quote}
Given the present, the future is independent of the past.
\end{quote}

More precisely, once the current state \(X_t\) is known, the whole earlier history
\[
X_0,X_1,\dots,X_{t-1}
\]
becomes irrelevant for predicting the next step.

This does \emph{not} mean the process has no memory at all. It means that all relevant information from the past is summarized by the current state.

\begin{keyformula}
For a Markov chain,
\[
\mathbb P(X_{t+1}=j\mid X_0,\dots,X_t)
=
\mathbb P(X_{t+1}=j\mid X_t)
=
p_{X_t j}.
\]
So the next move depends only on the current state.
\end{keyformula}

\subsection{Example: frog on lily pads}

Consider a frog moving on \(20\) lily pads arranged in a circle. Let
\[
X_t=\text{the index of the lily pad occupied by the frog at time } t.
\]
Then the state space is
\[
S=\{1,2,3,\dots,20\}.
\]

Suppose the frog starts at lily pad \(3\), so the initial distribution is
\[
\nu_i=
\begin{cases}
1, & i=3,\\
0, & i\ne 3.
\end{cases}
\]

At each step, the frog:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item stays where it is with probability \(1/3\),
    \item moves one pad clockwise with probability \(1/3\),
    \item moves one pad counterclockwise with probability \(1/3\).
\end{itemize}

Thus the transition probabilities are
\[
p_{ij}=
\begin{cases}
\frac13, & j=i,\\[0.4em]
\frac13, & j\equiv i+1 \pmod{20},\\[0.4em]
\frac13, & j\equiv i-1 \pmod{20},\\[0.4em]
0, & \text{otherwise.}
\end{cases}
\]

So from each state there are exactly three possible next moves. This is a typical finite-state Markov chain.

\begin{remark}
The transition matrix here is a \(20\times 20\) matrix. Most entries are \(0\), and each row has exactly three entries equal to \(1/3\).
\end{remark}

\subsection{Example: coin tossing}

At each time \(t=1,2,3,\dots\), toss a fair coin and let
\[
X_t=\text{number of heads obtained in the first \(t\) tosses}.
\]

Then the state space is
\[
S=\{0,1,2,\dots\}.
\]

The chain starts at
\[
X_0=0,
\]
so
\[
\nu_0=1,
\qquad
\nu_i=0 \quad (i\ge 1).
\]

If the current value is \(i\), then after one more toss:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item the value stays at \(i\) if the new toss is tails;
    \item the value moves to \(i+1\) if the new toss is heads.
\end{itemize}

Hence
\[
p_{ij}=
\begin{cases}
\frac12, & j=i,\\[0.4em]
\frac12, & j=i+1,\\[0.4em]
0, & \text{otherwise.}
\end{cases}
\]

This is again a Markov chain, because given the current number of heads, the next step depends only on the next toss, not on the whole previous sequence.

\subsection{Example: Ehrenfest's urn}

There are two boxes containing a total of \(d\) balls. Initially, box \(1\) contains \(a\) balls and box \(2\) contains \(b\) balls, where
\[
d=a+b.
\]

At each step:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item choose one of the \(d\) balls uniformly at random;
    \item move that ball to the opposite box.
\end{itemize}

Let
\[
X_t=\text{number of balls in box \(1\) at time } t.
\]

Then the state space is
\[
S=\{0,1,2,\dots,d\}.
\]

Since initially there are \(a\) balls in box \(1\),
\[
\nu_i=
\begin{cases}
1, & i=a,\\
0, & i\ne a.
\end{cases}
\]

If \(X_t=i\), then box \(1\) currently contains \(i\) balls and box \(2\) contains \(d-i\) balls.

So:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item with probability \(\frac{d-i}{d}\), we choose a ball from box \(2\) and move it into box \(1\), so
    \[
    X_{t+1}=i+1;
    \]
    \item with probability \(\frac{i}{d}\), we choose a ball from box \(1\) and move it into box \(2\), so
    \[
    X_{t+1}=i-1.
    \]
\end{itemize}

Therefore
\[
p_{ij}=
\begin{cases}
\frac{d-i}{d}, & j=i+1,\\[0.4em]
\frac{i}{d}, & j=i-1,\\[0.4em]
0, & \text{otherwise.}
\end{cases}
\]

This is a fundamental example of a Markov chain arising from a physical model.

\subsection{A non-example}

Not every stochastic process is Markov.

For example, suppose the next move depends not only on the current state \(X_t\), but also on whether the chain visited some state earlier in its history. Then the transition rule depends on the past before time \(t\), so the Markov property fails.

So the essential feature of a Markov chain is:
\begin{quote}
the future depends on the present state only, not on the whole past trajectory.
\end{quote}

\subsection{A basic consequence of the Markov property}

Throughout, for \(i\in S\), write
\[
\mathbb P_i(\,\cdot\,)=\mathbb P(\,\cdot\,\mid X_0=i),
\qquad
\mathbb E_i[\cdot]=\mathbb E[\cdot\mid X_0=i].
\]

The Markov property immediately gives the following important factorization rule.

\begin{proposition}[Path probability]
For any states \(i_0,i_1,\dots,i_n\in S\),
\[
\mathbb P(X_0=i_0,X_1=i_1,\dots,X_n=i_n)
=
\nu_{i_0}\,p_{i_0i_1}p_{i_1i_2}\cdots p_{i_{n-1}i_n}.
\]
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
Using conditional probability,
\begin{align*}
&\mathbb P(X_0=i_0,X_1=i_1,\dots,X_n=i_n) \\
&\qquad =
\mathbb P(X_0=i_0)\,
\mathbb P(X_1=i_1\mid X_0=i_0)\,
\mathbb P(X_2=i_2\mid X_0=i_0,X_1=i_1)\cdots \\
&\qquad\qquad \cdots
\mathbb P(X_n=i_n\mid X_0=i_0,\dots,X_{n-1}=i_{n-1}).
\end{align*}
Now apply the Markov property at each step:
\[
\mathbb P(X_{m+1}=i_{m+1}\mid X_0=i_0,\dots,X_m=i_m)=p_{i_m i_{m+1}}.
\]
So the product reduces to
\[
\nu_{i_0}\,p_{i_0i_1}p_{i_1i_2}\cdots p_{i_{n-1}i_n}.
\]
\end{proof}

A useful special case is:
\[
\mathbb P(X_0=i_0,X_1=i_1,X_2=i_2)=\nu_{i_0}p_{i_0i_1}p_{i_1i_2}.
\]

If we sum over the intermediate state \(i_1\), we get
\[
\mathbb P(X_0=i_0,X_2=i_2)
=
\nu_{i_0}\sum_{i_1\in S}p_{i_0i_1}p_{i_1i_2}.
\]

This is exactly matrix multiplication.

\subsection{Matrix notation and multi-step transitions}

For matrices \(A=(a_{ik})\) and \(B=(b_{kj})\) indexed by \(S\), define
\[
[AB]_{ij}=\sum_{k\in S} a_{ik}b_{kj}.
\]

When \(S\) is countably infinite, these are infinite-dimensional matrices. In general one must be careful with convergence, but for probability transition matrices the relevant sums are nonnegative and bounded by \(1\), so the formulas below make sense.

\begin{definition}[\(n\)-step transition probabilities]
For \(n\ge 0\), define
\[
p_{ij}^{(n)}=\mathbb P(X_n=j\mid X_0=i)=\mathbb P_i(X_n=j).
\]
\end{definition}

For \(n=1\), this is just
\[
p_{ij}^{(1)}=p_{ij}.
\]

For \(n=0\), by convention,
\[
p_{ij}^{(0)}=
\begin{cases}
1, & i=j,\\
0, & i\ne j.
\end{cases}
\]

\begin{proposition}
For every integer \(n\ge 0\),
\[
\mathbb P_i(X_n=j)=[P^n]_{ij}.
\]
Equivalently,
\[
p_{ij}^{(n)}=[P^n]_{ij}.
\]
\end{proposition}

Also, if the initial distribution is \(\nu\), then
\[
\mathbb P(X_n=j)=[\nu P^n]_j.
\]

\begin{keyformula}
The matrix power \(P^n\) describes the \(n\)-step movement of the chain:
\[
p_{ij}^{(n)}=[P^n]_{ij},
\qquad
\mathbb P(X_n=j)=[\nu P^n]_j.
\]
\end{keyformula}

\subsection{Chapman--Kolmogorov equation}

The \(n\)-step transition probabilities satisfy the most important algebraic identity in the theory.

\begin{theorem}[Chapman--Kolmogorov equation]
For all \(m,n\ge 0\) and all \(i,j\in S\),
\[
p_{ij}^{(m+n)}
=
\sum_{k\in S} p_{ik}^{(m)}p_{kj}^{(n)}.
\]
Equivalently,
\[
P^{m+n}=P^mP^n.
\]
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
Condition on the state at time \(m\):
\begin{align*}
p_{ij}^{(m+n)}
&=\mathbb P_i(X_{m+n}=j) \\
&=\sum_{k\in S}\mathbb P_i(X_{m+n}=j,X_m=k) \\
&=\sum_{k\in S}\mathbb P_i(X_{m+n}=j\mid X_m=k)\mathbb P_i(X_m=k).
\end{align*}
By the Markov property,
\[
\mathbb P_i(X_{m+n}=j\mid X_m=k)=\mathbb P_k(X_n=j)=p_{kj}^{(n)},
\]
and
\[
\mathbb P_i(X_m=k)=p_{ik}^{(m)}.
\]
Hence
\[
p_{ij}^{(m+n)}
=
\sum_{k\in S} p_{ik}^{(m)}p_{kj}^{(n)}.
\]
\end{proof}

\begin{keyformula}
To go from \(i\) to \(j\) in \(m+n\) steps, sum over all possible intermediate states \(k\) at time \(m\):
\[
p_{ij}^{(m+n)}
=
\sum_{k\in S} p_{ik}^{(m)}p_{kj}^{(n)}.
\]
\end{keyformula}

\subsection{Counting visits to a state}

To study long-run behavior, define the total number of visits to a state after time \(0\).

\begin{definition}
For \(j\in S\), let
\[
N(j)=\sum_{t=1}^{\infty}\mathbf 1_{\{X_t=j\}}.
\]
\end{definition}

So \(N(j)\) counts how many times the chain visits state \(j\) at times \(1,2,3,\dots\).

This random variable may be finite or infinite.

\subsection{Hitting probabilities}

\begin{definition}
For \(i,j\in S\), define
\[
f_{ij}=\mathbb P_i(N(j)\ge 1).
\]
\end{definition}

This is the probability that starting from \(i\), the chain hits \(j\) at least once at some future time.

In particular,
\[
f_{ii}
\]
is the probability of ever returning to \(i\) after time \(0\).

\begin{definition}[Recurrence and transience]
A state \(i\) is called
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item \textbf{recurrent} if \(f_{ii}=1\);
    \item \textbf{transient} if \(f_{ii}<1\).
\end{itemize}
\end{definition}

So:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item recurrent means that if we start at \(i\), then we return to \(i\) eventually with probability \(1\);
    \item transient means there is a positive probability that after leaving \(i\), we never come back.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{A first geometric law}

A key fact from the lecture is that repeated returns behave geometrically.

\begin{proposition}
For every state \(i\in S\) and every integer \(k\ge 1\),
\[
\mathbb P_i(N(i)\ge k)=f_{ii}^k.
\]
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}[Idea]
For \(k=1\), this is exactly the definition of \(f_{ii}\).

Now suppose the chain has already returned to \(i\) \(k-1\) times. Once it is back at \(i\), the future evolution starts afresh from \(i\). Therefore the probability of one more return is again \(f_{ii}\).

By repeating this argument,
\[
\mathbb P_i(N(i)\ge k)
=
f_{ii}\cdot f_{ii}\cdots f_{ii}
=
f_{ii}^k.
\]
The rigorous justification uses the strong Markov property at successive hitting times of \(i\).
\end{proof}

\subsubsection*{Formal proof}

Let
\[
\tau_1:=\inf\{n\ge 1:X_n=i\},
\]
and for each \(m\ge 2\), define recursively
\[
\tau_m:=\inf\{n>\tau_{m-1}:X_n=i\}.
\]
As usual, we adopt the convention \(\inf\varnothing=\infty\).

Then \(\tau_m\) is the time of the \(m\)-th return to the state \(i\). Hence
\[
\{N(i)\ge k\}=\{\tau_k<\infty\}.
\]
Therefore it is enough to prove that
\[
P_i(\tau_k<\infty)=f_{ii}^k,\qquad k\ge 1.
\]

By definition of the return probability,
\[
f_{ii}=P_i(\tau_1<\infty).
\]

We now prove by induction on \(k\) that
\[
P_i(\tau_k<\infty)=f_{ii}^k.
\]

For \(k=1\), this is immediate from the definition:
\[
P_i(\tau_1<\infty)=f_{ii}.
\]

Now suppose \(k\ge 2\), and assume that \(P_i(\tau_{k-1}<\infty)=f_{ii}^{\,k-1}\). We show that
\[
P_i(\tau_k<\infty)=f_{ii}\,P_i(\tau_{k-1}<\infty).
\]

On the event \(\{\tau_{k-1}<\infty\}\), we have \(X_{\tau_{k-1}}=i\). After time \(\tau_{k-1}\), define
\[
\sigma:=\inf\{m\ge 1:X_{\tau_{k-1}+m}=i\}.
\]
Then on \(\{\tau_{k-1}<\infty\}\), the event \(\{\tau_k<\infty\}\) is exactly the event \(\{\sigma<\infty\}\). Thus
\[
P_i(\tau_k<\infty)
=
E_i\!\left[\mathbf{1}_{\{\tau_{k-1}<\infty\}}\mathbf{1}_{\{\sigma<\infty\}}\right].
\]

Now condition on \(\mathcal{F}_{\tau_{k-1}}\). Since \(\tau_{k-1}\) is a stopping time, the strong Markov property implies that on the event \(\{\tau_{k-1}<\infty\}\),
\[
P_i(\sigma<\infty\mid \mathcal{F}_{\tau_{k-1}})
=
P_{X_{\tau_{k-1}}}(\tau_1<\infty).
\]
But \(X_{\tau_{k-1}}=i\) on \(\{\tau_{k-1}<\infty\}\), so
\[
P_i(\sigma<\infty\mid \mathcal{F}_{\tau_{k-1}})
=
P_i(\tau_1<\infty)
=
f_{ii}.
\]

Therefore,
\[
\begin{aligned}
P_i(\tau_k<\infty)
&=
E_i\!\left[
\mathbf{1}_{\{\tau_{k-1}<\infty\}}
E_i\!\left[\mathbf{1}_{\{\sigma<\infty\}}\mid \mathcal{F}_{\tau_{k-1}}\right]
\right] \\
&=
E_i\!\left[
\mathbf{1}_{\{\tau_{k-1}<\infty\}}
P_i(\sigma<\infty\mid \mathcal{F}_{\tau_{k-1}})
\right] \\
&=
E_i\!\left[
\mathbf{1}_{\{\tau_{k-1}<\infty\}}\,f_{ii}
\right] \\
&=
f_{ii}\,P_i(\tau_{k-1}<\infty).
\end{aligned}
\]

Using the induction hypothesis,
\[
P_i(\tau_k<\infty)
=
f_{ii}\,f_{ii}^{\,k-1}
=
f_{ii}^k.
\]

Thus for every integer \(k\ge 1\),
\[
P_i(N(i)\ge k)=P_i(\tau_k<\infty)=f_{ii}^k.
\]
This completes the proof.

This already explains the recurrence/transience dichotomy:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item if \(f_{ii}=1\), then
    \[
    \mathbb P_i(N(i)\ge k)=1 \quad \text{for every } k,
    \]
    so the chain returns to \(i\) infinitely many times almost surely;
    \item if \(f_{ii}<1\), then the tail probabilities decay geometrically.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Strong Markov viewpoint}

Let
\[
\tau_i=\inf\{t\ge 1:X_t=i\}
\]
be the first return/hitting time of state \(i\) after time \(0\).

More generally, if we are interested in the first time the chain hits a state \(j\), we use
\[
\tau_j=\inf\{t\ge 0:X_t=j\}.
\]

The strong Markov principle says that once the chain hits a state, the future from that time onward behaves like a fresh Markov chain started from that state.

Informally,
\[
(X_{\tau_i},X_{\tau_i+1},X_{\tau_i+2},\dots)
\]
has the same law as a new chain started from \(i\), on the event \(\{\tau_i<\infty\}\).

This is the key reason the geometric formulas above work.

\subsection{Generalization to different starting and target states}

Now fix \(i,j\in S\). Starting from \(i\), the chain must first hit \(j\) once, and after that, each additional visit to \(j\) behaves like a fresh chain started from \(j\).

Therefore for every \(k\ge 1\),
\[
\mathbb P_i(N(j)\ge k)=f_{ij}\,f_{jj}^{\,k-1}.
\]

Indeed:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item \(f_{ij}\) is the probability of hitting \(j\) at least once;
    \item after the first visit to \(j\), the probability of getting at least \(k-1\) more visits is \(f_{jj}^{\,k-1}\).
\end{itemize}

\begin{keyformula}
For \(k\ge 1\),
\[
\mathbb P_i(N(j)\ge k)=f_{ij}\,f_{jj}^{\,k-1}.
\]
This is one of the most useful formulas in Lecture 1.
\end{keyformula}

\subsection{Consequences for the distribution of \texorpdfstring{$N(i)$}{N(i)}}

Take \(j=i\). If \(f_{ii}<1\), then
\[
\mathbb P_i(N(i)\ge k)=f_{ii}^k,
\qquad k\ge 0,
\]
where the \(k=0\) case is trivial.

Hence
\[
\mathbb P_i(N(i)=k)
=
\mathbb P_i(N(i)\ge k)-\mathbb P_i(N(i)\ge k+1)
=
f_{ii}^k-f_{ii}^{k+1},
\qquad k=0,1,2,\dots
\]
which is a geometric distribution.

So:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item if \(f_{ii}=1\), then
    \[
    N(i)=\infty
    \qquad \text{almost surely under } \mathbb P_i;
    \]
    \item if \(f_{ii}<1\), then
    \[
    \mathbb P_i(N(i)=k)=f_{ii}^k(1-f_{ii}),
    \qquad k=0,1,2,\dots
    \]
    and \(N(i)\) is geometric.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Geometric random variable}

We now explain why the random variable \(N(i)\) has a geometric distribution when \(f_{ii}<1\).

Recall that if \(f_{ii}<1\), then for every integer \(k\ge 0\),
\[
P_i\bigl(N(i)\ge k\bigr)=f_{ii}^k.
\]
Therefore,
\[
P_i\bigl(N(i)=k\bigr)
=
P_i\bigl(N(i)\ge k\bigr)-P_i\bigl(N(i)\ge k+1\bigr)
=
f_{ii}^k-f_{ii}^{k+1}
=
f_{ii}^k(1-f_{ii}),
\qquad k=0,1,2,\dots
\]

This is exactly the probability mass function of a geometric random variable on
\(\{0,1,2,\dots\}\) with parameter
\[
p=1-f_{ii}.
\]

\medskip

\noindent
\textbf{Definition.}
A random variable \(X\) is said to have a geometric distribution with parameter \(p\in(0,1]\) on
\(\{0,1,2,\dots\}\) if
\[
P(X=k)=(1-p)^k p,\qquad k=0,1,2,\dots
\]
In our case, taking
\[
p=1-f_{ii},
\]
we get
\[
P_i\bigl(N(i)=k\bigr)=f_{ii}^k(1-f_{ii})=(1-p)^k p,
\]
so \(N(i)\) is geometric.

\medskip

\noindent
\textbf{Probability mass function (pmf).}
If \(X\sim \mathrm{Geom}(p)\) on \(\{0,1,2,\dots\}\), then
\[
P(X=k)=(1-p)^k p,\qquad k=0,1,2,\dots
\]

\medskip

\noindent
\textbf{Tail probabilities.}
For \(k\ge 0\),
\[
P(X\ge k)=\sum_{m=k}^{\infty}(1-p)^m p=(1-p)^k.
\]
This is exactly the form we found above:
\[
P_i\bigl(N(i)\ge k\bigr)=f_{ii}^k.
\]
So here the role of \(1-p\) is played by \(f_{ii}\).

\medskip

\noindent
\textbf{Cumulative distribution function (cdf).}
For \(k=0,1,2,\dots\),
\[
P(X\le k)=1-P(X\ge k+1)=1-(1-p)^{k+1}.
\]

\medskip

\noindent
\textbf{Expectation.}
If \(X\sim \mathrm{Geom}(p)\) on \(\{0,1,2,\dots\}\), then
\[
E[X]=\frac{1-p}{p}.
\]
Hence for \(N(i)\),
\[
E_i[N(i)]
=
\frac{f_{ii}}{1-f_{ii}},
\qquad \text{when } f_{ii}<1.
\]

\medskip

\noindent
\textbf{Variance.}
If \(X\sim \mathrm{Geom}(p)\) on \(\{0,1,2,\dots\}\), then
\[
\mathrm{Var}(X)=\frac{1-p}{p^2}.
\]
Thus for \(N(i)\),
\[
\mathrm{Var}_i(N(i))
=
\frac{f_{ii}}{(1-f_{ii})^2},
\qquad \text{when } f_{ii}<1.
\]

\medskip

\noindent
\textbf{Memoryless property.}
A geometric random variable is memoryless:
\[
P(X\ge m+n\mid X\ge m)=P(X\ge n),
\qquad m,n\ge 0.
\]
Indeed,
\[
P(X\ge m+n\mid X\ge m)
=
\frac{P(X\ge m+n)}{P(X\ge m)}
=
\frac{(1-p)^{m+n}}{(1-p)^m}
=
(1-p)^n
=
P(X\ge n).
\]
This matches the Markov chain interpretation: once the chain returns to \(i\), the future starts afresh, so the chance of making further returns is the same as before.

\medskip

\noindent
\textbf{Conclusion for \(N(i)\).}
Therefore:
\begin{itemize}
    \item If \(f_{ii}=1\), then
    \[
    P_i\bigl(N(i)\ge k\bigr)=1 \quad \text{for every } k,
    \]
    so
    \[
    N(i)=\infty \quad \text{almost surely under } P_i.
    \]

    \item If \(f_{ii}<1\), then
    \[
    P_i\bigl(N(i)=k\bigr)=f_{ii}^k(1-f_{ii}),\qquad k=0,1,2,\dots,
    \]
    so \(N(i)\) is geometric on \(\{0,1,2,\dots\}\) with parameter \(1-f_{ii}\).
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Expected number of visits}

Using the tail-sum formula,
\[
\mathbb E_i[N(j)]
=
\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\mathbb P_i(N(j)\ge k).
\]

Substituting the formula above gives:
\[
\mathbb E_i[N(j)]
=
\sum_{k=1}^{\infty} f_{ij}f_{jj}^{\,k-1}.
\]

Therefore
\[
\mathbb E_i[N(j)]
=
\begin{cases}
\dfrac{f_{ij}}{1-f_{jj}}, & f_{jj}<1,\\[1em]
+\infty, & f_{jj}=1 \text{ and } f_{ij}>0,\\[0.4em]
0, & f_{ij}=0.
\end{cases}
\]

In particular,
\[
\mathbb E_i[N(i)]
=
\begin{cases}
\dfrac{f_{ii}}{1-f_{ii}}, & f_{ii}<1,\\[1em]
+\infty, & f_{ii}=1.
\end{cases}
\]

So recurrence is equivalent to having infinitely many expected returns.

\subsection{Recurrence state theorem}

The transition probabilities themselves can be used to detect recurrence.

\begin{theorem}[Recurrence state theorem]
A state \(i\) is recurrent if and only if
\[
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} p_{ii}^{(n)}=+\infty.
\]
Equivalently, \(i\) is transient if and only if
\[
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} p_{ii}^{(n)}<\infty.
\]
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
By definition,
\[
N(i)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\mathbf 1_{\{X_n=i\}}.
\]
Taking expectation under \(\mathbb P_i\),
\[
\mathbb E_i[N(i)]
=
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\mathbb E_i[\mathbf 1_{\{X_n=i\}}]
=
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\mathbb P_i(X_n=i)
=
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} p_{ii}^{(n)}.
\]

On the other hand, from the previous subsection,
\[
\mathbb E_i[N(i)]
=
\begin{cases}
\dfrac{f_{ii}}{1-f_{ii}}, & f_{ii}<1,\\[1em]
+\infty, & f_{ii}=1.
\end{cases}
\]

Thus
\[
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} p_{ii}^{(n)}=+\infty
\quad \Longleftrightarrow \quad
f_{ii}=1,
\]
which is exactly the statement that \(i\) is recurrent.
\end{proof}

\begin{keyformula}
A state \(i\) is recurrent exactly when
\[
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} p_{ii}^{(n)}=\infty.
\]
So recurrence can be tested by looking at the return probabilities \(p_{ii}^{(n)}\).
\end{keyformula}

\subsection{Example: simple random walk on \texorpdfstring{$\mathbb Z$}{Z}}

Consider the simple random walk on the integers:
\[
S=\mathbb Z,
\qquad
p_{i,i+1}=p_{i,i-1}=\frac12,
\qquad i\in\mathbb Z.
\]

We ask whether state \(0\) is recurrent.

By symmetry and translation invariance, it is enough to study returns to \(0\).

First, if \(n\) is odd, then
\[
p_{00}^{(n)}=0,
\]
because after an odd number of steps the walk cannot be back at the origin.

Now let \(n=2m\). To return to \(0\) after \(2m\) steps, the walk must make exactly \(m\) upward steps and \(m\) downward steps. Hence
\[
p_{00}^{(2m)}
=
\binom{2m}{m}\left(\frac12\right)^{2m}.
\]

Using Stirling's formula,
\[
m!\sim \sqrt{2\pi m}\left(\frac{m}{e}\right)^m,
\]
one obtains the classical asymptotic
\[
\binom{2m}{m}\sim \frac{4^m}{\sqrt{\pi m}}.
\]
Therefore
\[
p_{00}^{(2m)}
=
\binom{2m}{m}\,2^{-2m}
\sim \frac{1}{\sqrt{\pi m}}.
\]

Since
\[
\sum_{m=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{\sqrt{m}}=+\infty,
\]
it follows that
\[
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} p_{00}^{(n)}
=
\sum_{m=1}^{\infty} p_{00}^{(2m)}
=+\infty.
\]

By the recurrence state theorem, state \(0\) is recurrent.

Because the simple random walk on \(\mathbb Z\) is irreducible, every state communicates with \(0\). Hence every state is recurrent.

\begin{summarybox}
For simple random walk on \(\mathbb Z\),
\[
p_{00}^{(2m)}=\binom{2m}{m}2^{-2m}\sim \frac{1}{\sqrt{\pi m}},
\qquad
p_{00}^{(2m+1)}=0.
\]
Since the series of return probabilities diverges, the walk is recurrent.
\end{summarybox}

\subsection{Summary of Lecture 1}

\begin{summarybox}
Lecture 1 introduces discrete-time Markov chains and the first long-run questions.

Main points:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item A Markov chain is determined by a state space \(S\), an initial distribution \(\nu\), and a transition matrix \(P\).
    \item The Markov property says the next step depends only on the current state.
    \item Important examples include the frog on a circle, coin tossing, and Ehrenfest's urn.
    \item The probability of a path factors as
    \[
    \nu_{i_0}p_{i_0i_1}\cdots p_{i_{n-1}i_n}.
    \]
    \item The \(n\)-step transition probabilities are given by matrix powers:
    \[
    p_{ij}^{(n)}=[P^n]_{ij}.
    \]
    \item Chapman--Kolmogorov:
    \[
    p_{ij}^{(m+n)}=\sum_{k\in S}p_{ik}^{(m)}p_{kj}^{(n)}.
    \]
    \item The total number of future visits to a state is
    \[
    N(j)=\sum_{t=1}^{\infty}\mathbf 1_{\{X_t=j\}}.
    \]
    \item The hitting probabilities
    \[
    f_{ij}=\mathbb P_i(N(j)\ge 1)
    \]
    lead to the definitions of recurrence and transience.
    \item A state \(i\) is recurrent iff
    \[
    \sum_{n=1}^{\infty} p_{ii}^{(n)}=\infty.
    \]
    \item Simple random walk on \(\mathbb Z\) is recurrent.
\end{itemize}
\end{summarybox}

