\section{Lecture 2}

\subsection{Recall from Lecture 1: recurrence criterion}

From the previous lecture, a state \(i\) is recurrent if and only if
\[
\sum_{n=1}^\infty p_{ii}^{(n)}=+\infty.
\]

So recurrence can be detected by looking at the total mass of the return probabilities.

\subsection{A detour: the Borel--Cantelli lemma}

The lecture briefly recalls a general probabilistic fact.

\begin{lemma}[Borel--Cantelli]
Let \((E_n)_{n\ge 1}\) be a sequence of events. If
\[
\sum_{n=1}^\infty \mathbb P(E_n)<\infty,
\]
then only finitely many of the events \(E_n\) occur, almost surely.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}[Idea]
We have
\[
\sum_{n=1}^\infty \mathbb P(E_n)
=
\mathbb E\!\left[\sum_{n=1}^\infty \mathbf 1_{E_n}\right].
\]
But \(\sum_{n=1}^\infty \mathbf 1_{E_n}\) is exactly the number of events among \((E_n)\) that occur. So if the expectation is finite, this random variable cannot be \(+\infty\) with positive probability. Hence only finitely many \(E_n\) occur almost surely.
\end{proof}

A natural choice in the Markov-chain setting is
\[
E_n=\{X_n=i\}.
\]
Then
\[
\sum_{n=1}^\infty \mathbb P_i(E_n)
=
\sum_{n=1}^\infty p_{ii}^{(n)}.
\]

So if \(\sum_{n\ge 1} p_{ii}^{(n)}<\infty\), then the chain visits \(i\) only finitely many times almost surely.

However, the backward implication is \emph{not} true in general for arbitrary events: ``only finitely many occurrences a.s.'' does not by itself imply \(\sum_n \mathbb P(E_n)<\infty\).

The important point is that for Markov chains, the number of returns in the transient case has a geometric structure, so one does recover the backward implication there.

\subsection{Simple random walk in one dimension}

For one-dimensional simple random walk, the return probability satisfies
\[
p_{00}^{(n)}\sim \frac{1}{\sqrt n}.
\]
Hence
\[
\sum_{n=1}^\infty p_{00}^{(n)}=+\infty.
\]
Therefore the origin is recurrent, and by irreducibility all states are recurrent.

\subsection{A higher-dimensional walk built from independent coordinates}

The lecture then considers a \(d\)-dimensional walk
\[
X_n=(X_n^{(1)},X_n^{(2)},\dots,X_n^{(d)}),
\]
where each coordinate is an independent one-dimensional simple random walk.

Equivalently, from \(i=(i_1,\dots,i_d)\) the chain moves to
\[
j=(j_1,\dots,j_d)
\]
with probability
\[
p_{ij}
=
\begin{cases}
2^{-d}, & \text{if } |i_k-j_k|=1 \text{ for every } k=1,\dots,d,\\[0.4em]
0, & \text{otherwise.}
\end{cases}
\]

So every coordinate moves by \(\pm 1\) at each step, independently of the others.

Since the coordinates are independent,
\[
p_{00}^{(n)}
=
\prod_{r=1}^d \mathbb P(X_n^{(r)}=0)
=
\left(2^{-n}\binom{n}{n/2}\right)^d
\sim n^{-d/2}.
\]

Therefore
\[
\sum_{n=1}^\infty p_{00}^{(n)}
\begin{cases}
=+\infty, & d=1,2,\\[0.3em]
<\infty, & d\ge 3.
\end{cases}
\]

So this walk is:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item recurrent in dimensions \(1\) and \(2\),
    \item transient in dimensions \(d\ge 3\).
\end{itemize}

\begin{keyformula}
For the product-type \(d\)-dimensional walk,
\[
p_{00}^{(n)}\sim n^{-d/2}.
\]
Hence recurrence occurs for \(d=1,2\), while transience occurs for \(d\ge 3\).
\end{keyformula}

This is the origin of the slogan:

\begin{quote}
A drunk man gets home, while a drunk bird may not.
\end{quote}

\subsection{Hitting probabilities}

We now introduce one of the main objects of Lecture 2.

\begin{definition}[Hitting probability]
For states \(i,j\in S\), define
\[
f_{ij}=\mathbb P_i(\text{ever visit } j).
\]
Equivalently, \(f_{ij}\) is the probability that starting from \(i\), the chain hits \(j\) at least once at a positive time.
\end{definition}

In particular, \(f_{ii}\) is the return probability to \(i\).

\subsection{A small example: computing some \texorpdfstring{$f_{ij}$}{fij}}

The lecture gives a small finite-state example to show how to compute \(f_{ij}\) directly.

\begin{center}
\begin{tikzpicture}[->, >=stealth, shorten >=1pt, auto, thick]

    % Nodes in square shape
    \node[circle, draw, minimum size=1cm] (1) at (0,2) {\(1\)};
    \node[circle, draw, minimum size=1cm] (2) at (2,2) {\(2\)};
    \node[circle, draw, minimum size=1cm] (3) at (0,0) {\(3\)};
    \node[circle, draw, minimum size=1cm] (4) at (2,0) {\(4\)};

    % State 1 absorbing
    \path (1) edge[loop above] node {\(1\)} (1);

    % From state 2
    \path (2) edge node[above] {\(\frac14\)} (1);
    \path (2) edge[loop above] node {\(\frac14\)} (2);
    \path (2) edge[bend left=15] node[right] {\(\frac12\)} (3);

    % From state 3
    \path (3) edge[loop below] node {\(\frac25\)} (3);
    \path (3) edge[bend left=15] node[above] {\(\frac35\)} (4);

    % From state 4
    \path (4) edge[bend left=15] node[above] {\(\frac13\)} (3);
    \path (4) edge[loop right] node {\(\frac23\)} (4);

\end{tikzpicture}
\end{center}

From the diagram:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item state \(1\) is absorbing;
    \item from state \(2\), the chain goes to \(1\) with probability \(1/4\), stays at \(2\) with probability \(1/4\), and goes to \(3\) with probability \(1/2\);
    \item from state \(3\), it stays at \(3\) with probability \(2/5\) and goes to \(4\) with probability \(3/5\);
    \item from state \(4\), it goes to \(3\) with probability \(1/3\) and stays at \(4\) with probability \(2/3\).
\end{itemize}

From this:
\[
f_{11}=1,
\qquad
f_{1j}=0 \quad (j=2,3,4),
\]
because once the chain is at \(1\), it never leaves.

Also,
\[
f_{22}=\frac14,
\]
since after starting from \(2\), the only way to return to \(2\) is to use the self-loop immediately.

Next,
\[
f_{21}
=
\frac14+\frac14\cdot\frac14+\left(\frac14\right)^2\frac14+\cdots
=
\frac{\frac14}{1-\frac14}
=
\frac13.
\]

Similarly,
\[
f_{23}
=
\frac12+\frac14\cdot\frac12+\left(\frac14\right)^2\frac12+\cdots
=
\frac{\frac12}{1-\frac14}
=
\frac23.
\]

This illustrates the general idea that hitting probabilities can often be found either by:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item direct first-step analysis, or
    \item solving a linear system.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{First-step expansion for \texorpdfstring{$f_{ij}$}{fij}}

Condition on the first step \(X_1\). Then
\[
f_{ij}
=
\sum_{k\in S} \mathbb P_i(X_1=k)\,\mathbb P_k(\text{ever visit } j).
\]
But this expression must be handled carefully when \(k=j\). If \(X_1=j\), the event ``ever visit \(j\)'' has already happened, so the contribution is simply \(p_{ij}\), not \(p_{ij}f_{jj}\).

Therefore the correct first-step expansion is
\[
f_{ij}
=
p_{ij}
+
\sum_{k\in S,\;k\neq j} p_{ik}f_{kj}.
\]

\begin{keyformula}
The hitting probabilities satisfy the first-step equations
\[
f_{ij}
=
p_{ij}
+
\sum_{k\in S,\;k\neq j} p_{ik}f_{kj}.
\]
So in principle one gets \(|S|^2\) linear equations for the \(|S|^2\) unknowns \(f_{ij}\).
\end{keyformula}

\subsection{Example: gambler's ruin}

Consider the classical gambler's ruin chain.

A gambler starts with initial wealth
\[
X_0=a,
\qquad a\in \mathbb N.
\]
At each round:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item the gambler wins \$1 with probability \(1/2\),
    \item the gambler loses \$1 with probability \(1/2\).
\end{itemize}
The game stops when the wealth reaches either \(0\) or \(c\), where \(c>a\).

So the state space is
\[
S=\{0,1,2,\dots,c\},
\]
with \(0\) and \(c\) absorbing.

We are interested in
\[
\mathbb P_a(\text{ever visit } c)=f_{ac}.
\]

Since \(0\) and \(c\) are absorbing,
\[
f_{00}=1,
\qquad
f_{cc}=1.
\]
For \(i\in\{1,2,\dots,c-1\}\), the state \(i\) is transient in this finite stopped chain, so \(f_{ii}<1\).

\subsection{Gambler's ruin when \texorpdfstring{$p=1/2$}{p=1/2}}

For \(1\le i\le c-1\), the first-step expansion gives
\[
f_{ic}
=
\frac12 f_{(i+1)c}+\frac12 f_{(i-1)c}.
\]
Equivalently,
\[
f_{(i+1)c}-f_{ic}
=
f_{ic}-f_{(i-1)c}.
\]
So the differences are constant:
\[
f_{ic}-f_{(i-1)c}=\text{constant}.
\]

Now telescope:
\[
1
=
f_{cc}-f_{0c}
=
\sum_{i=1}^c \bigl(f_{ic}-f_{(i-1)c}\bigr)
=
c\bigl(f_{1c}-f_{0c}\bigr).
\]
Hence
\[
f_{ic}-f_{(i-1)c}=\frac1c.
\]
Therefore
\[
f_{ac}
=
a\cdot \frac1c
=
\frac{a}{c}.
\]

\begin{theorem}[Gambler's ruin, fair case]
If the gambler wins and loses each with probability \(1/2\), then
\[
\mathbb P_a(\text{hit } c \text{ before } 0)=\frac{a}{c}.
\]
\end{theorem}

\subsection{Gambler's ruin when \texorpdfstring{$p\neq 1/2$}{p ≠ 1/2}}

Now suppose
\[
p_{i,i+1}=p,
\qquad
p_{i,i-1}=1-p,
\qquad
1\le i\le c-1,
\]
with \(p\neq 1/2\).

Then
\[
f_{ic}
=
p\,f_{(i+1)c}+(1-p)f_{(i-1)c}.
\]
Rearranging,
\[
f_{(i+1)c}-f_{ic}
=
\frac{1-p}{p}\bigl(f_{ic}-f_{(i-1)c}\bigr).
\]
So the increments form a geometric sequence:
\[
f_{(i+1)c}-f_{ic}
=
\left(\frac{1-p}{p}\right)^i (f_{1c}-f_{0c}).
\]

Summing from \(i=0\) to \(c-1\),
\[
1
=
f_{cc}-f_{0c}
=
\sum_{i=0}^{c-1} (f_{(i+1)c}-f_{ic})
=
(f_{1c}-f_{0c})\sum_{i=0}^{c-1}\left(\frac{1-p}{p}\right)^i.
\]
This gives
\[
f_{ac}
=
\frac{\left(\frac{1-p}{p}\right)^a-1}{\left(\frac{1-p}{p}\right)^c-1}.
\]

\begin{theorem}[Gambler's ruin, biased case]
If \(p\neq 1/2\), then
\[
\mathbb P_a(\text{hit } c \text{ before } 0)
=
\frac{\left(\frac{1-p}{p}\right)^a-1}
{\left(\frac{1-p}{p}\right)^c-1}.
\]
\end{theorem}

\subsection{Communication and irreducibility}

\begin{definition}[Communication]
We say that \(i\) \emph{communicates with} \(j\), written
\[
i\to j,
\]
if
\[
f_{ij}>0.
\]
If both \(i\to j\) and \(j\to i\), we write
\[
i\leftrightarrow j.
\]
\end{definition}

\begin{definition}[Irreducible Markov chain]
A Markov chain is called \emph{irreducible} if for every \(i,j\in S\),
\[
i\leftrightarrow j.
\]
\end{definition}

Examples:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item one-dimensional simple random walk is irreducible;
    \item the product-type higher-dimensional walk above is not necessarily irreducible, because parity-type obstructions may appear;
    \item if instead one chooses a random coordinate and moves only that coordinate by \(\pm 1\) at each step, then the resulting walk on \(\mathbb Z^d\) is irreducible;
    \item gambler's ruin is reducible because the absorbing states \(0\) and \(c\) cannot reach the interior states.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Recurrence is a class property}

A key fact is that recurrence is shared across communicating states.

\begin{proposition}[Simultaneous recurrence]
If
\[
i\leftrightarrow j
\]
and \(i\) is recurrent, then \(j\) is also recurrent.
\end{proposition}

So within one communicating class, either every state is recurrent or every state is transient.

\begin{corollary}[Case theorem]
If a Markov chain is irreducible, then exactly one of the following holds:
\begin{enumerate}[label=(\roman*)]
    \item all states are recurrent;
    \item all states are transient.
\end{enumerate}
\end{corollary}

Thus for an irreducible chain it makes sense to speak of a \emph{recurrent chain} or a \emph{transient chain}.

\subsection{The sum lemma}

The proof of simultaneous recurrence is based on the following comparison lemma.

\begin{lemma}[Sum lemma]
Suppose
\[
i\to k
\qquad\text{and}\qquad
\ell\to j.
\]
If
\[
\sum_{n=1}^\infty p_{k\ell}^{(n)}=+\infty,
\]
then
\[
\sum_{n=1}^\infty p_{ij}^{(n)}=+\infty.
\]
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
Since \(i\to k\), there exists \(m>0\) such that
\[
p_{ik}^{(m)}>0.
\]
Similarly, since \(\ell\to j\), there exists \(r>0\) such that
\[
p_{\ell j}^{(r)}>0.
\]

For \(n>m+r\), the Chapman--Kolmogorov inequality gives
\[
p_{ij}^{(n)}
\ge
p_{ik}^{(m)}\,p_{k\ell}^{(n-m-r)}\,p_{\ell j}^{(r)}.
\]
Therefore
\[
\sum_{n=1}^\infty p_{ij}^{(n)}
\ge
p_{ik}^{(m)}p_{\ell j}^{(r)}
\sum_{t=1}^\infty p_{k\ell}^{(t)}.
\]
The right-hand side is \(+\infty\), so
\[
\sum_{n=1}^\infty p_{ij}^{(n)}=+\infty.
\]
\end{proof}

\subsection{Proof that recurrence is shared inside a communicating class}

Take \(i\leftrightarrow k\). If \(k\) is recurrent, then
\[
\sum_{n=1}^\infty p_{kk}^{(n)}=+\infty.
\]
Apply the sum lemma with
\[
k=\ell,
\qquad
j=i.
\]
Since \(i\to k\) and \(k\to i\), we get
\[
\sum_{n=1}^\infty p_{ii}^{(n)}=+\infty.
\]
Hence \(i\) is recurrent.

So communicating states are recurrent or transient together.

\subsection[What about the sum of n-step transition probabilities?]{What about \texorpdfstring{$\sum_n p_{ij}^{(n)}$}{the sum of n-step transition probabilities?}}

For an irreducible chain, not only \(\sum_n p_{ii}^{(n)}\) but also the mixed sums \(\sum_n p_{ij}^{(n)}\) have a clean dichotomy.

\begin{proposition}
Suppose the chain is irreducible.
\begin{enumerate}[label=(\roman*)]
    \item If the chain is recurrent, then for all \(i,j\in S\),
    \[
    \sum_{n=1}^\infty p_{ij}^{(n)}=+\infty.
    \]
    \item If the chain is transient, then for all \(i,j\in S\),
    \[
    \sum_{n=1}^\infty p_{ij}^{(n)}<\infty.
    \]
\end{enumerate}
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
First observe that
\[
\sum_{n=1}^\infty p_{ij}^{(n)}
=
\mathbb E_i\!\bigl[\#\text{ visits to } j\bigr].
\]

If the chain is recurrent and irreducible, then \(j\) is recurrent and \(i\to j\). Choose \(m\) such that \(p_{ij}^{(m)}>0\). Then
\[
\mathbb E_i[\#\text{ visits to } j]
\ge
p_{ij}^{(m)}\,\mathbb E_j[\#\text{ returns to } j]
=
+\infty.
\]

If the chain is transient, then once the chain hits \(j\), the number of future returns to \(j\) has geometric behavior with parameter \(1-f_{jj}>0\). Hence
\[
\mathbb E_i[\#\text{ visits to } j]
=
\frac{f_{ij}}{1-f_{jj}}
<\infty.
\]
Therefore
\[
\sum_{n=1}^\infty p_{ij}^{(n)}<\infty.
\]
\end{proof}

\begin{keyformula}
For an irreducible chain:
\[
\text{recurrent}
\iff
\sum_{n=1}^\infty p_{ij}^{(n)}=+\infty \quad (\forall i,j\in S),
\]
while
\[
\text{transient}
\iff
\sum_{n=1}^\infty p_{ij}^{(n)}<\infty \quad (\forall i,j\in S).
\]
\end{keyformula}

\subsection{Finite irreducible chains are recurrent}

A very important special case is the finite-state case.

\begin{theorem}
If the chain is irreducible and \(|S|<\infty\), then it is recurrent.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
Fix \(i\in S\). Then
\[
\sum_{j\in S}\sum_{n=1}^\infty p_{ij}^{(n)}
=
\sum_{n=1}^\infty \sum_{j\in S} p_{ij}^{(n)}
=
\sum_{n=1}^\infty 1
=
+\infty.
\]
Since \(S\) is finite, at least one state \(j\in S\) must satisfy
\[
\sum_{n=1}^\infty p_{ij}^{(n)}=+\infty.
\]
By the previous proposition, this forces the irreducible chain to be recurrent.
\end{proof}

\subsection{Goal: a criterion in terms of \texorpdfstring{$f_{ij}$}{fij}}

We now want a necessary and sufficient condition for an irreducible chain to be recurrent, expressed directly through the hitting probabilities \(f_{ij}\).

The key statement is the following.

\begin{lemma}[\(f\)-lemma]
If
\[
j\to i
\qquad\text{and}\qquad
f_{jj}=1,
\]
then
\[
f_{ij}=1.
\]
\end{lemma}

So if \(j\) is recurrent and \(i\) can be reached from \(j\), then starting from \(i\) one must eventually hit \(j\) with probability \(1\).

\subsection{A technical tool: the hit lemma}

\begin{lemma}[Hit lemma]
Let \(H_{ij}\) be the event that starting from \(j\), the chain hits \(i\) before returning to \(j\). If
\[
j\to i,
\]
then
\[
\mathbb P_j(H_{ij})>0.
\]
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}[Idea]
If \(j\to i\), then there exists a finite path
\[
x_0=j,\;x_1,\;\dots,\;x_m=i
\]
with
\[
p_{x_0x_1}p_{x_1x_2}\cdots p_{x_{m-1}x_m}>0.
\]
This path reaches \(i\) before coming back to \(j\), so the event \(H_{ij}\) has positive probability.
\end{proof}

\subsection{Proof of the \texorpdfstring{$f$}{f}-lemma}

\begin{proof}
Since \(j\to i\), the hit lemma gives
\[
\mathbb P_j(H_{ij})>0.
\]

Because \(j\) is recurrent,
\[
\mathbb P_j(\text{never return to } j)=0.
\]

Now consider the event:
\begin{quote}
hit \(i\) before returning to \(j\), and then starting from \(i\), never visit \(j\).
\end{quote}
By the strong Markov property, this event has probability
\[
\mathbb P_j(H_{ij})\cdot \mathbb P_i(\text{never visit } j).
\]
But this event is contained in the event ``never return to \(j\),''
so
\[
0
=
\mathbb P_j(\text{never return to } j)
\ge
\mathbb P_j(H_{ij})\cdot \mathbb P_i(\text{never visit } j).
\]
Since \(\mathbb P_j(H_{ij})>0\), it follows that
\[
\mathbb P_i(\text{never visit } j)=0.
\]
Therefore
\[
f_{ij}=1.
\]
\end{proof}

\subsection{Infinite returns lemma}

Define
\[
N(j)=\#\{\text{visits to } j\}.
\]

For irreducible chains, recurrence and transience can be characterized by whether every state is visited infinitely often or only finitely often.

\begin{lemma}[Infinite returns lemma]
Suppose the chain is irreducible.
\begin{enumerate}[label=(\roman*)]
    \item If the chain is recurrent, then for all \(i,j\in S\),
    \[
    \mathbb P_i(N(j)=+\infty)=1.
    \]
    \item If the chain is transient, then for all \(i,j\in S\),
    \[
    \mathbb P_i(N(j)=+\infty)=0.
    \]
\end{enumerate}
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
If the chain is recurrent, then \(f_{jj}=1\). Since the chain is irreducible, \(j\to i\), so by the \(f\)-lemma,
\[
f_{ij}=1.
\]
For any \(k\in\mathbb N\),
\[
\mathbb P_i(N(j)\ge k)
=
f_{ij}\,f_{jj}^{\,k-1}
=
1.
\]
Hence
\[
\mathbb P_i(N(j)=+\infty)=1.
\]

If the chain is transient, then
\[
\mathbb E_i[N(j)]
=
\frac{f_{ij}}{1-f_{jj}}
<\infty.
\]
Therefore \(N(j)<\infty\) almost surely, so
\[
\mathbb P_i(N(j)=+\infty)=0.
\]
\end{proof}

\subsection{Recurrence equivalence theorem}

We can now collect the main equivalent formulations of recurrence for irreducible chains.

\begin{theorem}[Recurrence equivalence theorem]
Suppose the Markov chain is irreducible. Then the following are equivalent:
\begin{enumerate}[label=(\roman*)]
    \item there exist \(k,\ell\in S\) such that
    \[
    \sum_{n=1}^\infty p_{k\ell}^{(n)}=+\infty;
    \]
    \item for all \(k,\ell\in S\),
    \[
    \sum_{n=1}^\infty p_{k\ell}^{(n)}=+\infty;
    \]
    \item there exists \(k\in S\) such that
    \[
    f_{kk}=1;
    \]
    \item for all \(k\in S\),
    \[
    f_{kk}=1;
    \]
    \item for all \(i,j\in S\),
    \[
    f_{ij}=1;
    \]
    \item there exist \(k,\ell\in S\) such that
    \[
    \mathbb P_k(N(\ell)=+\infty)=1;
    \]
    \item for all \(k,\ell\in S\),
    \[
    \mathbb P_k(N(\ell)=+\infty)=1.
    \]
\end{enumerate}
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}[Why these are equivalent]
The implications are assembled from the previous results:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item (i) \(\Rightarrow\) (ii): by the sum lemma and irreducibility;
    \item (ii) \(\Rightarrow\) (iii): take \(k=\ell\);
    \item (iii) \(\Rightarrow\) (iv): by simultaneous recurrence;
    \item (iv) \(\Rightarrow\) (v): by the \(f\)-lemma;
    \item (v) \(\Rightarrow\) (iv): trivial by setting \(i=j\);
    \item (v) \(\Rightarrow\) (vii): by the infinite returns lemma;
    \item (vi) \(\Rightarrow\) (vii): by irreducibility and the infinite returns lemma;
    \item (vii) \(\Rightarrow\) (vi): trivial.
\end{itemize}
Hence all seven statements are equivalent.
\end{proof}

\begin{keyformula}
For an irreducible Markov chain, the following all mean the same thing:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item some/all return-probability sums are infinite;
    \item some/all states have return probability \(1\);
    \item all hitting probabilities satisfy \(f_{ij}=1\);
    \item every state is visited infinitely often almost surely.
\end{itemize}
These are all equivalent formulations of recurrence.
\end{keyformula}

\subsection{Important warning: the existential version of \texorpdfstring{$f_{ij}=1$}{fij = 1} is not enough}

The lecture ends with an important counterexample.

Consider the random walk on \(\mathbb Z\) defined by
\[
X_{n+1}=X_n+\varepsilon_{n+1},
\]
where
\[
\varepsilon_{n+1}
=
\begin{cases}
1, & \text{with probability } 2/3,\\
-1, & \text{with probability } 1/3.
\end{cases}
\]

This is a biased random walk with positive drift. It is transient.

However,
\[
f_{01}=1.
\]
Indeed, starting from \(0\), the walk hits \(1\) with probability \(1\), even though it does not keep returning indefinitely.

So the statement
\[
\exists\, i,j\in S \text{ such that } f_{ij}=1
\]
does \emph{not} imply recurrence.

What is needed is the much stronger condition
\[
f_{ij}=1 \qquad \text{for all } i,j\in S,
\]
which, in the irreducible setting, \emph{is} equivalent to recurrence.

\subsection{Summary}

\begin{summarybox}
Lecture 2 develops the theory of recurrence further by introducing hitting probabilities \(f_{ij}\), communication, irreducibility, and the class-property nature of recurrence/transience.

The main points are:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item recurrence is equivalent to
    \[
    \sum_{n=1}^\infty p_{ii}^{(n)}=+\infty;
    \]
    \item hitting probabilities satisfy the first-step equations
    \[
    f_{ij}=p_{ij}+\sum_{k\neq j} p_{ik}f_{kj};
    \]
    \item gambler's ruin can be solved neatly using these equations;
    \item in an irreducible chain, either all states are recurrent or all are transient;
    \item finite irreducible chains are automatically recurrent;
    \item for irreducible chains, recurrence is equivalent to \(f_{ij}=1\) for all \(i,j\), and also equivalent to visiting every state infinitely often almost surely.
\end{itemize}
\end{summarybox}

\clearpage

\section{Lecture 3}

\subsection{Recall: recurrence and transience in an irreducible chain}

Let \(P\) be an irreducible Markov chain on a finite or countable state space \(S\).

Recall the standard notation:
\[
f_{ij}=\mathbb P_i(\tau_j<\infty),
\]
where
\[
\tau_j=\inf\{n\ge 1:X_n=j\}
\]
is the first hitting/return time of \(j\) after time \(0\).

We also write
\[
N(j)=\sum_{n\ge 0}\mathbf 1_{\{X_n=j\}}
\]
for the total number of visits to state \(j\).

As before:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item \(j\) is called \emph{recurrent} if
    \[
    f_{jj}=1;
    \]
    \item \(j\) is called \emph{transient} if
    \[
    f_{jj}<1.
    \]
\end{itemize}

Because the chain is irreducible, recurrence and transience are class properties. So either all states are recurrent, or all states are transient.

\subsection{Equivalent criteria for recurrence}

The first part of the lecture collects several equivalent ways to recognize recurrence.

\begin{theorem}[Recurrence equivalence theorem]
Let \(P\) be irreducible. Then the following are equivalent:
\begin{enumerate}[label=\arabic*.]
    \item the chain is recurrent;
    \item for some, equivalently every, \(i\in S\),
    \[
    f_{ii}=1;
    \]
    \item for some, equivalently every, \(i,j\in S\),
    \[
    \mathbb P_i\bigl(N(j)=\infty\bigr)=1;
    \]
    \item for some, equivalently every, \(i,j\in S\),
    \[
    \sum_{n=1}^{\infty} p_{ij}^{(n)}=\infty;
    \]
    \item for every \(i,j\in S\),
    \[
    f_{ij}=1.
    \]
\end{enumerate}
\end{theorem}

So for an irreducible chain, recurrence means much more than just ``eventually returning to the starting state.'' It means every state is hit with probability \(1\), and every state is visited infinitely often almost surely.

\begin{theorem}[Transience equivalence theorem]
Let \(P\) be irreducible. Then the following are equivalent:
\begin{enumerate}[label=\arabic*.]
    \item the chain is transient;
    \item for some, equivalently every, \(i\in S\),
    \[
    f_{ii}<1;
    \]
    \item for some, equivalently every, \(i,j\in S\),
    \[
    \mathbb P_i\bigl(N(j)=\infty\bigr)=0;
    \]
    \item for some, equivalently every, \(i,j\in S\),
    \[
    \sum_{n=1}^{\infty} p_{ij}^{(n)}<\infty;
    \]
    \item there exist \(i,j\in S\) such that
    \[
    f_{ij}<1.
    \]
\end{enumerate}
\end{theorem}

A useful way to think about the transient case is that returns eventually stop. In particular, once a state has a strictly positive probability of never being hit again, repeated attempts force the total number of visits to be finite almost surely.

\begin{keyformula}
For an irreducible chain,
\[
\text{recurrence}
\quad\Longleftrightarrow\quad
\mathbb P_i\bigl(N(j)=\infty\bigr)=1
\quad\Longleftrightarrow\quad
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} p_{ij}^{(n)}=\infty,
\]
for some/every \(i,j\in S\).

Likewise,
\[
\text{transience}
\quad\Longleftrightarrow\quad
\mathbb P_i\bigl(N(j)=\infty\bigr)=0
\quad\Longleftrightarrow\quad
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} p_{ij}^{(n)}<\infty.
\]

However,
\[
\exists\, i,j \text{ such that } f_{ij}=1
\]
is \emph{not} by itself an equivalent criterion for recurrence.
\end{keyformula}

\subsection{A counterexample: irreducible and transient, but \texorpdfstring{$f_{ij}=1$}{fij = 1} for some pair}

The notes explicitly warn that the condition
\[
\exists\, i,j \text{ such that } f_{ij}=1
\]
is not enough.

\begin{proposition}
There exists an irreducible Markov chain which is transient, but for some pair \(i,j\) we still have \(f_{ij}=1\).
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
Consider the nearest-neighbor random walk on \(\mathbb Z\):
\[
X_0=0,
\qquad
X_{n+1}=X_n+\varepsilon_{n+1},
\]
where
\[
\varepsilon_{n+1}=
\begin{cases}
+1, & \text{with probability } p,\\[0.3em]
-1, & \text{with probability } 1-p,
\end{cases}
\qquad p>\frac12.
\]

This chain is irreducible, because by successive \(\pm 1\) moves one can go from any integer to any other integer.

To test recurrence, look at the return probabilities to \(0\). For odd times,
\[
p_{00}^{(n)}=0.
\]
For even times \(n=2m\),
\[
p_{00}^{(2m)}
=
\binom{2m}{m}p^m(1-p)^m.
\]
Using the central-binomial asymptotic,
\[
\binom{2m}{m}\sim \frac{4^m}{\sqrt{\pi m}},
\]
we get
\[
p_{00}^{(2m)}
\sim
\frac{(4p(1-p))^m}{\sqrt{\pi m}}.
\]
Since \(p>\frac12\), we have \(4p(1-p)<1\), so
\[
\sum_{m=0}^{\infty} p_{00}^{(2m)}<\infty.
\]
Therefore the chain is transient.

On the other hand, by the law of large numbers,
\[
\frac{X_n}{n}
=
\frac1n\sum_{k=1}^n \varepsilon_k
\longrightarrow
\mathbb E[\varepsilon_1]
=
2p-1
>
0
\qquad \text{a.s.}
\]
Hence
\[
X_n\to +\infty
\qquad \text{a.s.}
\]
Starting from \(0\), any path that drifts to \(+\infty\) must hit \(1\), so
\[
f_{01}=1.
\]
Thus the chain is transient, irreducible, and yet \(f_{01}=1\).
\end{proof}

\begin{remark}
So the correct irreducible recurrence criterion is
\[
f_{ij}=1 \text{ for all } i,j,
\]
not merely for one special pair.
\end{remark}

\subsection{Reducible Markov chains on a finite state space}

The lecture then turns to the reducible case.

If the state space is finite and the chain is reducible, we may reorder the states so that the recurrent classes come first and the transient states come last. Then \(P\) can be written in block form as
\[
P=
\begin{pmatrix}
\widetilde P & 0\\
S & Q
\end{pmatrix},
\]
where:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item \(\widetilde P\) contains the recurrent classes;
    \item \(Q\) is the transient block;
    \item \(S\) describes transitions from transient states into recurrent classes.
\end{itemize}

More precisely, \(\widetilde P\) can be further decomposed as a block diagonal matrix
\[
\widetilde P=
\begin{pmatrix}
P_1 & 0 & \cdots & 0\\
0 & P_2 & \cdots & 0\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
0 & 0 & \cdots & P_r
\end{pmatrix},
\]
where each \(P_k\) is an irreducible recurrent class.

A useful fact is:

\begin{proposition}
If \(i\) is transient and \(j\) is recurrent, then \(j\nrightarrow i\).
\end{proposition}

Intuitively, once the chain enters a recurrent class, it cannot later escape into a transient part.

Raising the block matrix to the \(n\)-th power gives
\[
P^n=
\begin{pmatrix}
\widetilde P^{\,n} & 0\\
S_n & Q^n
\end{pmatrix}.
\]
Because the states in the \(Q\)-block are transient, one has
\[
Q^n\to 0
\qquad \text{as } n\to\infty.
\]

So eventually the mass in the transient block disappears, and the chain ends up in one of the recurrent classes. In concrete examples, the entries of \(S_n\) can be used to compute the probability that a transient starting point eventually lands in a given recurrent class.

\subsection{The main long-run question}

The lecture next asks the natural convergence question:
\[
\lim_{n\to\infty}\mathbb P_i(X_n=j)
=
\lim_{n\to\infty} p_{ij}^{(n)}.
\]

Suppose for a moment that for each fixed \(j\),
\[
p_{ij}^{(n)}\longrightarrow q_j.
\]
Then also
\[
p_{ij}^{(n+1)}\longrightarrow q_j.
\]
But by Chapman--Kolmogorov,
\[
p_{ij}^{(n+1)}
=
\sum_{k\in S} p_{ik}^{(n)}p_{kj}.
\]
Passing formally to the limit suggests
\[
q_j
=
\sum_{k\in S} q_k p_{kj}.
\]
In vector form,
\[
q=qP.
\]

So any candidate limit must be stationary.

\subsection{Stationary distributions and stationary measures}

\begin{definition}[Stationary distribution]
A probability distribution \(\pi=(\pi_i)_{i\in S}\) is called \emph{stationary} for \(P\) if
\[
\pi=\pi P,
\qquad
\sum_{i\in S}\pi_i=1.
\]
\end{definition}

Here \(\pi\) is viewed as a row vector.

The notes also point out that in infinite state spaces one may have a nonnegative solution of
\[
\pi=\pi P
\]
with
\[
\sum_{i\in S}\pi_i=+\infty.
\]
Such an object is called a \emph{stationary measure}, but not a stationary distribution.

\subsection{Example: the frog walk on \texorpdfstring{$20$}{20} states}

Recall the frog walk on the circle with \(20\) states. From each state \(i\),
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item the chain moves to \(i-1 \pmod{20}\) with probability \(1/3\),
    \item stays at \(i\) with probability \(1/3\),
    \item moves to \(i+1 \pmod{20}\) with probability \(1/3\).
\end{itemize}

Guess the uniform distribution:
\[
\pi=
\left[\frac1{20},\frac1{20},\dots,\frac1{20}\right].
\]
For each state \(i\), there are exactly three states that can jump into \(i\), and each contributes probability \(1/3\). Hence
\[
\sum_{j\in S} \pi_j p_{ji}
=
\frac1{20}\cdot \frac13 \cdot 3
=
\frac1{20}
=
\pi_i.
\]
So the uniform distribution is stationary.

\subsection{Doubly stochastic matrices}

\begin{definition}[Doubly stochastic]
A transition matrix \(P\) on a finite state space is called \emph{doubly stochastic} if, in addition to
\[
\sum_{j\in S} p_{ij}=1
\qquad (\forall i\in S),
\]
we also have
\[
\sum_{i\in S} p_{ij}=1
\qquad (\forall j\in S).
\]
\end{definition}

The first condition says each row is a probability distribution. The second says each column also sums to \(1\).

\begin{proposition}
If \(P\) is doubly stochastic on a finite state space \(S\), then the uniform distribution
\[
\pi=
\left[\frac1{|S|},\frac1{|S|},\dots,\frac1{|S|}\right]
\]
is stationary.
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
For each \(i\in S\),
\[
\sum_{j\in S}\pi_j p_{ji}
=
\sum_{j\in S}\frac1{|S|}p_{ji}
=
\frac1{|S|}\sum_{j\in S}p_{ji}
=
\frac1{|S|}
=
\pi_i.
\]
\end{proof}

In fact, on a finite state space the converse is also true: the uniform distribution is stationary if and only if the matrix is doubly stochastic.

\subsection{Reversibility and detailed balance}

A very useful sufficient condition for stationarity is the detailed balance identity.

\begin{definition}[Reversibility / detailed balance]
Let \(\pi\) be a probability distribution on \(S\). We say that \(P\) is \emph{reversible with respect to \(\pi\)} if
\[
\pi_i p_{ij}=\pi_j p_{ji}
\qquad \text{for all } i,j\in S.
\]
\end{definition}

\begin{proposition}
If \(P\) is reversible with respect to \(\pi\), then \(\pi\) is a stationary distribution for \(P\).
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
Fix \(j\in S\). Then
\[
\sum_{i\in S}\pi_i p_{ij}
=
\sum_{i\in S}\pi_j p_{ji}
=
\pi_j \sum_{i\in S}p_{ji}.
\]
A cleaner way to write the same computation is to use detailed balance term by term:
\[
\sum_{i\in S}\pi_i p_{ij}
=
\sum_{i\in S}\pi_j p_{ji}
=
\pi_j \sum_{i\in S} p_{ji}
=
\pi_j.
\]
Thus \(\pi=\pi P\).
\end{proof}

\begin{keyformula}
Detailed balance
\[
\pi_i p_{ij}=\pi_j p_{ji}
\qquad (\forall i,j)
\]
implies stationarity:
\[
\pi=\pi P.
\]
So reversibility is a powerful way to \emph{guess and verify} a stationary distribution.
\end{keyformula}

\subsection{Example: the Ehrenfest urn}

The lecture gives the Ehrenfest urn as a standard reversible example.

Suppose there are \(d\) balls split between two boxes. At each step:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item choose one of the \(d\) balls uniformly at random;
    \item move it to the opposite box.
\end{itemize}

Let
\[
X_n=\text{number of balls in Box 1 after the \(n\)-th step}.
\]
Then the state space is \(\{0,1,\dots,d\}\), and from state \(i\),
\[
p_{i,i+1}=\frac{d-i}{d},
\qquad
p_{i,i-1}=\frac{i}{d}.
\]

The natural candidate stationary distribution is binomial:
\[
\pi_i=\binom{d}{i}2^{-d},
\qquad i=0,1,\dots,d.
\]

To check detailed balance, compute
\[
\pi_i p_{i,i+1}
=
2^{-d}\binom{d}{i}\frac{d-i}{d}
=
2^{-d}\frac{d!}{i!(d-i)!}\cdot \frac{d-i}{d}
=
2^{-d}\frac{(d-1)!}{i!(d-i-1)!}.
\]
On the other hand,
\[
\pi_{i+1}p_{i+1,i}
=
2^{-d}\binom{d}{i+1}\frac{i+1}{d}
=
2^{-d}\frac{d!}{(i+1)!(d-i-1)!}\cdot \frac{i+1}{d}
=
2^{-d}\frac{(d-1)!}{i!(d-i-1)!}.
\]
So
\[
\pi_i p_{i,i+1}=\pi_{i+1}p_{i+1,i},
\]
which is exactly detailed balance for neighboring states. Hence \(P\) is reversible with respect to \(\pi\), and therefore \(\pi\) is stationary.

\begin{remark}
The notes mention that one can also solve \(\pi=\pi P\) directly, but detailed balance is usually the cleaner method when it is available.
\end{remark}

\subsection{Stationary does not imply reversible}

The converse is false: a chain may have a stationary distribution without being reversible.

\begin{proposition}
There exists a Markov chain with stationary distribution \(\pi\) such that \(P\) is not reversible with respect to \(\pi\).
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
Consider the \(3\)-state chain \(\{1,2,3\}\) with clockwise transition probability \(p\) and counterclockwise transition probability \(1-p\):
\[
p_{12}=p,\quad p_{13}=1-p,
\]
\[
p_{23}=p,\quad p_{21}=1-p,
\]
\[
p_{31}=p,\quad p_{32}=1-p,
\]
with \(p\neq \frac12\).

Because each column also sums to \(1\), the matrix is doubly stochastic. Hence
\[
\pi_1=\pi_2=\pi_3=\frac13
\]
is stationary.

But detailed balance fails. For instance,
\[
\pi_1 p_{12}
=
\frac13 p,
\qquad
\pi_2 p_{21}
=
\frac13(1-p).
\]
These are unequal when \(p\neq \frac12\). Therefore the chain is not reversible with respect to \(\pi\).
\end{proof}

\subsection{Existence and uniqueness of stationary distributions}

The lecture now asks two separate questions:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item when does a stationary distribution exist?
    \item when is it unique?
\end{itemize}

The answers depend strongly on whether the chain is finite, infinite, irreducible, or reducible.

\begin{example}[Simple random walk on \(\mathbb Z\)]
For simple random walk on \(\mathbb Z\), the function
\[
\pi_i\equiv 1
\qquad (i\in \mathbb Z)
\]
satisfies
\[
\pi=\pi P,
\]
so it is a stationary measure. But
\[
\sum_{i\in\mathbb Z}\pi_i=+\infty,
\]
so it is not a stationary distribution.
\end{example}

\begin{example}[Reducible chain]
Suppose the chain has two closed classes with transition matrices \(P_1\) and \(P_2\), and let \(\pi^{(1)}\) and \(\pi^{(2)}\) be stationary distributions on those classes. Then for any \(\lambda\in[0,1]\),
\[
\bigl[\lambda \pi^{(1)},(1-\lambda)\pi^{(2)}\bigr]
\]
is a stationary distribution for the whole chain.

So in the reducible case, uniqueness can fail very badly.
\end{example}

\begin{theorem}
If the state space is finite, then at least one stationary distribution always exists.
\end{theorem}

This is a standard fixed-point result, usually proved using Brouwer's fixed-point theorem.

\subsection{Vanishing probabilities imply non-existence of a stationary distribution}

The lecture next proves a useful criterion for non-existence.

\begin{theorem}[Vanishing probabilities]
Suppose that for every \(i,j\in S\),
\[
\lim_{n\to\infty} p_{ij}^{(n)}=0.
\]
Then the Markov chain has no stationary distribution.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
Suppose instead that \(\pi\) is a stationary distribution. Then
\[
\pi=\pi P=\pi P^2=\cdots=\pi P^n
\qquad (\forall n\ge 1).
\]
So for each fixed \(j\),
\[
\pi_j
=
\sum_{i\in S}\pi_i p_{ij}^{(n)}.
\]

If we could pass the limit inside the sum, we would get
\[
\pi_j
=
\sum_{i\in S}\pi_i \lim_{n\to\infty} p_{ij}^{(n)}
=
\sum_{i\in S}\pi_i \cdot 0
=
0,
\]
which is impossible.

To justify the exchange of limit and summation, note that
\[
\sup_{n\ge 1}\bigl|\pi_i p_{ij}^{(n)}\bigr|
\le \pi_i,
\]
hence
\[
\sum_{i\in S}\sup_{n\ge 1}\bigl|\pi_i p_{ij}^{(n)}\bigr|
\le
\sum_{i\in S}\pi_i
=
1.
\]
So the Weierstrass \(M\)-test (equivalently dominated convergence for series) applies, and therefore
\[
\pi_j
=
\lim_{n\to\infty}\sum_{i\in S}\pi_i p_{ij}^{(n)}
=
\sum_{i\in S}\pi_i \lim_{n\to\infty}p_{ij}^{(n)}
=
0.
\]
Contradiction.
\end{proof}

\subsection{A vanishing lemma}

The previous theorem assumes vanishing for every pair \(i,j\). The next lemma shows that in an irreducible chain it is enough to know vanishing for a single well-placed pair.

\begin{lemma}[Vanishing lemma]
Suppose for some \(k,\ell\in S\),
\[
\lim_{n\to\infty} p_{k\ell}^{(n)}=0.
\]
If \(k\to i\) and \(j\to \ell\), then
\[
\lim_{n\to\infty} p_{ij}^{(n)}=0.
\]
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
Because \(k\to i\), there exists \(r\ge 0\) such that
\[
p_{ki}^{(r)}>0.
\]
Because \(j\to \ell\), there exists \(s\ge 0\) such that
\[
p_{j\ell}^{(s)}>0.
\]
Then Chapman--Kolmogorov gives
\[
p_{k\ell}^{(r+n+s)}
\ge
p_{ki}^{(r)}\,p_{ij}^{(n)}\,p_{j\ell}^{(s)}.
\]
The left-hand side tends to \(0\) by assumption, while the factors
\[
p_{ki}^{(r)},\quad p_{j\ell}^{(s)}
\]
are fixed positive constants. Therefore \(p_{ij}^{(n)}\to 0\).
\end{proof}

\begin{proposition}
For an irreducible Markov chain, if there exists one pair \(k,\ell\) such that
\[
\lim_{n\to\infty} p_{k\ell}^{(n)}=0,
\]
then in fact
\[
\lim_{n\to\infty} p_{ij}^{(n)}=0
\qquad \text{for all } i,j\in S.
\]
Consequently, the chain has no stationary distribution.
\end{proposition}

\begin{proposition}
A transient irreducible Markov chain cannot have a stationary distribution.
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
For a transient irreducible chain,
\[
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} p_{ij}^{(n)}<\infty
\qquad (\forall i,j\in S).
\]
Hence \(p_{ij}^{(n)}\to 0\) for every \(i,j\), so the previous theorem applies.
\end{proof}

\begin{remark}
For an irreducible chain, the transition probabilities ``vanish together'':
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item either \(p_{ij}^{(n)}\to 0\) for every \(i,j\);
    \item or \(p_{ij}^{(n)}\) does not vanish for any \(i,j\).
\end{itemize}
The second case does \emph{not} necessarily mean the sequence converges; periodic chains are the main counterexample.
\end{remark}

\subsection{Examples}

\begin{example}[One-dimensional simple random walk]
For simple random walk on \(\mathbb Z\),
\[
p_{00}^{(2n)}
=
\binom{2n}{n}2^{-2n}
\sim
\frac{c}{\sqrt{n}}
\to 0.
\]
So the chain does not have a stationary distribution.
\end{example}

\begin{example}[An infinite-state chain with a stationary distribution]
There are also infinite-state chains for which a genuine stationary distribution \emph{does} exist.

Let
\[
S=\{1,2,3,\dots\}.
\]
Define the transition probabilities by
\[
p_{11}=\frac34,
\qquad
p_{12}=\frac14,
\]
and for \(i\ge 2\),
\[
p_{i,i-1}=\frac12,
\qquad
p_{ii}=\frac14,
\qquad
p_{i,i+1}=\frac14.
\]

Now set
\[
\pi_i=2^{-i},
\qquad i\ge 1.
\]
Since
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{\infty} 2^{-i}=1,
\]
this is a probability distribution.

It is also reversible. For \(i\ge 1\),
\[
\pi_i p_{i,i+1}
=
2^{-i}\cdot \frac14
=
2^{-(i+2)},
\]
while
\[
\pi_{i+1}p_{i+1,i}
=
2^{-(i+1)}\cdot \frac12
=
2^{-(i+2)}.
\]
So
\[
\pi_i p_{i,i+1}=\pi_{i+1}p_{i+1,i}.
\]
Therefore \(\pi\) is stationary.
\end{example}

\begin{example}{(An infinite-state chain with a stationary distribution)}

A simple example is a birth--death chain on
\[
S=\{0,1,2,\dots\},
\]
with transition probabilities
\[
P(0,0)=q,\qquad P(0,1)=p,
\]
and for every \(i\ge 1\),
\[
P(i,i+1)=p,\qquad P(i,i-1)=q,
\]
where
\[
0<p<q<1.
\]
So the chain tends to move left more often than right, which keeps it from drifting off to infinity.

\medskip

\noindent
A picture of the chain is:

\begin{center}
\begin{tikzpicture}[>=stealth,->,thick]
    \node[circle,draw,minimum size=0.9cm] (0) at (0,0) {\(0\)};
    \node[circle,draw,minimum size=0.9cm] (1) at (2,0) {\(1\)};
    \node[circle,draw,minimum size=0.9cm] (2) at (4,0) {\(2\)};
    \node[circle,draw,minimum size=0.9cm] (3) at (6,0) {\(3\)};
    \node at (8,0) {\(\cdots\)};

    % loop at 0
    \path (0) edge[loop above] node {\(q\)} (0);

    % arrows between 0 and 1
    \path (0) edge[bend left=20] node[above] {\(p\)} (1);
    \path (1) edge[bend left=20] node[below] {\(q\)} (0);

    % arrows between 1 and 2
    \path (1) edge[bend left=20] node[above] {\(p\)} (2);
    \path (2) edge[bend left=20] node[below] {\(q\)} (1);

    % arrows between 2 and 3
    \path (2) edge[bend left=20] node[above] {\(p\)} (3);
    \path (3) edge[bend left=20] node[below] {\(q\)} (2);
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{center}

\medskip

\noindent
We claim that this chain has stationary distribution
\[
\pi_i=(1-r)r^i,\qquad i=0,1,2,\dots,
\]
where
\[
r=\frac{p}{q}.
\]
Since \(p<q\), we have \(0<r<1\), so
\[
\sum_{i=0}^\infty \pi_i=(1-r)\sum_{i=0}^\infty r^i=1.
\]
Thus \((\pi_i)\) is indeed a probability distribution.

\medskip

\noindent
To verify stationarity, it is enough to check the detailed balance equations:
\[
\pi_i P(i,i+1)=\pi_{i+1}P(i+1,i),\qquad i\ge 0.
\]
Indeed,
\[
\pi_i p=(1-r)r^i p,
\]
while
\[
\pi_{i+1} q=(1-r)r^{i+1}q=(1-r)r^i(rq).
\]
But \(r=\frac{p}{q}\), so \(rq=p\). Therefore
\[
\pi_{i+1}q=(1-r)r^i p=\pi_i p.
\]
Hence detailed balance holds, so \(\pi\) is a stationary distribution.

\medskip

\noindent
Therefore, this infinite-state Markov chain has stationary distribution
\[
\boxed{\pi_i=\left(1-\frac{p}{q}\right)\left(\frac{p}{q}\right)^i,\qquad i=0,1,2,\dots}
\]
which is a geometric distribution on \(\{0,1,2,\dots\}\).

\medskip

\noindent
\textbf{Remark.}
If \(p\ge q\), then the chain no longer has this summable stationary distribution. So the condition \(p<q\) is what creates enough drift to the left for a stationary distribution to exist.
\end{example}

\subsection{Why stationarity alone does not guarantee convergence}

At this point the lecture isolates two separate obstructions to convergence:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item \textbf{reducibility};
    \item \textbf{periodicity}.
\end{itemize}

\begin{example}[Reducibility can destroy convergence to a universal limit]
Take the two-state chain in which both states are absorbing:
\[
P=
\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 0\\
0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}.
\]
Every distribution of the form
\[
[\lambda,1-\lambda],
\qquad \lambda\in[0,1],
\]
is stationary.

But if the chain starts from state \(1\), then
\[
p_{12}^{(n)}=0
\qquad (\forall n).
\]
So the distribution at time \(n\) cannot converge to a prescribed stationary law such as
\[
\left[\frac12,\frac12\right].
\]
This shows why irreducibility is necessary in the convergence theorem.
\end{example}

\begin{example}[Periodicity can destroy convergence even when the stationary law is unique]
Consider the deterministic \(3\)-cycle
\[
1\to 2\to 3\to 1.
\]
This chain is irreducible, and its unique stationary distribution is
\[
\pi=
\left[\frac13,\frac13,\frac13\right].
\]
However,
\[
p_{11}^{(n)}
=
\begin{cases}
1, & \text{if } 3\mid n,\\[0.3em]
0, & \text{if } 3\nmid n.
\end{cases}
\]
So \(p_{11}^{(n)}\) does not converge. Hence uniqueness of the stationary distribution is still not enough; we must also rule out periodicity.
\end{example}

\subsection{Period and aperiodicity}

\begin{definition}[Period]
The \emph{period} of a state \(i\in S\) is
\[
d(i)=\gcd\{n\ge 1: p_{ii}^{(n)}>0\}.
\]
\end{definition}

For the \(3\)-cycle above,
\[
\{n\ge 1:p_{11}^{(n)}>0\}=\{3,6,9,\dots\},
\]
so \(d(1)=3\).

Two quick ways to get period \(1\) are:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item if \(p_{ii}>0\), then \(1\in \{n\ge 1:p_{ii}^{(n)}>0\}\), hence \(d(i)=1\);
    \item more generally, if both \(p_{ii}^{(n)}>0\) and \(p_{ii}^{(n+1)}>0\) for some \(n\), then the gcd is \(1\).
\end{itemize}

\begin{lemma}[Equal period lemma]
If \(i\leftrightarrow j\), then \(i\) and \(j\) have the same period.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
Assume \(i\leftrightarrow j\). Then there exist integers \(r,s\ge 0\) such that
\[
p_{ij}^{(r)}>0,
\qquad
p_{ji}^{(s)}>0.
\]

Now suppose \(p_{ii}^{(n)}>0\) for some \(n\ge 1\). Then
\[
p_{jj}^{(r+n+s)}
\ge
p_{ji}^{(s)}\,p_{ii}^{(n)}\,p_{ij}^{(r)}
>
0.
\]
Also,
\[
p_{ii}^{(r+s)}
\ge
p_{ij}^{(r)}\,p_{ji}^{(s)}
>
0.
\]
Let \(d(i)\) and \(d(j)\) denote the respective periods. Since \(d(j)\) divides every return time to \(j\), it divides both \(r+n+s\) and \(r+s\), hence it divides their difference \(n\). Therefore every \(n\) with \(p_{ii}^{(n)}>0\) is divisible by \(d(j)\). This shows
\[
d(j)\le d(i).
\]
By symmetry,
\[
d(i)\le d(j).
\]
So \(d(i)=d(j)\).
\end{proof}

\begin{proposition}
If a Markov chain is irreducible, then all states have the same period.
\end{proposition}

\begin{definition}[Aperiodicity]
A state \(i\) is called \emph{aperiodic} if \(d(i)=1\).

An irreducible chain is called \emph{aperiodic} if one (equivalently every) state has period \(1\).
\end{definition}

\subsection{The convergence theorem}

We now have exactly the right hypotheses: irreducibility rules out the reducible obstruction, and aperiodicity rules out the cyclic obstruction.

\begin{theorem}[Markov chain convergence]
Suppose a Markov chain is irreducible, aperiodic, and has a stationary distribution \(\pi\). Then for every \(i,j\in S\),
\[
\lim_{n\to\infty} p_{ij}^{(n)}=\pi_j.
\]
Equivalently, starting from a fixed state \(i\),
\[
\mathbb P_i(X_n=j)\longrightarrow \pi_j.
\]
More generally, if \(X_0\sim \nu\), then
\[
\mathbb P_\nu(X_n=j)
=
\sum_{i\in S}\nu_i p_{ij}^{(n)}
\longrightarrow
\pi_j.
\]
\end{theorem}

In particular, the limit does not depend on the initial state. So the theorem automatically implies uniqueness of the stationary distribution.

\begin{keyformula}
If the chain is
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item irreducible,
    \item aperiodic,
    \item and admits a stationary distribution \(\pi\),
\end{itemize}
then
\[
p_{ij}^{(n)}\longrightarrow \pi_j
\qquad (\forall i,j\in S).
\]
So the chain forgets its starting point and converges to equilibrium.
\end{keyformula}

\subsection{Summary}

\begin{summarybox}
Lecture 3 builds the long-run theory of discrete-time Markov chains.

Main takeaways:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item in an irreducible chain, recurrence and transience admit several equivalent descriptions through \(f_{ij}\), \(N(j)\), and the sums \(\sum_n p_{ij}^{(n)}\);
    \item the condition \(\exists\, i,j\) with \(f_{ij}=1\) is not enough for recurrence;
    \item any possible limit of \(p_{ij}^{(n)}\) must be stationary, so stationary distributions are the natural candidates for equilibrium;
    \item doubly stochastic matrices have the uniform stationary law, and detailed balance is a convenient sufficient condition for stationarity;
    \item finite chains always have at least one stationary distribution, but infinite chains may fail to have one, and reducible chains may have many;
    \item for irreducible chains, transient behavior forces \(p_{ij}^{(n)}\to 0\), so no stationary distribution can exist;
    \item to obtain convergence to stationarity, one must rule out both reducibility and periodicity;
    \item the final convergence theorem says that irreducible + aperiodic + stationary distribution implies
    \[
    p_{ij}^{(n)}\to \pi_j.
    \]
\end{itemize}
\end{summarybox}

