    \item electronics, including calculators, are not allowed;
    \item the material covered is everything from the first four weeks.
\end{itemize}

After this announcement, the lecture turns to the main conceptual question: \emph{when does an irreducible Markov chain converge to equilibrium, and when does a stationary distribution exist at all?}

\subsection{Main convergence theorem}

The first major statement of the lecture is the convergence theorem for irreducible, aperiodic chains.

\begin{theorem}[Convergence of an irreducible aperiodic chain]
Let \(P\) be an irreducible and aperiodic Markov chain on a countable state space \(S\). Assume that \(P\) has a stationary distribution \(\pi\). Then for every \(i,j\in S\),
\[
\lim_{n\to\infty} p_{ij}^{(n)}=\pi_j.
\]
\end{theorem}

So once irreducibility and aperiodicity are present, the only remaining issue is whether a stationary distribution exists. Lecture 4 proves the convergence result first, then develops a criterion for the existence of a stationary distribution in terms of return times.

\subsection{The key idea: Markov forgetting}

The proof begins with the following lemma, called in the lecture the \emph{Markov forgetting} property.

\begin{lemma}[Markov forgetting]
Assume \(P\) is irreducible, aperiodic, and has a stationary distribution. Then for every \(i,j,k\in S\),
\[
\lim_{n\to\infty} \left|p_{ik}^{(n)}-p_{jk}^{(n)}\right|=0.
\]
\end{lemma}

In words, if we look far enough into the future, the chain essentially forgets its starting state.

Once this lemma is known, convergence to \(\pi\) is immediate: compare a chain started from a fixed state with a chain started from stationarity.

\subsection{Comparing two copies of the chain}

Fix two initial states \(i,j\in S\). We want to compare
\[
(X_n^{(1)})_{n\ge 0}\quad\text{started from }i,
\qquad
(X_n^{(2)})_{n\ge 0}\quad\text{started from }j.
\]

The lecture constructs a new Markov chain on the product space
\[
\overline S = S\times S,
\]
whose coordinates evolve independently according to \(P\) until a suitable coupling time.

If \((x_1,x_2),(y_1,y_2)\in S\times S\), define the product-chain transition probabilities by
\[
\overline p_{(x_1,x_2),(y_1,y_2)}
=
 p_{x_1y_1}p_{x_2y_2}.
\]
Equivalently,
\[
\overline P = P\otimes P.
\]

The marginals of this chain are exactly the two independent copies of the original Markov chain.

\subsection{Stationarity for the product chain}

If \(\pi\) is stationary for \(P\), then the product measure
\[
\overline\pi_{(x,y)} = \pi_x\pi_y,
\qquad (x,y)\in S\times S,
\]
is stationary for \(\overline P\).

\begin{lemma}[Product stationary distribution]
If \(\pi P=\pi\), then \(\overline\pi\,\overline P=\overline\pi\).
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
For \((u,v)\in S\times S\),
\[
\sum_{(x,y)\in S\times S}\overline\pi_{(x,y)}\overline p_{(x,y),(u,v)}
=
\sum_{x,y}\pi_x\pi_y p_{xu}p_{yv}
=
\left(\sum_x \pi_x p_{xu}\right)
\left(\sum_y \pi_y p_{yv}\right)
=
\pi_u\pi_v
=
\overline\pi_{(u,v)}.
\]
\end{proof}

So the product chain also has a stationary distribution.

\subsection{Why irreducibility of the base chain is not enough}

A subtle point in the handwritten notes is that \emph{irreducibility of \(P\) alone does not automatically imply irreducibility of the product chain \(\overline P\)}.

For example, if \(P\) is the one-dimensional simple random walk, then parity effects prevent the two-coordinate chain from reaching all states of \(S\times S\). The obstruction comes from periodicity.

This is exactly where the assumption of \textbf{aperiodicity} is used.

\subsection{Aperiodicity gives eventual positivity}

The first technical lemma says that for an aperiodic state, sufficiently large return times all have positive probability.

\begin{lemma}[Eventual positivity of return probabilities]
Let \(i\in S\) be an aperiodic state. Then there exists \(n_0(i)\in\mathbb N\) such that
\[
p_{ii}^{(n)}>0
\qquad \text{for all } n\ge n_0(i).
\]
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}[Idea]
Consider the set
\[
A_i = \{n\ge 1 : p_{ii}^{(n)}>0\}.
\]
This set is additive: if \(m,n\in A_i\), then by Chapman--Kolmogorov,
\[
p_{ii}^{(m+n)}
\ge
p_{ii}^{(m)}p_{ii}^{(n)}
>0,
\]
so \(m+n\in A_i\).

Aperiodicity means
\[
\gcd(A_i)=1.
\]
A standard number-theoretic fact then says that an additive subset of \(\mathbb N\) with greatest common divisor \(1\) must contain all sufficiently large integers. Hence \(p_{ii}^{(n)}>0\) for all large \(n\).
\end{proof}

This is the key tool for removing the periodic obstruction.

\begin{proposition}[Eventual positivity between any two states]
If \(P\) is irreducible and aperiodic, then for every \(i,j\in S\) there exists \(n_0(i,j)\in\mathbb N\) such that
\[
p_{ij}^{(n)}>0
\qquad \text{for all } n\ge n_0(i,j).
\]
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
Because the chain is irreducible, there exists some \(r\ge 0\) with \(p_{ij}^{(r)}>0\). Since \(j\) is aperiodic in an irreducible chain, there exists \(N\) such that \(p_{jj}^{(m)}>0\) for all \(m\ge N\). Therefore, for every \(n\ge r+N\),
\[
p_{ij}^{(n)}
\ge
p_{ij}^{(r)}p_{jj}^{(n-r)}
>0.
\]
This proves the claim.
\end{proof}

\subsection{Irreducibility of the product chain}

Now fix \((i,j),(k,\ell)\in S\times S\). By the corollary above, there exists \(N\) such that for all \(n\ge N\),
\[
p_{ik}^{(n)}>0
\qquad\text{and}\qquad
p_{j\ell}^{(n)}>0.
\]
Hence for all sufficiently large \(n\),
\[
\overline p^{(n)}_{(i,j),(k,\ell)}
=
p_{ik}^{(n)}p_{j\ell}^{(n)}
>0.
\]
So the product chain is irreducible.

Because it also has a stationary distribution \(\overline\pi\), the product chain is in fact positive recurrent. In particular, every state of \(S\times S\) is recurrent.

\subsection{Hitting a common reference state}

Fix some reference state \(i_0\in S\), and define
\[
\tau=
\inf\{n\ge 0 : X_n^{(1)}=X_n^{(2)}=i_0\}.
\]

Since the product chain is irreducible and positive recurrent, every state is recurrent, so from any starting point \((i,j)\in S\times S\),
\[
\overline{\mathbb P}_{i,j}(\tau<\infty)=1.
\]

This is the coupling time used in the notes: we wait until both copies hit the same distinguished state \(i_0\) at the same time.

\subsection{Proof of Markov forgetting by coupling}

Up to time \(\tau\), let the two coordinates evolve independently according to the product chain. At time \(\tau\), both coordinates equal \(i_0\). From that moment on, we can force the two chains to use the same randomness, so that they move together forever after time \(\tau\).

Fix \(k\in S\). For the first chain,
\[
p_{ik}^{(n)}
=
\overline{\mathbb P}_{i,j}(X_n^{(1)}=k).
\]
Split according to the value of \(\tau\):
\[
p_{ik}^{(n)}
=
\sum_{m=0}^{n}
\overline{\mathbb P}_{i,j}(X_n^{(1)}=k,\tau=m)
+
\overline{\mathbb P}_{i,j}(X_n^{(1)}=k,\tau\ge n+1).
\]
When \(\tau=m\le n\), the first chain is at \(i_0\) at time \(m\), so by the Markov property,
\[
\overline{\mathbb P}_{i,j}(X_n^{(1)}=k,\tau=m)
=
\overline{\mathbb P}_{i,j}(\tau=m)
\,p_{i_0k}^{(n-m)}.
\]
Thus
\[
p_{ik}^{(n)}
=
\sum_{m=0}^{n}
\overline{\mathbb P}_{i,j}(\tau=m)
\,p_{i_0k}^{(n-m)}
+
\overline{\mathbb P}_{i,j}(X_n^{(1)}=k,\tau\ge n+1).
\]
Exactly the same argument gives
\[
p_{jk}^{(n)}
=
\sum_{m=0}^{n}
\overline{\mathbb P}_{i,j}(\tau=m)
\,p_{i_0k}^{(n-m)}
+
\overline{\mathbb P}_{i,j}(X_n^{(2)}=k,\tau\ge n+1).
\]
Subtracting,
\[
\left|p_{ik}^{(n)}-p_{jk}^{(n)}\right|
\le
\overline{\mathbb P}_{i,j}(X_n^{(1)}=k,\tau\ge n+1)
+
\overline{\mathbb P}_{i,j}(X_n^{(2)}=k,\tau\ge n+1)
\le
2\,\overline{\mathbb P}_{i,j}(\tau\ge n+1).
\]
Since \(\overline{\mathbb P}_{i,j}(\tau<\infty)=1\), we have
\[
\overline{\mathbb P}_{i,j}(\tau\ge n+1)\to 0,
\]
and therefore
\[
\left|p_{ik}^{(n)}-p_{jk}^{(n)}\right|\to 0.
\]
This proves the Markov forgetting lemma.

\begin{keyformula}
For the coupling time
\[
\tau=\inf\{n\ge 0 : X_n^{(1)}=X_n^{(2)}=i_0\},
\]
one has
\[
\left|p_{ik}^{(n)}-p_{jk}^{(n)}\right|
\le
2\,\overline{\mathbb P}_{i,j}(\tau\ge n+1)
\longrightarrow 0.
\]
This is the precise mathematical form of ``the chain forgets where it started.''
\end{keyformula}

\subsection{From forgetting to convergence to stationarity}

Now compare a chain started from \(i\) with a chain started from the stationary distribution \(\pi\). Since \(\pi P^n=\pi\), we have
\[
\pi_j = \sum_{k\in S}\pi_k p_{kj}^{(n)}.
\]
Hence
\[
\left|p_{ij}^{(n)}-\pi_j\right|
=
\left|p_{ij}^{(n)}-\sum_{k\in S}\pi_k p_{kj}^{(n)}\right|
\le
\sum_{k\in S}\pi_k\left|p_{ij}^{(n)}-p_{kj}^{(n)}\right|.
\]
For each fixed \(k\), the Markov forgetting lemma says that
\[
\left|p_{ij}^{(n)}-p_{kj}^{(n)}\right|\to 0.
\]
Also,
\[
0\le \pi_k\left|p_{ij}^{(n)}-p_{kj}^{(n)}\right|\le \pi_k,
\qquad
\sum_{k\in S}\pi_k=1.
\]
So by dominated convergence,
\[
\left|p_{ij}^{(n)}-\pi_j\right|\to 0.
\]
Therefore,
\[
p_{ij}^{(n)}\to \pi_j.
\]

\subsection{Initial distributions, not just initial states}

The same argument works if the chain starts from an arbitrary initial distribution \(\nu\). Indeed,
\[
\mathbb P_\nu(X_n=j)=\sum_{i\in S}\nu_i p_{ij}^{(n)}.
\]
Since \(p_{ij}^{(n)}\to \pi_j\) for every \(i\), dominated convergence yields
\[
\mathbb P_\nu(X_n=j)\to \pi_j.
\]
So the limiting distribution is independent of the starting law.

\subsection{What changes in the periodic case?}

The lecture next asks what happens if the chain is irreducible but periodic.

Suppose the chain has period \(b\ge 2\). Then the state space can be decomposed into cyclic classes
\[
S_0,S_1,\dots,S_{b-1},
\]
such that transitions go from \(S_r\) into \(S_{r+1\!\!\pmod b}\).

In that case, the chain keeps rotating through the classes, so the full limit \(p_{ij}^{(n)}\to \pi_j\) generally fails. However, the stationary distribution spreads equally across the cyclic classes:
\[
\pi(S_0)=\pi(S_1)=\cdots=\pi(S_{b-1})=\frac{1}{b}.
\]

\begin{theorem}[Averaged convergence for a periodic chain]
Assume \(P\) is irreducible of period \(b\ge 2\), and assume \(P\) has a stationary distribution \(\pi\). Then for every \(i,j\in S\),
\[
\lim_{n\to\infty}
\frac1b\Bigl(
p_{ij}^{(n)}+p_{ij}^{(n+1)}+\cdots+p_{ij}^{(n+b-1)}
\Bigr)
=
\pi_j.
\]
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}[Idea]
If we look at \(P^b\) restricted to a single cyclic class \(S_r\), then the periodicity disappears: inside each class, \(P^b\) is irreducible and aperiodic. Therefore the convergence theorem applies to \(P^b\) on each \(S_r\). Averaging across one complete cycle of length \(b\) then gives the displayed limit.
\end{proof}

\begin{proposition}[Ces\`aro convergence]
If \(P\) is irreducible and has a stationary distribution \(\pi\), then for every \(i,j\in S\),
\[
\lim_{N\to\infty}\frac1N\sum_{n=1}^{N} p_{ij}^{(n)}=\pi_j.
\]
\end{proposition}

So even when pointwise convergence fails because of periodic oscillation, the time average still converges to \(\pi\).

As a consequence, if an irreducible chain has a stationary distribution, then that stationary distribution must be unique.

\subsection{The next question: when does a stationary distribution exist?}

The second half of Lecture 4 addresses the existence problem.

For a state \(i\in S\), define the first return time
\[
T_i = \inf\{n\ge 1 : X_n=i\}.
\]
If the chain is recurrent, then
\[
\mathbb P_i(T_i<\infty)=1.
\]
But recurrence alone does \emph{not} imply
\[
\mathbb E_i[T_i]<\infty.
\]
This distinction leads to the notions of \emph{positive recurrence} and \emph{null recurrence}.

\subsection{Excursion decomposition and the heuristic formula}

The notes draw the trajectory starting from \(i\) and split it into blocks:
\[
X_0=i, X_1,X_2,\dots,X_{T_i-1}
\qquad\Big|\qquad
X_{T_i}=i,
\]
then the next block between the first and second returns, and so on. These blocks are i.i.d. by the strong Markov property.

This picture suggests the following heuristic.

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item The average length of one excursion block should be \(\mathbb E_i[T_i]\).
    \item Each block contains exactly one visit to \(i\), namely at its start.
    \item Therefore the long-run frequency of visits to \(i\) should be roughly
    \[
    \frac{1}{\mathbb E_i[T_i]}.
    \]
    \item But in stationarity, the long-run frequency of visits to \(i\) is exactly \(\pi_i\).
\end{itemize}

So the lecture predicts the fundamental formula
\[
\pi_i = \frac{1}{\mathbb E_i[T_i]}.
\]
The rest of the lecture makes this precise.

\subsection{A stationary measure built from one excursion}

Fix a recurrent irreducible chain and a reference state \(i_0\in S\). Define
\[
\mu_{i_0}(j)
=
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}
\mathbb P_{i_0}(X_n=j,\,T_{i_0}>n),
\qquad j\in S.
\]

This quantity counts the expected number of visits to \(j\) during one excursion away from \(i_0\), including time \(0\) and stopping just before the return to \(i_0\).

\begin{theorem}[Canonical stationary measure]
Assume \(P\) is irreducible and recurrent. Then for every fixed \(i_0\in S\):
\begin{enumerate}[label=(\roman*)]
    \item \(\mu_{i_0}(j)<\infty\) for every \(j\in S\);
    \item \(\mu_{i_0}(i_0)=1\);
    \item \(\mu_{i_0}\) is a stationary measure, i.e.
    \[
    \mu_{i_0}P = \mu_{i_0}.
    \]
\end{enumerate}
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
First,
\[
\mu_{i_0}(i_0)
=
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}
\mathbb P_{i_0}(X_n=i_0,\,T_{i_0}>n).
\]
Only the term \(n=0\) contributes, because for \(n\ge 1\), the event \(X_n=i_0\) together with \(T_{i_0}>n\) is impossible. Thus
\[
\mu_{i_0}(i_0)=1.
\]

Now fix \(k\in S\). We compute
\[
\sum_{j\in S}\mu_{i_0}(j)p_{jk}
=
\sum_{j\in S}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}
\mathbb P_{i_0}(X_n=j,T_{i_0}>n)p_{jk}.
\]
By Tonelli's theorem,
\[
\sum_{j\in S}\mu_{i_0}(j)p_{jk}
=
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\sum_{j\in S}
\mathbb P_{i_0}(X_n=j,T_{i_0}>n)p_{jk}.
\]
Use the Markov property at time \(n\).

If \(k\neq i_0\), then moving from \(j\) to \(k\) at time \(n+1\) automatically means the chain has not yet returned to \(i_0\), so
\[
\sum_{j\in S}
\mathbb P_{i_0}(X_n=j,T_{i_0}>n)p_{jk}
=
\mathbb P_{i_0}(X_{n+1}=k,T_{i_0}>n+1).
\]
Hence
\[
\sum_{j\in S}\mu_{i_0}(j)p_{jk}
=
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}
\mathbb P_{i_0}(X_{n+1}=k,T_{i_0}>n+1)
=
\mu_{i_0}(k)
\qquad (k\neq i_0).
\]

If \(k=i_0\), then the only way to land in \(i_0\) at time \(n+1\) while still having \(T_{i_0}>n\) is that the first return occurs exactly at time \(n+1\). Therefore
\[
\sum_{j\in S}
\mathbb P_{i_0}(X_n=j,T_{i_0}>n)p_{ji_0}
=
\mathbb P_{i_0}(T_{i_0}=n+1).
\]
Summing over \(n\) gives
\[
\sum_{j\in S}\mu_{i_0}(j)p_{ji_0}
=
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\mathbb P_{i_0}(T_{i_0}=n+1)
=
1
=
\mu_{i_0}(i_0).
\]
So \(\mu_{i_0}P=\mu_{i_0}\).

It remains to show finiteness. Since the chain is irreducible, for each \(j\in S\) there exists \(m\ge 0\) such that \(p_{ji_0}^{(m)}>0\). Using stationarity of \(\mu_{i_0}\),
\[
1
=
\mu_{i_0}(i_0)
=
\sum_{\ell\in S}\mu_{i_0}(\ell)p_{\ell i_0}^{(m)}
\ge
\mu_{i_0}(j)p_{ji_0}^{(m)}.
\]
Hence
\[
\mu_{i_0}(j)
\le
\frac{1}{p_{ji_0}^{(m)}}
<\infty.
\]
This proves all claims.
\end{proof}

\begin{remark}
The measure \(\mu_{i_0}\) is supported on all states in an irreducible recurrent chain, so in fact \(\mu_{i_0}(j)>0\) for every \(j\in S\). In a reducible chain, a stationary measure may live only on a smaller closed class, so irreducibility matters here.
\end{remark}

\subsection{When can the stationary measure be normalized?}

The total mass of \(\mu_{i_0}\) is
\[
\sum_{j\in S}\mu_{i_0}(j)
=
\sum_{j\in S}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}
\mathbb P_{i_0}(X_n=j,T_{i_0}>n).
\]
Interchanging the sums,
\[
\sum_{j\in S}\mu_{i_0}(j)
=
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}
\sum_{j\in S}\mathbb P_{i_0}(X_n=j,T_{i_0}>n)
=
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}
\mathbb P_{i_0}(T_{i_0}>n).
\]
But for a positive integer-valued random variable,
\[
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\mathbb P(T_{i_0}>n)=\mathbb E_{i_0}[T_{i_0}].
\]
Therefore,
\[
\sum_{j\in S}\mu_{i_0}(j)=\mathbb E_{i_0}[T_{i_0}].
\]

This shows exactly when \(\mu_{i_0}\) can be normalized to a probability distribution.

\begin{definition}[Positive recurrence]
A state \(i\in S\) is called \emph{positive recurrent} if
\[
\mathbb E_i[T_i]<\infty.
\]
If \(i\) is recurrent but
\[
\mathbb E_i[T_i]=\infty,
\]
then \(i\) is called \emph{null recurrent}.
\end{definition}

\begin{proposition}[Stationary distribution from positive recurrence]
If \(P\) is irreducible and recurrent, and if some state \(i\) satisfies \(\mathbb E_i[T_i]<\infty\), then
\[
\pi_j = \frac{\mu_i(j)}{\mathbb E_i[T_i]},
\qquad j\in S,
\]
defines a stationary distribution.
\end{proposition}

Thus positive recurrence is the correct condition for existence of a stationary distribution.

\subsection{Classifying irreducible chains}

Positive recurrence is a class property.

\begin{proposition}[Communication preserves positive recurrence]
If \(i\leftrightarrow j\) and \(i\) is positive recurrent, then \(j\) is also positive recurrent.
\end{proposition}

Hence in an irreducible chain, either all states are positive recurrent or none are.

\begin{proposition}[Existence criterion]
For an irreducible Markov chain, the following are equivalent:
\begin{enumerate}[label=(\roman*)]
    \item there exists a stationary distribution;
    \item one state is positive recurrent;
    \item every state is positive recurrent.
\end{enumerate}
\end{proposition}

So an irreducible chain falls into exactly one of three regimes:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item \textbf{transient};
    \item \textbf{null recurrent};
    \item \textbf{positive recurrent}.
\end{itemize}
Only in the positive recurrent case does a stationary \emph{distribution} exist. In the recurrent cases, a stationary \emph{measure} always exists, but it may have infinite total mass.

\subsection{Long-run frequency of visits}

The final theorem of the lecture identifies the frequency of visits to a state in terms of the mean return time.

For \(i\in S\), let
\[
N_n(i)=\sum_{t=1}^{n}\mathbf 1\{X_t=i\}
\]
be the number of visits to \(i\) up to time \(n\).

\begin{theorem}[Visit-frequency theorem]
Assume \(P\) is irreducible and recurrent. Then for every \(i\in S\),
\[
\frac{N_n(i)}{n}
\longrightarrow
\frac{1}{\mathbb E_i[T_i]}
\qquad \text{almost surely},
\]
with the convention that \(1/\infty=0\).
\end{theorem}

This is the strong-law version of convergence for Markov chains: the empirical proportion of time spent at state \(i\) equals the reciprocal of the mean return time to \(i\).

\subsection{Proof via i.i.d. excursion blocks}

Let
\[
T_i^{(k)} = \text{time of the }k\text{-th visit to }i,
\qquad k\ge 1,
\]
and set \(T_i^{(0)}=0\). Then the blocks
\[
\bigl(X_t : T_i^{(k)}<t\le T_i^{(k+1)}\bigr),
\qquad k=0,1,2,\dots,
\]
are i.i.d. by the strong Markov property.

The increments
\[
Y_k=T_i^{(k)}-T_i^{(k-1)},
\qquad k\ge 1,
\]
are therefore i.i.d. with the same law as \(T_i\) under \(\mathbb P_i\).

Also,
\[
T_i^{(N_n(i))}\le n < T_i^{(N_n(i)+1)}.
\]
Dividing by \(N_n(i)\),
\[
\frac{T_i^{(N_n(i))}}{N_n(i)}
\le
\frac{n}{N_n(i)}
\le
\frac{T_i^{(N_n(i)+1)}}{N_n(i)}.
\]
Because the chain is recurrent, \(N_n(i)\to\infty\) almost surely. So it is enough to understand the asymptotic behavior of \(T_i^{(k)}/k\).

Now
\[
\frac{T_i^{(k)}}{k}
=
\frac1k\sum_{\ell=1}^{k}\bigl(T_i^{(\ell)}-T_i^{(\ell-1)}\bigr)
=
\frac1k\sum_{\ell=1}^{k}Y_\ell.
\]
By the strong law of large numbers,
\[
\frac{T_i^{(k)}}{k}
\to
\mathbb E_i[T_i]
\qquad \text{almost surely}
\]
when \(\mathbb E_i[T_i]<\infty\), and it diverges to \(+\infty\) if \(\mathbb E_i[T_i]=\infty\). The same is true for
\[
\frac{T_i^{(k+1)}}{k}
=
\frac{T_i^{(k+1)}}{k+1}\cdot\frac{k+1}{k}.
\]
Therefore the squeeze inequality gives
\[
\frac{n}{N_n(i)}\to \mathbb E_i[T_i]
\qquad \text{almost surely},
\]
which is equivalent to
\[
\frac{N_n(i)}{n}
\to
\frac{1}{\mathbb E_i[T_i]}.
\]

\subsection{Recovering the stationary distribution formula}

Suppose now that \(P\) is irreducible and has a stationary distribution \(\pi\). Then the Ces\`aro convergence theorem gives
\[
\frac1n\sum_{t=1}^{n} p_{ii}^{(t)} \to \pi_i.
\]
But
\[
\mathbb E_i[N_n(i)]
=
\sum_{t=1}^{n}\mathbb P_i(X_t=i)
=
\sum_{t=1}^{n} p_{ii}^{(t)},
\]
so
\[
\frac{\mathbb E_i[N_n(i)]}{n}
\to \pi_i.
\]
On the other hand, from the visit-frequency theorem and dominated convergence,
\[
\frac{\mathbb E_i[N_n(i)]}{n}
\to
\frac{1}{\mathbb E_i[T_i]}.
\]
Hence
\[
\pi_i = \frac{1}{\mathbb E_i[T_i]}.
\]
This completes the ``other direction'' promised by the lecture: if a stationary distribution exists, then the chain must be positive recurrent, and its stationary probabilities are determined by mean return times.

\begin{keyformula}
For an irreducible positive recurrent Markov chain,
\[
\pi_i = \frac{1}{\mathbb E_i[T_i]}
\qquad \text{for every } i\in S.
\]
This is one of the most important formulas in the theory of Markov chains.
\end{keyformula}

\subsection{Summary}

\begin{summarybox}
Lecture 4 has two big themes.

\textbf{(1) Convergence to stationarity.}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item If \(P\) is irreducible, aperiodic, and has a stationary distribution \(\pi\), then
    \[
    p_{ij}^{(n)}\to \pi_j.
    \]
    \item The proof is based on a coupling argument on the product chain \(S\times S\).
    \item The key lemma is \emph{Markov forgetting}:
    \[
    \left|p_{ik}^{(n)}-p_{jk}^{(n)}\right|\to 0.
    \]
    \item If the chain is periodic, pointwise convergence may fail, but Ces\`aro averages still converge to \(\pi\).
\end{itemize}

\textbf{(2) Existence of a stationary distribution.}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item For a recurrent irreducible chain, one can always build a stationary measure
    \[
    \mu_i(j)=\sum_{n\ge 0}\mathbb P_i(X_n=j, T_i>n).
    \]
    \item Its total mass is exactly \(\mathbb E_i[T_i]\).
    \item Therefore a stationary distribution exists \emph{iff} the chain is positive recurrent.
    \item In that case,
    \[
    \pi_i = \frac{1}{\mathbb E_i[T_i]}.
    \]
    \item Null recurrent and transient irreducible chains do not admit stationary distributions.
\end{itemize}
\end{summarybox}

