\subsection*{Question 3 \hfill [15 points]}

Recall the independent coupling defined in class. Consider two copies of Markov chains
\[
\{X_n^{(1)}\}_{n\ge 0}
\qquad \text{and} \qquad
\{X_n^{(2)}\}_{n\ge 0}
\]
with the same transition matrix \(P\). At each step, the two chains move independently according to \(P\), regardless of their current states. Assume \(P\) is irreducible, aperiodic, and recurrent (but not necessarily positive recurrent).

\paragraph{(1) \hfill [6 pts]}
Show that the joint chain
\[
\{(X_n^{(1)},X_n^{(2)})\}_{n\ge 0}
\]
has a stationary measure.

\textbf{Answer:}
Let \(\pi\) be a stationary measure of \(P\). Then \(\pi\otimes \pi\) is a stationary measure for the joint chain, i.e.
\[
(\pi\otimes \pi)(i,j)=\pi_i\pi_j.
\]
Indeed,
\[
\sum_{(k,l)\in S\times S}(\pi\otimes \pi)(k,l)\,p_{(k,l),(i,j)}
=
\sum_{k,l}\pi_k\pi_l\,p_{ki}p_{lj}
=
\left(\sum_k \pi_k p_{ki}\right)\left(\sum_l \pi_l p_{lj}\right)
=
\pi_i\pi_j.
\]

\textbf{Rubrics:}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item If you construct the correct stationary measure but do not verify stationarity, you can get \(3\) points.
    \item An incomplete verification gets partial credit.
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{(2) \hfill [9 pts]}
Construct a Markov chain \(P\) satisfying the above conditions such that the joint chain
\[
\{(X_n^{(1)},X_n^{(2)})\}_{n\ge 0}
\]
is transient.

\textbf{Answer:}
Let \(P\) be a lazy version of two-dimensional simple random walk on \(\mathbb Z^2\):
\[
X_{n+1}=X_n+(\varepsilon_{n+1}^{(1)},\varepsilon_{n+1}^{(2)}),
\]
where \(\varepsilon_{n+1}^{(1)}\) and \(\varepsilon_{n+1}^{(2)}\) are i.i.d. with
\[
\mathbb P(\varepsilon_{n+1}^{(1)}=0)=\frac12,
\qquad
\mathbb P(\varepsilon_{n+1}^{(1)}=\pm 1)=\frac14 \text{ each,}
\]
and the same distribution for \(\varepsilon_{n+1}^{(2)}\).

This chain is irreducible and aperiodic. It is recurrent since simple random walk on \(\mathbb Z^2\) is recurrent. But the joint chain can be viewed as a lazy random walk on \(\mathbb Z^4\), which is transient.

