\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item Any valid construction gets full credit.
    \item If the construction is valid but you do not explain why the joint chain is transient, you can get \(8\) points.
    \item If you use ordinary two-dimensional simple random walk without laziness, you can get \(6\) points since the chain is not aperiodic.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Question 4 \hfill [8 points]}

Let \(P\) be an irreducible Markov chain on a finite state space \(S\). Let \(T_i\) be the hitting time to state \(i\). Show that for any state \(i\in S\),
\[
\mathbb E_i[T_i^n]<\infty,
\qquad \text{for any } n\in\mathbb N_+.
\]

\textbf{Answer:}
Since \(P\) is irreducible, for every \(j\in S\), there exists \(m_j\in\mathbb N_+\) such that
\[
p_{ji}^{(m_j)}>0.
\]
Let
\[
m=\max_{j\in S} m_j,
\qquad
\varepsilon=\min_{j\in S} p_{ji}^{(m_j)}.
\]
Since \(S\) is finite,
\[
m<\infty,
\qquad
\varepsilon>0.
\]
Hence
\[
\mathbb P_j(T_i>m)\le 1-\varepsilon,
\qquad \text{for all } j\in S.
\]
Therefore, for any \(k\in\mathbb N_+\),
\[
\mathbb P_i(T_i>km)\le (1-\varepsilon)^k.
\]
Then
\[
\mathbb E_i[T_i^n]
=
\sum_{t=0}^\infty \mathbb P_i(T_i\ge t)\big((t+1)^n-t^n\big)
\le
\sum_{t=0}^\infty (1-\varepsilon)^{\lfloor t/m\rfloor}(n+1)(t+1)^{n-1}
<\infty.
\]

\textbf{Rubrics:}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item If you cite the relevant Lawler practice result clearly and use it correctly, full credit.
    \item If you prove the exponential tail bound but do not finish the moment argument, \(5\) points.
    \item If you only prove \(\mathbb E_i[T_i]<\infty\), \(2\) points.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Question 5 \hfill [15 points]}

Consider a Markov chain on
\[
S=\{0,1,2,\dots\}.
\]
For \(i\ge 1\), define
\[
p_{i,i+1}=\frac{i}{2i+2},
\qquad
p_{i,i-1}=\frac{i+2}{2i+2},
\]
and \(p_{i,j}=0\) for \(j\notin\{i-1,i+1\}\). Also let
\[
p_{0,1}=1,
\qquad
p_{0,j}=0 \quad (j>1).
\]

\paragraph{(1) \hfill [7 pts]}
Let \(T_i\) be the hitting time to state \(i\). Compute \(\mathbb E_0[T_0]\).

\textbf{Answer:}
Since the chain is irreducible,
\[
\mathbb E_0[T_0]=\frac{1}{\pi_0},
\]
where \(\pi\) is the stationary distribution.

Using detailed balance,
\[
\pi_i p_{i,i+1}=\pi_{i+1}p_{i+1,i}.
\]
First,
\[
\pi_0\cdot 1=\pi_1\cdot \frac34
\quad \Rightarrow \quad
\pi_1=\frac43\pi_0.
\]
For \(i\ge 1\),
\[
\pi_i\frac{i}{2(i+1)}
=
\pi_{i+1}\frac{i+3}{2(i+2)}
\quad \Rightarrow \quad
\pi_{i+1}
=
\pi_i\frac{i(i+2)}{(i+1)(i+3)}.
\]
Hence, for \(n\ge 1\),
\[
\pi_n
=
\pi_1\prod_{k=1}^{n-1}\frac{k(k+2)}{(k+1)(k+3)}
=
\frac43\pi_0
\prod_{k=1}^{n-1}\frac{k}{k+1}\cdot\frac{k+2}{k+3}
=
\pi_0\frac{4}{n(n+2)}.
\]
Normalize:
\[
1
=
\sum_{n=0}^\infty \pi_n
=
\pi_0+\sum_{n=1}^\infty \pi_0\frac{4}{n(n+2)}
=
\pi_0\left(1+4\sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{1}{n(n+2)}\right).
\]
Since
\[
\frac{1}{n(n+2)}=\frac12\left(\frac1n-\frac{1}{n+2}\right),
\]
we get
\[
\sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{1}{n(n+2)}=\frac34.
\]
So
\[
1=\pi_0(1+4\cdot \tfrac34)=4\pi_0,
\qquad
\pi_0=\frac14.
\]
Therefore,
\[
\mathbb E_0[T_0]=\frac{1}{\pi_0}=4.
\]

\textbf{Rubrics:}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item \(2\) points for realizing \(\mathbb E_0[T_0]=1/\pi_0\).
    \item \(5\) points for computing \(\pi_0\) correctly.
    \item Minor calculation errors: deduct \(1\) point.
    \item If you get only a stationary measure but do not normalize it, you can get \(3\) of the \(5\) computation points.
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{(2) \hfill [8 pts]}
Compute
\[
\mathbb E_0\left[\sum_{t=1}^{T_0}\mathbf 1_{\{X_t=1\}}\right].
\]

\textbf{Answer:}
By the stationary-measure construction from lecture,
\[
\mu_0(0)=1,
\qquad
\mu_0(i)=
\mathbb E_0\left[\sum_{t=1}^{T_0}\mathbf 1_{\{X_t=i\}}\right]
\quad (i\ge 1)
\]
defines a stationary measure.

Since the chain is irreducible and positive recurrent, normalizing \(\mu_0\) gives the unique stationary distribution:
\[
\tilde \mu(i)=\frac{\mu_0(i)}{\sum_{j\in S}\mu_0(j)}=\pi_i.
\]
Therefore,
\[
\mu_0(1)=\pi_1\sum_{j\in S}\mu_0(j)=\frac{\pi_1}{\pi_0}.
\]
Since
\[
\pi_1=\frac43\pi_0,
\]
we obtain
\[
\mathbb E_0\left[\sum_{t=1}^{T_0}\mathbf 1_{\{X_t=1\}}\right]
=
\mu_0(1)=\frac{\pi_1}{\pi_0}=\frac43.
\]

\textbf{Rubrics:}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item \(5\) points for correctly using the stationary measure construction.
    \item \(2\) points for correctly computing \(\pi_1/\pi_0\).
    \item \(1\) point for explaining uniqueness to conclude \(\tilde\mu=\pi\).
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Question 6 \hfill [12 points]}

During class, asymptotic convergence of Markov chains was proved using independent coupling. In this problem, the idea is extended to general coupling and explicit convergence rates.

Suppose we can construct a joint chain
\[
\{(X_n^{(1)},X_n^{(2)})\}_{n\ge 0},
\]
such that marginally \(\{X_n^{(1)}\}\) and \(\{X_n^{(2)}\}\) are both Markov chains with the same transition matrix \(P\) (but not necessarily independent). Suppose
\[
X_0^{(1)}=i
\qquad \text{and} \qquad
X_0^{(2)}\sim \pi,
\]
where \(\pi\) is the stationary distribution. Define the coupling time
\[
T=\inf\{n\ge 0:X_n^{(1)}=X_n^{(2)}\}.
\]

\paragraph{(1) \hfill [4 pts]}
Show that for any \(n\ge 0\),
\[
\sum_{j\in S}|p_{ij}^{(n)}-\pi_j|\le 2\mathbb P(T\ge n).
\]

\textbf{Hint:} For any two discrete distributions \(\mu,\nu\) on \(S\), and any coupling \((X,Y)\) of \(\mu,\nu\),
\[
\sum_{j\in S}|\mu_j-\nu_j|\le 2\mathbb P(X\ne Y).
\]

\textbf{Answer:}
Under the coupling,
\[
X_n^{(1)}\sim P^n(i,\cdot),
\qquad
X_n^{(2)}\sim \pi.
\]
Applying the hint,
\[
\sum_{j\in S}|p_{ij}^{(n)}-\pi_j|
\le
2\mathbb P(X_n^{(1)}\ne X_n^{(2)}).
\]
By the strong Markov property, after the first meeting time \(T\), we may modify the coupling so the chains move together forever:
\[
X_{T+k}^{(1)}=X_{T+k}^{(2)}
\qquad \text{for all } k\ge 0.
\]
Hence
\[
\mathbb P(X_n^{(1)}\ne X_n^{(2)})=\mathbb P(T\ge n),
\]
and therefore
\[
\sum_{j\in S}|p_{ij}^{(n)}-\pi_j|\le 2\mathbb P(T\ge n).
\]

\textbf{Rubrics:}
If you only apply the hint but do not explain why
\[
\mathbb P(X_n^{(1)}\ne X_n^{(2)})=\mathbb P(T\ge n),
\]
you get \(2\) points.

\paragraph{(2) \hfill [8 pts]}
Consider the concrete Markov chain on
\[
S=\{0,1\}^N
\]
for some positive integer \(N\): from the current state \(x=(x_1,\dots,x_N)\), choose an index \(i\) uniformly from \(\{1,\dots,N\}\), and update \(x_i\) to be \(0\) or \(1\) with probability \(1/2\) each, independently of its previous value. All other coordinates remain unchanged.

Let \(\pi\) be the stationary distribution of this Markov chain. Show that for any initial state \(x\in S\),
\[
\sum_{y\in S}|p_{xy}^{(n)}-\pi_y|
\le
2N\left(1-\frac{1}{N}\right)^n.
\]

\textbf{Answer:}
Construct a coupling as follows:
\[
X_0^{(1)}=x,
\qquad
X_0^{(2)}\sim \pi.
\]
At each step, choose the same coordinate \(i\) for both chains, and update the \(i\)-th coordinate of both chains to the same new value, \(0\) or \(1\), each with probability \(1/2\).

Then marginally both chains follow the transition matrix \(P\).

The chains have coupled once every coordinate has been updated at least once. So
\[
\mathbb P(T\ge n)
=
\mathbb P(\text{at least one coordinate is not updated in the first } n \text{ steps}).
\]
Using the union bound,
\[
\mathbb P(T\ge n)
\le
\sum_{i=1}^N
\mathbb P(\text{the } i\text{-th coordinate is not updated in the first } n \text{ steps})
=
N\left(1-\frac1N\right)^n.
\]
Applying part (1),
\[
\sum_{y\in S}|p_{xy}^{(n)}-\pi_y|
\le
2\mathbb P(T\ge n)
\le
2N\left(1-\frac1N\right)^n.
\]

\textbf{Rubrics:}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item Any other valid construction gets full credit.
    \item \(5\) points for constructing the coupling correctly.
    \item \(3\) points for computing the tail bound for \(T\).
    \item If your upper bound is weaker than the desired one, you may get \(1\) or \(2\) out of the \(3\) tail-bound points.
    \item A partially correct construction gets partial credit.
\end{itemize}

