\section{Lecture 5}

\subsection{An additional Markov chain topic: MCMC}

The lecture begins with an additional Markov chain topic: \emph{Markov chain Monte Carlo} (MCMC).

The goal is to sample from a target distribution \(\pi\) on a state space \(S\). For simplicity, assume \(S\) is discrete.

Typical motivations are:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item the state space \(S\) is extremely large or infinite;
    \item we only know \(\pi\) up to a normalizing constant, i.e.
    \[
    \pi(x)\propto f(x)
    \]
    for some known function \(f\).
\end{itemize}

Algorithmically, the idea is to construct a Markov chain \((X_t)_{t\ge 0}\) with:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item some initial distribution,
    \item irreducibility,
    \item aperiodicity,
    \item stationary distribution \(\pi\).
\end{itemize}

Then, under suitable assumptions,
\[
\mathbb P(X_t=j)\to \pi_j,
\]
and one also gets a law of large numbers for sample averages along the chain.

\subsection{Metropolis--Hastings algorithm}

Start with a proposal distribution
\[
q(x,\cdot)
\qquad \text{for each } x\in S.
\]

Define a new transition kernel by
\[
p(x,y)=\min\left\{q(x,y),\ q(y,x)\frac{\pi(y)}{\pi(x)}\right\},
\qquad x,y\in S.
\]

Operationally, when \(X_t=x\):
\begin{enumerate}[label=\arabic*.]
    \item sample \(Y_t\sim q(x,\cdot)\);
    \item set
    \[
    X_{t+1}=
    \begin{cases}
    Y_t, & \text{with probability }
    \min\left\{1,\frac{q(Y_t,x)\pi(Y_t)}{q(x,Y_t)\pi(x)}\right\},\\[0.8em]
    X_t, & \text{otherwise.}
    \end{cases}
    \]
\end{enumerate}

The key observation is the detailed balance identity:
\[
p(x,y)\pi(x)
=
\min\{q(x,y)\pi(x),\,q(y,x)\pi(y)\}
=
p(y,x)\pi(y).
\]
Thus \(p\) is reversible with respect to \(\pi\), and therefore \(\pi\) is a stationary distribution.

\begin{keyformula}
For Metropolis--Hastings,
\[
p(x,y)\pi(x)=p(y,x)\pi(y),
\]
so the chain is reversible with respect to \(\pi\).
\end{keyformula}

\subsection{Martingales: the main new topic}

The lecture then turns to martingales.

\begin{definition}[Martingale]
A stochastic process \((X_n)_{n\ge 0}\) is called a \emph{martingale} if:
\begin{enumerate}[label=(\roman*)]
    \item
    \[
    \mathbb E[|X_n|]<\infty
    \qquad \text{for all } n,
    \]
    \item
    \[
    \mathbb E[X_{n+1}\mid X_0,X_1,\dots,X_n]=X_n
    \qquad \text{for all } n.
    \]
\end{enumerate}
\end{definition}

A martingale need not be Markov. The conditional distribution of \(X_{n+1}\) may depend on the whole past \(X_0,\dots,X_n\); the martingale condition only says that the conditional mean is exactly the current value \(X_n\).

\subsection{Basic example: simple random walk}

Let
\[
X_n=\sum_{i=1}^n \varepsilon_i,
\]
where \(\varepsilon_i\) are i.i.d. random variables satisfying
\[
\mathbb P(\varepsilon_i=1)=\mathbb P(\varepsilon_i=-1)=\frac12.
\]
Then \((X_n)_{n\ge 0}\) is a martingale.

Indeed,
\[
\mathbb E[|X_n|]\le \sum_{i=1}^n \mathbb E[|\varepsilon_i|]\le n<\infty,
\]
and
\[
\mathbb E[X_{n+1}\mid X_0,\dots,X_n]
=
\mathbb E[X_n+\varepsilon_{n+1}\mid X_0,\dots,X_n]
=
X_n+\mathbb E[\varepsilon_{n+1}]
=
X_n.
\]

More generally, if
\[
X_n=\sum_{i=1}^n Y_i,
\]
where \(Y_i\) are i.i.d., \(\mathbb E[|Y_i|]<\infty\), and \(\mathbb E[Y_i]=0\), then \((X_n)\) is a martingale.

\subsection{A corrected martingale}

For the one-dimensional simple random walk, the process \((X_n^2)_{n\ge 0}\) is not a martingale, but a corrected version is.

Define
\[
M_n=X_n^2-n.
\]

The idea is that \(X_n^2\) grows on average like \(n\), so subtracting \(n\) removes the drift.

First,
\[
\mathbb E[M_n]=\mathbb E[X_n^2]-n=0.
\]
Also,
\[
\mathbb E[|M_n|]\le \mathbb E[X_n^2]+n\le 2n<\infty.
\]

Now compute:
\[
\mathbb E[M_{n+1}\mid X_0,\dots,X_n]
=
\mathbb E\!\left[(X_n+\varepsilon_{n+1})^2-(n+1)\mid X_0,\dots,X_n\right].
\]
Expanding,
\[
=
X_n^2+2X_n\mathbb E[\varepsilon_{n+1}\mid X_0,\dots,X_n]
+\mathbb E[\varepsilon_{n+1}^2]-(n+1).
\]
Since \(\mathbb E[\varepsilon_{n+1}]=0\) and \(\varepsilon_{n+1}^2=1\),
\[
\mathbb E[M_{n+1}\mid X_0,\dots,X_n]
=
X_n^2+1-(n+1)=X_n^2-n=M_n.
\]

So \((M_n)_{n\ge 0}\) is a martingale.

\begin{keyformula}
For a one-dimensional symmetric simple random walk,
\[
M_n=X_n^2-n
\]
is a martingale.
\end{keyformula}

\subsection{Filtrations and notation}

Given a stochastic process \((X_n)_{n\ge 0}\), define
\[
\mathcal F_n=\sigma(X_0,X_1,\dots,X_n),
\]
the information contained in the process up to time \(n\).

We often write
\[
\mathbb E[X_{n+1}\mid \mathcal F_n]
\]
as shorthand for
\[
\mathbb E[X_{n+1}\mid X_0,X_1,\dots,X_n].
\]

A useful fact is that if \((X_n)\) is a martingale, then for \(0\le m<n\),
\[
\mathbb E[X_n\mid \mathcal F_m]=X_m.
\]
In particular, taking \(m=0\),
\[
\mathbb E[X_n]=\mathbb E[X_0].
\]

\begin{proof}[Idea]
For example,
\[
\mathbb E[X_{n+2}\mid X_0,\dots,X_n]
=
\mathbb E\!\left[\mathbb E[X_{n+2}\mid X_0,\dots,X_{n+1}] \mid X_0,\dots,X_n\right]
=
\mathbb E[X_{n+1}\mid X_0,\dots,X_n]
=
X_n.
\]
Then continue by induction.
\end{proof}

\subsection{A warning: optional evaluation is subtle}

A major theme for the next few lectures is that
\[
\mathbb E[X_T]\neq \mathbb E[X_0]
\]
in general if \(T\) is a random time depending on the process.

For example, let \((X_n)\) be a simple random walk and define
\[
T=\operatorname*{arg\,max}_{0\le t\le 100} X_t.
\]
Then one can show
\[
\mathbb E[X_T]>0.
\]
The problem is that at time \(65\), say, we do not know whether \(T=65\); we only know the value of \(T\) after observing the whole path up to time \(100\).

So we need a class of random times for which stopping is legitimate.

\subsection{Stopping times}

\begin{definition}[Stopping time, discrete time]
A nonnegative integer-valued random variable \(T\) is called a \emph{stopping time} if for every \(n=0,1,2,\dots\), the event
\[
\{T=n\}
\]
is determined by \(X_0,X_1,\dots,X_n\), equivalently measurable with respect to \(\mathcal F_n\).
\end{definition}

In continuous time, the corresponding definition is: \(T\) is a stopping time if for every \(t\ge 0\), the event
\[
\{T\le t\}
\]
is determined by \((X_s)_{0\le s\le t}\).

\subsection{Examples of stopping times}

Examples include:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item any deterministic time;
    \item hitting times, e.g.
    \[
    T=\inf\{t\ge 0:X_t=x\},
    \]
    or more generally
    \[
    T=\inf\{t\ge 0:X_t\in A\};
    \]
    \item the \(k\)-th visit time to a state \(x\), denoted \(T_x^{(k)}\).
\end{itemize}

An important non-example is
\[
T=\inf\{t\ge 2:X_{t+2}=5\}.
\]
This is not a stopping time, because deciding whether \(T=t\) requires information from the future.

If \(T_1\) and \(T_2\) are stopping times, then:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item \(\min(T_1,T_2)\) is a stopping time;
    \item \(\max(T_1,T_2)\) is a stopping time;
    \item \(T_1+T_2\) is a stopping time in discrete time.
\end{itemize}
But in general:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item \(T_1T_2\) need not be a stopping time;
    \item \(T_1-T_2\) need not be a stopping time, even if \(T_1\ge T_2\) almost surely.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Strong Markov property}

Recall the strong Markov property for Markov chains.

If \((X_n)_{n\ge 0}\) is a discrete-time Markov chain and \(T\) is a stopping time, then conditional on \(T=t\) and \(X_0,X_1,\dots,X_t\), the post-\(T\) process
\[
(X_n)_{n\ge T}
\]
behaves like a fresh Markov chain started from \(X_t\).

\subsection{Bounded optional stopping lemma}

We return to martingales.

A basic non-example is the simple random walk with
\[
T=\inf\{t\ge 0:X_t=5\}.
\]
Since simple random walk is recurrent,
\[
\mathbb P(T<\infty)=1.
\]
So
\[
X_T=5,
\qquad\text{hence}\qquad
\mathbb E[X_T]=5\neq \mathbb E[X_0]=0.
\]
The issue is that \(T\) is not bounded, and the process can wander very far before stopping.

The easy case is when \(T\) is bounded.

\begin{lemma}[Optional stopping, bounded case]
Let \((X_n)_{n\ge 0}\) be a martingale, and let \(T\) be a stopping time such that
\[
\mathbb P(T\le m)=1
\]
for some finite \(m\). Then
\[
\mathbb E[X_T]=\mathbb E[X_0].
\]
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
Write
\[
X_T-X_0=\sum_{k=1}^T (X_k-X_{k-1})
=
\sum_{k=1}^m (X_k-X_{k-1})\mathbf 1_{\{k\le T\}}.
\]
Taking expectations,
\[
\mathbb E[X_T]-\mathbb E[X_0]
=
\sum_{k=1}^m \mathbb E\big[(X_k-X_{k-1})\mathbf 1_{\{k\le T\}}\big].
\]
Now \(\mathbf 1_{\{k\le T\}}\) is determined by \(X_0,\dots,X_{k-1}\), so it is \(\mathcal F_{k-1}\)-measurable. Therefore,
\[
\mathbb E\big[(X_k-X_{k-1})\mathbf 1_{\{k\le T\}}\big]
=
\mathbb E\Big[\mathbf 1_{\{k\le T\}}\mathbb E[X_k-X_{k-1}\mid \mathcal F_{k-1}]\Big]
=0.
\]
Summing gives
\[
\mathbb E[X_T]=\mathbb E[X_0].
\]
\end{proof}

\subsection{A more general optional stopping theorem}

We now relax the boundedness assumption.

\begin{theorem}[Optional stopping theorem]
Let \((X_n)_{n\ge 0}\) be a martingale, and let \(T\) be a stopping time such that
\[
\mathbb P(T<\infty)=1.
\]
Assume:
\begin{enumerate}[label=(\roman*)]
    \item
    \[
    \mathbb E[|X_T|]<\infty,
    \]
    \item
    \[
    \lim_{n\to\infty}\mathbb E\big[|X_n|\mathbf 1_{\{T>n\}}\big]=0.
    \]
\end{enumerate}
Then
\[
\mathbb E[X_T]=\mathbb E[X_0].
\]
\end{theorem}

A useful corollary is the following: if \(\mathbb P(T<\infty)=1\) and there exists \(B>0\) such that
\[
\mathbb P\big(|X_n|\le B \text{ for all } n=0,1,\dots,T\big)=1,
\]
then OST holds.

Indeed:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item \(|X_T|\le B\), so \(\mathbb E[|X_T|]<\infty\);
    \item
    \[
    \mathbb E[|X_n|\mathbf 1_{\{T>n\}}]\le B\,\mathbb P(T>n)\to 0
    \]
    since \(\mathbb P(T<\infty)=1\).
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Proof idea of the general OST}

Define
\[
T_m=\min(T,m).
\]
Then \(T_m\) is a bounded stopping time, so by the bounded lemma,
\[
\mathbb E[X_{T_m}]=\mathbb E[X_0]
\qquad \text{for every } m.
\]

Now decompose:
\[
X_{T_m}=X_T\mathbf 1_{\{T\le m\}}+X_m\mathbf 1_{\{T>m\}},
\]
while
\[
X_T=X_T\mathbf 1_{\{T\le m\}}+X_T\mathbf 1_{\{T>m\}}.
\]
Hence
\[
|\mathbb E[X_{T_m}]-\mathbb E[X_T]|
\le
\mathbb E[|X_m|\mathbf 1_{\{T>m\}}]
+
\mathbb E[|X_T|\mathbf 1_{\{T>m\}}].
\]
The first term tends to \(0\) by assumption (ii). The second tends to \(0\) by dominated convergence, since \(|X_T|\) is integrable and \(\mathbf 1_{\{T>m\}}\to 0\) almost surely.

Therefore
\[
\mathbb E[X_{T_m}]\to \mathbb E[X_T].
\]
Since \(\mathbb E[X_{T_m}]=\mathbb E[X_0]\) for every \(m\), we conclude
\[
\mathbb E[X_T]=\mathbb E[X_0].
\]

\subsection{Application: gambler's ruin}

Consider the simple random walk
\[
X_{n+1}=X_n+\varepsilon_{n+1},
\]
where
\[
\varepsilon_{n+1}=
\begin{cases}
1, & \text{with probability } \tfrac12,\\
-1, & \text{with probability } \tfrac12.
\end{cases}
\]
Let
\[
X_0=a\in[0,c],
\]
and define the hitting time
\[
T=\inf\{n\ge 0:X_n\in\{0,c\}\}.
\]

\subsection{Symmetric case}

Since \((X_n)\) is a martingale and \(|X_n|\le c\) up to time \(T\), OST applies:
\[
\mathbb E[X_T]=\mathbb E[X_0]=a.
\]
But
\[
X_T=
\begin{cases}
c, & \text{if } X_T=c,\\
0, & \text{if } X_T=0.
\end{cases}
\]
So
\[
a=\mathbb E[X_T]
=
c\,\mathbb P(X_T=c)+0\cdot \mathbb P(X_T=0).
\]
Hence
\[
\mathbb P(X_T=c)=\frac{a}{c}.
\]

\begin{keyformula}
For symmetric gambler's ruin,
\[
\mathbb P_a(\text{hit } c \text{ before } 0)=\frac{a}{c}.
\]
\end{keyformula}

\subsection{Asymmetric case}

Now suppose
\[
\varepsilon_n=
\begin{cases}
1, & \text{with probability } p,\\
-1, & \text{with probability } 1-p,
\end{cases}
\qquad p\neq \frac12.
\]

Construct the process
\[
Y_n=\left(\frac{1-p}{p}\right)^{X_n}.
\]
It is straightforward to verify that \((Y_n)\) is a martingale.

Since \(X_n\in[0,c]\) up to time \(T\), we have
\[
|Y_n|\le \max\left\{1,\left(\frac{1-p}{p}\right)^c\right\}
\qquad \text{up to time } T,
\]
so OST applies:
\[
\mathbb E[Y_T]=\mathbb E[Y_0]
=
\left(\frac{1-p}{p}\right)^a.
\]

But
\[
Y_T=
\left(\frac{1-p}{p}\right)^c \mathbf 1_{\{X_T=c\}}
+
1\cdot \mathbf 1_{\{X_T=0\}}.
\]
So
\[
\left(\frac{1-p}{p}\right)^a
=
\left(\frac{1-p}{p}\right)^c \mathbb P(X_T=c)
+
\mathbb P(X_T=0).
\]
Using
\[
\mathbb P(X_T=0)=1-\mathbb P(X_T=c),
\]
we solve for \(\mathbb P(X_T=c)\):
\[
\mathbb P(X_T=c)
=
\frac{1-\left(\frac{1-p}{p}\right)^a}
{1-\left(\frac{1-p}{p}\right)^c}.
\]

\begin{keyformula}
For asymmetric gambler's ruin with \(p\neq \tfrac12\),
\[
\mathbb P_a(\text{hit } c \text{ before } 0)
=
\frac{1-\left(\frac{1-p}{p}\right)^a}
{1-\left(\frac{1-p}{p}\right)^c}.
\]
\end{keyformula}

