\section{Lecture 6}

\subsection{Intuition: martingales as ``fair games''}

A central idea in this lecture is the notion of a \emph{fair gambling process}.
If we think of \(X_n\) as the amount of money we have after round \(n\), then the process is called a martingale if, given all information up to time \(n\), the expected amount at the next round is exactly the current amount.

So the game may fluctuate randomly, but on average there is no built-in drift upward or downward.

\subsection{Filtration and information available up to time \texorpdfstring{$n$}{n}}

To formalize the phrase ``given the past,'' we use a filtration.
For a process \((X_n)_{n\ge 0}\), define
\[
\mathcal F_n:=\sigma(X_0,X_1,\dots,X_n).
\]
This is the sigma-field generated by the observations up to time \(n\). Informally, \(\mathcal F_n\) represents all information available by time \(n\).

When the notes write things like
\[
\mathbb E[X_{n+1}\mid X_0,\dots,X_n],
\]
this is the same as writing
\[
\mathbb E[X_{n+1}\mid \mathcal F_n].
\]

\subsection{Definition of a martingale}

\begin{definition}[Martingale]
A real-valued stochastic process \((X_n)_{n\ge 0}\) adapted to \((\mathcal F_n)_{n\ge 0}\) is called a \emph{martingale} if for every \(n\ge 0\),
\begin{enumerate}[label=(\roman*)]
    \item \(\mathbb E[|X_n|]<\infty\), and
    \item
    \[
    \mathbb E[X_{n+1}\mid \mathcal F_n]=X_n.
    \]
\end{enumerate}
\end{definition}

So a martingale is exactly a process whose conditional expected next value equals its current value.

\begin{keyformula}
The martingale property is
\[
\mathbb E[X_{n+1}\mid \mathcal F_n]=X_n.
\]
Interpretation: after seeing the entire history up to time \(n\), the game is still fair.
\end{keyformula}

\subsection{First examples of martingales}

\begin{example}[Simple random walk]
Let
\[
X_n=\sum_{i=1}^n Z_i,
\qquad X_0=0,
\]
where the increments \(Z_i\) are i.i.d. with
\[
\mathbb P(Z_i=1)=\mathbb P(Z_i=-1)=\frac12.
\]
Then \((X_n)\) is the symmetric simple random walk on \(\mathbb Z\).

Since
\[
X_{n+1}=X_n+Z_{n+1}
\]
and \(Z_{n+1}\) is independent of \(\mathcal F_n\) with mean zero, we get
\[
\mathbb E[X_{n+1}\mid \mathcal F_n]
=
\mathbb E[X_n+Z_{n+1}\mid \mathcal F_n]
=
X_n+\mathbb E[Z_{n+1}]
=
X_n.
\]
Hence \((X_n)\) is a martingale.
\end{example}

\begin{example}[Partial sums of mean-zero i.i.d. variables]
More generally, if \((Y_i)_{i\ge 1}\) are i.i.d. random variables satisfying
\[
\mathbb E[|Y_1|]<\infty,
\qquad
\mathbb E[Y_1]=0,
\]
and we define
\[
X_n:=\sum_{i=1}^n Y_i,
\qquad X_0=0,
\]
then \((X_n)\) is a martingale.

Indeed,
\[
\mathbb E[X_{n+1}\mid \mathcal F_n]
=
\mathbb E[X_n+Y_{n+1}\mid \mathcal F_n]
=
X_n+\mathbb E[Y_{n+1}]
=
X_n.
\]
\end{example}

The message is: sums of independent mean-zero increments naturally produce martingales.

\subsection[A useful derived martingale: Xn2 - n]{A useful derived martingale: \texorpdfstring{$X_n^2-n$}{Xn2 - n}}

For the symmetric simple random walk, the process \((X_n^2)\) itself is \emph{not} a martingale, but it becomes one after subtracting a deterministic correction term.

Let \((X_n)\) be the simple random walk, so that
\[
X_{n+1}=X_n+Z_{n+1},
\qquad Z_{n+1}\in\{-1,1\},
\qquad \mathbb E[Z_{n+1}]=0.
\]
Then
\[
X_{n+1}^2=(X_n+Z_{n+1})^2=X_n^2+2X_nZ_{n+1}+Z_{n+1}^2.
\]
Conditioning on \(\mathcal F_n\),
\[
\mathbb E[X_{n+1}^2\mid \mathcal F_n]
=
X_n^2+2X_n\mathbb E[Z_{n+1}\mid \mathcal F_n]+\mathbb E[Z_{n+1}^2\mid \mathcal F_n].
\]
Because \(Z_{n+1}\) is independent of \(\mathcal F_n\), has mean zero, and satisfies \(Z_{n+1}^2=1\), this becomes
\[
\mathbb E[X_{n+1}^2\mid \mathcal F_n]=X_n^2+1.
\]
Therefore
\[
\mathbb E[X_{n+1}^2-(n+1)\mid \mathcal F_n]=X_n^2-n.
\]
So we obtain the following.

\begin{proposition}
If \((X_n)\) is a symmetric simple random walk, then
\[
M_n:=X_n^2-n
\]
is a martingale.
\end{proposition}

This is one of the most important examples in the lecture, because it will later be combined with optional stopping to compute expected hitting times.

\subsection{Conditioning further back in time}

The martingale property is usually stated one step at a time, but it automatically implies a more general identity.

\begin{proposition}
If \((X_n)\) is a martingale, then for every \(0\le m<n\),
\[
\mathbb E[X_n\mid \mathcal F_m]=X_m.
\]
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
Apply the tower property repeatedly:
\[
\mathbb E[X_n\mid \mathcal F_m]
=
\mathbb E\bigl[\mathbb E[X_n\mid \mathcal F_{n-1}]\mid \mathcal F_m\bigr]
=
\mathbb E[X_{n-1}\mid \mathcal F_m].
\]
Continuing backward one step at a time gives
\[
\mathbb E[X_n\mid \mathcal F_m]=X_m.
\]
\end{proof}

So once a process is a martingale, its conditional expectation at any future time, given present information, is just the current value.

\subsection{Stopping times}

The next topic is random times at which we decide to stop observing the process.
The key point is that the decision to stop must depend only on information available \emph{up to that time}.

\begin{definition}[Stopping time]
A nonnegative integer-valued random variable \(T\) is called a \emph{stopping time} with respect to \((\mathcal F_n)\) if for every \(n\ge 0\),
\[
\{T=n\}\in \mathcal F_n.
\]
Equivalently, for every \(n\ge 0\), the event
\[
\{T\le n\}\in \mathcal F_n.
\]
\end{definition}

In words: by time \(n\), we can determine whether stopping has already occurred.

\begin{remark}
A stopping time is about whether we know \emph{now} that stopping has happened. We are not allowed to look into the future.
\end{remark}

\subsection{Examples and a non-example}

Assume \((X_n)\) is a process and \(\mathcal F_n=\sigma(X_0,\dots,X_n)\).

\begin{example}[Deterministic time]
For any fixed constant \(c\in \mathbb N\cup\{0\}\), the time
\[
T\equiv c
\]
is a stopping time.

This simply means: stop after the \(c\)-th round.
\end{example}

\begin{example}[Hitting times]
The following are stopping times:
\[
T=\inf\{t\ge 0:X_t=5\},
\qquad
T=\inf\{t\ge 0:|X_t|\ge 5\}.
\]
To decide whether \(T\le n\), we only need to inspect the path \(X_0,\dots,X_n\).
\end{example}

\begin{example}[Visit times]
If \(T_i^{(k)}\) denotes the time of the \(k\)-th visit to state \(i\), then \(T_i^{(k)}\) is also a stopping time.
\end{example}

\begin{example}[A shifted hitting time]
The time
\[
T=\inf\{t\ge 0:X_{t+2}=5\}
\]
is \emph{not} a stopping time.
To know whether \(T=n\), we would need information about \(X_{n+2}\), which is not available at time \(n\).
\end{example}

So the distinction is simple but important: stopping times are based on the past and present, not the future.

\subsection{Basic operations on stopping times}

If \(T_1\) and \(T_2\) are stopping times, then the following are again stopping times:
\[
\min(T_1,T_2),
\qquad
\max(T_1,T_2),
\qquad
T_1+T_2.
\]
In discrete time, one may also check that products such as \(T_1T_2\) are stopping times.

However, even if \(T_1\ge T_2\), the difference
\[
T_1-T_2
\]
need \emph{not} be a stopping time in general.

So stopping times are stable under some natural operations, but not under all algebraic manipulations.

\subsection{Why optional stopping is not automatically true}

A first guess might be:
\begin{quote}
If \((X_n)\) is a martingale and \(T\) is a stopping time, then perhaps
\(\mathbb E[X_T]=\mathbb E[X_0]\).
\end{quote}
This is the optional stopping principle. But it is \emph{not} always true without extra assumptions.

\begin{example}[Counterexample]
Let \((X_n)\) be a symmetric simple random walk starting from \(0\), and define
\[
T:=\inf\{t\ge 0:X_t=5\}.
\]
Since simple random walk on \(\mathbb Z\) is recurrent,
\[
\mathbb P(T<\infty)=1.
\]
But by definition,
\[
X_T=5
\qquad \text{a.s.}
\]
Therefore
\[
\mathbb E[X_T]=5\neq 0=\mathbb E[X_0].
\]
So optional stopping fails in this case.
\end{example}

This shows that some additional structure is needed.

\subsection{Optional stopping in the bounded-time case}

The easiest valid version is the case where the stopping time is bounded by a deterministic constant.

\begin{lemma}[Optional stopping for bounded stopping times]
Let \((X_n)_{n\ge 0}\) be a martingale, and let \(T\) be a stopping time such that
\[
\mathbb P(T\le m)=1
\]
for some deterministic constant \(m\ge 0\). Then
\[
\mathbb E[X_T]=\mathbb E[X_0].
\]
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
Since \(T\le m\) almost surely,
\[
X_T-X_0=\sum_{k=1}^m (X_k-X_{k-1})\mathbf 1_{\{k\le T\}}.
\]
Taking expectations,
\[
\mathbb E[X_T]-\mathbb E[X_0]
=
\sum_{k=1}^m \mathbb E\bigl[(X_k-X_{k-1})\mathbf 1_{\{k\le T\}}\bigr].
\]
Now note that
\[
\{k\le T\}=\{T\ge k\}=\{T\le k-1\}^c\in \mathcal F_{k-1},
\]
so \(\mathbf 1_{\{k\le T\}}\) is \(\mathcal F_{k-1}\)-measurable. Hence
\[
\mathbb E\bigl[(X_k-X_{k-1})\mathbf 1_{\{k\le T\}}\bigr]
=
\mathbb E\Bigl[\mathbf 1_{\{k\le T\}}\,\mathbb E[X_k-X_{k-1}\mid \mathcal F_{k-1}]\Bigr].
\]
Because \((X_n)\) is a martingale,
\[
\mathbb E[X_k-X_{k-1}\mid \mathcal F_{k-1}]=0.
\]
So each summand is zero, and therefore
\[
\mathbb E[X_T]=\mathbb E[X_0].
\]
\end{proof}

The idea is elegant: stop the telescoping sum at a bounded horizon, and use the fact that the indicator of ``not yet stopped'' is known one step before the increment occurs.

\subsection{A more general optional stopping theorem}

The lecture then proves a more flexible version by truncating the stopping time.

\begin{theorem}[Optional stopping theorem]
Let \((X_n)_{n\ge 0}\) be a martingale and let \(T\) be a stopping time such that:
\begin{enumerate}[label=(\roman*)]
    \item \(\mathbb P(T<\infty)=1\);
    \item \(\mathbb E[|X_T|]<\infty\);
    \item
    \[
    \lim_{n\to\infty}\mathbb E\bigl[|X_n|\mathbf 1_{\{T>n\}}\bigr]=0.
    \]
\end{enumerate}
Then
\[
\mathbb E[X_T]=\mathbb E[X_0].
\]
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}[Idea of proof by truncation]
For each \(m\ge 0\), define the truncated stopping time
\[
T_m:=\min(T,m)=T\wedge m.
\]
Then \(T_m\le m\) almost surely, so by the bounded-time lemma,
\[
\mathbb E[X_{T_m}]=\mathbb E[X_0].
\]
Thus it remains to show that \(X_{T_m}\to X_T\) in \(L^1\).

Now split according to whether \(T\le m\) or \(T>m\):
\[
X_{T_m}=X_T\mathbf 1_{\{T\le m\}}+X_m\mathbf 1_{\{T>m\}},
\]
while
\[
X_T=X_T\mathbf 1_{\{T\le m\}}+X_T\mathbf 1_{\{T>m\}}.
\]
Therefore
\[
X_{T_m}-X_T=(X_m-X_T)\mathbf 1_{\{T>m\}},
\]
and hence
\[
\mathbb E[|X_{T_m}-X_T|]
\le
\mathbb E[|X_m|\mathbf 1_{\{T>m\}}]
+
\mathbb E[|X_T|\mathbf 1_{\{T>m\}}].
\]
The first term tends to \(0\) by assumption (iii).

For the second term, because \(\mathbb P(T<\infty)=1\), we have
\[
\mathbf 1_{\{T>m\}}\to 0
\qquad \text{a.s.}
\]
as \(m\to\infty\). Since \(|X_T|\) is integrable by assumption (ii), the dominated convergence theorem gives
\[
\mathbb E[|X_T|\mathbf 1_{\{T>m\}}]\to 0.
\]
Thus
\[
\mathbb E[|X_{T_m}-X_T|]\to 0.
\]
So \(X_{T_m}\to X_T\) in \(L^1\), and consequently
\[
\mathbb E[X_T]=\lim_{m\to\infty}\mathbb E[X_{T_m}]=\mathbb E[X_0].
\]
\end{proof}

\subsection{A very useful special case}

The theorem becomes easy to apply when the process is uniformly bounded before the stopping time.

\begin{proposition}[A useful bounded-before-stopping criterion]
Let \((X_n)\) be a martingale and let \(T\) be a stopping time such that
\[
\mathbb P(T<\infty)=1.
\]
Assume there exists a constant \(C<\infty\) such that for all \(n<T\),
\[
|X_n|\le C.
\]
Then
\[
\mathbb E[X_T]=\mathbb E[X_0].
\]
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
On \(\{T>n\}\) we have \(n<T\), so
\[
|X_n|\mathbf 1_{\{T>n\}}\le C\mathbf 1_{\{T>n\}}.
\]
Hence
\[
\mathbb E[|X_n|\mathbf 1_{\{T>n\}}]
\le
C\,\mathbb P(T>n)\to 0,
\]
because \(\mathbb P(T<\infty)=1\).
Also,
\[
|X_T|\le C
\]
in the hitting-time examples treated below, so \(X_T\) is integrable. Thus the theorem applies.
\end{proof}

This bounded-before-stopping criterion is exactly what we need for gambler's ruin.

\subsection{Gambler's ruin revisited: symmetric case}

Consider the simple random walk
\[
X_{n+1}=X_n+\varepsilon_{n+1},
\qquad
\mathbb P(\varepsilon_{n+1}=1)=\mathbb P(\varepsilon_{n+1}=-1)=\frac12,
\]
with starting point
\[
X_0=a,\qquad 0<a<c.
\]
Define the stopping time
\[
T:=\inf\{t\ge 0:X_t=0\ \text{or}\ X_t=c\}.
\]
So \(T\) is the first time the walk hits either boundary \(0\) or \(c\).

Because the state space between the boundaries is finite, \(T<\infty\) almost surely. Also, for every \(n<T\),
\[
0<X_n<c,
\qquad \text{hence in particular } |X_n|\le c.
\]
So optional stopping applies to the martingale \((X_n)\):
\[
\mathbb E[X_T]=\mathbb E[X_0]=a.
\]
But at time \(T\), the process must be at one of the two endpoints, so
\[
X_T\in\{0,c\}.
\]
Therefore
\[
\mathbb E[X_T]=0\cdot \mathbb P(X_T=0)+c\cdot \mathbb P(X_T=c)=c\,\mathbb P(X_T=c).
\]
Comparing with \(\mathbb E[X_T]=a\), we get:

\begin{proposition}[Symmetric gambler's ruin probability]
For symmetric gambler's ruin,
\[
\mathbb P(X_T=c)=\frac{a}{c},
\qquad
\mathbb P(X_T=0)=1-\frac{a}{c}=\frac{c-a}{c}.
\]
\end{proposition}

So in the symmetric case, the probability of reaching the upper boundary is just the starting position divided by the interval length.

\subsection{Gambler's ruin revisited: asymmetric case}

Now suppose
\[
\mathbb P(\varepsilon_{n+1}=1)=p,
\qquad
\mathbb P(\varepsilon_{n+1}=-1)=1-p,
\qquad p\ne \frac12.
\]
The process \((X_n)\) is no longer a martingale. So we need to construct a new martingale.

Set
\[
r:=\frac{1-p}{p},
\qquad
Y_n:=r^{X_n}.
\]
Then
\[
Y_{n+1}=r^{X_n+\varepsilon_{n+1}}=r^{X_n}r^{\varepsilon_{n+1}}.
\]
Conditioning on \(\mathcal F_n\),
\[
\mathbb E[Y_{n+1}\mid \mathcal F_n]
=
r^{X_n}\bigl(pr+(1-p)r^{-1}\bigr).
\]
Since \(r=(1-p)/p\),
\[
pr+(1-p)r^{-1}=p\cdot\frac{1-p}{p}+(1-p)\cdot\frac{p}{1-p}=1.
\]
Hence
\[
\mathbb E[Y_{n+1}\mid \mathcal F_n]=r^{X_n}=Y_n.
\]
So \((Y_n)\) is a martingale.

Up to time \(T\), the walk stays inside \([0,c]\), so
\[
|Y_n|=r^{X_n}\le \max(1,r^c)
\qquad \text{for } n<T.
\]
Therefore optional stopping applies:
\[
\mathbb E[Y_T]=\mathbb E[Y_0]=r^a.
\]
Since \(X_T\in\{0,c\}\), we obtain
\[
r^a=r^c\,\mathbb P(X_T=c)+1\cdot \mathbb P(X_T=0).
\]
Using
\[
\mathbb P(X_T=0)=1-\mathbb P(X_T=c),
\]
we solve for the upper-boundary probability.

\begin{proposition}[Asymmetric gambler's ruin probability]
If \(p\ne \tfrac12\), then with \(r=(1-p)/p\),
\[
\mathbb P(X_T=c)=\frac{r^a-1}{r^c-1}.
\]
Equivalently,
\[
\mathbb P(X_T=0)=\frac{r^c-r^a}{r^c-1}.
\]
\end{proposition}

When \(p=\tfrac12\), we recover the symmetric formula \(a/c\).

\subsection{Expected duration of gambler's ruin}

The next question is: how long does the game last on average in the symmetric case?

Return to the symmetric walk and the stopping time
\[
T:=\inf\{t\ge 0:X_t=0\ \text{or}\ X_t=c\},
\qquad X_0=a.
\]
We already know that
\[
M_n:=X_n^2-n
\]
is a martingale.

If we apply optional stopping to \((M_n)\), we get
\[
\mathbb E[M_T]=\mathbb E[M_0]=a^2.
\]
That is,
\[
a^2=\mathbb E[X_T^2-T]=\mathbb E[X_T^2]-\mathbb E[T].
\]
Now \(X_T\in\{0,c\}\), so
\[
X_T^2=c^2\mathbf 1_{\{X_T=c\}}.
\]
Therefore
\[
\mathbb E[X_T^2]=c^2\mathbb P(X_T=c)=c^2\cdot \frac{a}{c}=ac.
\]
Substituting into the previous identity yields
\[
a^2=ac-\mathbb E[T].
\]
So:

\begin{proposition}[Expected duration of symmetric gambler's ruin]
For the symmetric walk started at \(a\in\{0,1,\dots,c\}\),
\[
\mathbb E[T]=a(c-a).
\]
\end{proposition}

\begin{remark}
To justify this application of optional stopping carefully, one checks that the assumptions of the theorem hold for the martingale \(M_n=X_n^2-n\). The main point is that in gambler's ruin the hitting time \(T\) has finite expectation, and on \(\{T>n\}\) we have
\[
|M_n|=|X_n^2-n|\le c^2+n.
\]
Then
\[
\mathbb E[|M_n|\mathbf 1_{\{T>n\}}]
\le
c^2\mathbb P(T>n)+\mathbb E[T\mathbf 1_{\{T>n\}}]\to 0,
\]
which is enough for optional stopping.
\end{remark}

\subsection{What this lecture is really teaching}

Lecture 6 introduces a standard strategy that appears throughout probability:
\begin{enumerate}[label=\arabic*.]
    \item identify a martingale;
    \item choose a meaningful stopping time;
    \item verify optional stopping can be applied;
    \item read off probabilities or expectations from the stopped value.
\end{enumerate}

This method turns conditional-expectation identities into concrete formulas for hitting probabilities and expected stopping times.

\begin{keyformula}
The core workflow is:
\[
\text{martingale} + \text{stopping time} + \text{OST} \Longrightarrow \text{explicit information about the process}.
\]
In Lecture 6, this is used to solve gambler's ruin.
\end{keyformula}

\subsection{Summary}

\begin{summarybox}
Lecture 6 develops the martingale-and-stopping-time toolkit.

Main points:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item A martingale satisfies
    \[
    \mathbb E[X_{n+1}\mid \mathcal F_n]=X_n.
    \]
    \item Sums of i.i.d. mean-zero increments are martingales.
    \item For simple random walk, \(X_n^2-n\) is also a martingale.
    \item A stopping time is a random time determined only by present and past information.
    \item Optional stopping is \emph{not} automatic; it needs hypotheses.
    \item If \(T\) is bounded, then
    \[
    \mathbb E[X_T]=\mathbb E[X_0].
    \]
    \item A more general optional stopping theorem follows by truncation.
    \item Applying OST to gambler's ruin gives:
    \[
    \mathbb P(X_T=c)=\frac{a}{c}
    \quad \text{in the symmetric case,}
    \]
    and in the asymmetric case,
    \[
    \mathbb P(X_T=c)=\frac{r^a-1}{r^c-1},
    \qquad r=\frac{1-p}{p}.
    \]
    \item Applying OST to \(X_n^2-n\) yields the expected duration formula
    \[
    \mathbb E[T]=a(c-a)
    \]
    for symmetric gambler's ruin.
\end{itemize}
\end{summarybox}

