\section{Lecture 7}

\subsection{Recall: the optional stopping theorem}

We begin by recalling the discrete-time optional stopping theorem from the previous lecture.

\begin{theorem}[Optional stopping theorem]
Let \((X_n)_{n\ge 0}\) be a martingale and let \(T\) be a stopping time. Assume:
\begin{enumerate}[label=(\roman*)]
    \item
    \[
    \mathbb E[|X_T|]<\infty;
    \]
    \item
    \[
    \mathbb E\bigl[|X_n|\mathbf 1_{\{T>n\}}\bigr]\to 0
    \qquad \text{as } n\to\infty.
    \]
\end{enumerate}
Then
\[
\mathbb E[X_T]=\mathbb E[X_0].
\]
\end{theorem}

Two useful special cases are worth remembering:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item if \(T\) is bounded, then OST is easy to apply;
    \item if the stopped martingale is uniformly bounded, then the tail condition is automatic.
\end{itemize}

Lecture 7 starts by revisiting this theorem and showing how to verify the tail condition in situations where neither of these easy special cases applies.

\subsection{Application: expected duration in gambler's ruin}

Consider the symmetric gambler's ruin chain on
\[
\{0,1,2,\dots,c\},
\]
started from
\[
X_0=a, \qquad 0<a<c,
\]
and let
\[
T=\inf\{n\ge 0:X_n\in\{0,c\}\}
\]
be the absorption time.

From the previous lecture we already know two facts:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item \((X_n)\) is a martingale;
    \item in the symmetric case,
    \[
    M_n:=X_n^2-n
    \]
    is also a martingale.
\end{itemize}

If OST applies to \((M_n)\) at time \(T\), then
\[
\mathbb E[M_T]=\mathbb E[M_0].
\]
Since \(X_T\in\{0,c\}\), we get
\[
\mathbb E[X_T^2]-\mathbb E[T]=a^2.
\]
Also,
\[
\mathbb P(X_T=c)=\frac{a}{c},
\qquad
\mathbb P(X_T=0)=1-\frac{a}{c},
\]
so
\[
\mathbb E[X_T^2]=c^2\cdot \frac{a}{c}=ac.
\]
Therefore,
\[
\mathbb E[T]=ac-a^2=a(c-a).
\]

\begin{keyformula}
For symmetric gambler's ruin started from \(a\in\{1,\dots,c-1\}\),
\[
\mathbb E[T]=a(c-a).
\]
\end{keyformula}

So the only real issue is to justify OST carefully.

\subsection{Why the easy OST cases do not apply here}

For the martingale
\[
M_n=X_n^2-n,
\]
we would like to use OST at the terminal time \(T\).

However:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item the stopping time \(T\) is not obviously bounded;
    \item the martingale \((M_n)\) is not uniformly bounded, because of the \(-n\) term.
\end{itemize}

So neither of the standard quick checks works. We must go back to the original tail condition
\[
\mathbb E\bigl[|M_n|\mathbf 1_{\{T>n\}}\bigr]\to 0.
\]

\subsection{Checking the OST tail condition directly}

On the event \(\{T>n\}\), the walk has not yet hit \(0\) or \(c\), so
\[
0\le X_n\le c.
\]
Hence
\[
|M_n|=|X_n^2-n|\le c^2+n
\qquad \text{on } \{T>n\}.
\]
Therefore
\[
\mathbb E\bigl[|M_n|\mathbf 1_{\{T>n\}}\bigr]
\le
(c^2+n)\,\mathbb P(T>n).
\]

So it is enough to show that
\[
(c^2+n)\mathbb P(T>n)\to 0.
\]
A mere proof that \(\mathbb P(T>n)\to 0\) is not enough; we need a quantitative decay rate, roughly faster than \(1/n\).

\subsection{Exponential tail bound for hitting times on a finite state space}

The lecture proves a more general fact for finite-state Markov chains.

\begin{proposition}[Exponential tail bound for hitting times]
Let \((X_n)\) be a Markov chain on a finite state space \(S\), and let \(A\subseteq S\) be a target set. Suppose that from every starting state \(i\in S\), the chain can hit \(A\) with positive probability in finitely many steps. If
\[
T_A=\inf\{n\ge 0:X_n\in A\},
\]
then there exist constants \(C>0\) and \(\rho\in(0,1)\) such that
\[
\mathbb P_i(T_A>n)\le C\rho^n
\qquad \text{for all } n\ge 0 \text{ and all } i\in S.
\]
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}[Idea from the notes]
For each state \(i\in S\), choose an integer \(n_i\ge 1\) such that
\[
q_i:=\mathbb P_i(T_A\le n_i)>0.
\]
Because \(S\) is finite, we may define
\[
n:=\max_{i\in S} n_i,
\qquad
q:=\min_{i\in S} q_i>0.
\]
Then starting from any state \(i\),
\[
\mathbb P_i(T_A\le n)\ge q.
\]
Equivalently,
\[
\mathbb P_i(T_A>n)\le 1-q.
\]

Now split time into blocks of length \(n\). After each unsuccessful block, regardless of the current state, the chance of success in the next block is still at least \(q\). Therefore
\[
\mathbb P_i(T_A>mn)\le (1-q)^m
\qquad (m\ge 1).
\]
This gives exponential decay on the subsequence \(mn\), and hence also for every integer time after adjusting the constants.
\end{proof}

For gambler's ruin, the state space is finite, so this proposition applies to the absorption time \(T\). Thus
\[
\mathbb P(T>n)\le C\rho^n
\qquad \text{for some } \rho\in(0,1).
\]

\subsection{Completing the OST check for gambler's ruin}

Using the exponential tail bound,
\[
\mathbb E\bigl[|M_n|\mathbf 1_{\{T>n\}}\bigr]
\le
(c^2+n)\mathbb P(T>n)
\le
(c^2+n)C\rho^n
\to 0.
\]
Since also \(\mathbb E[|M_T|]<\infty\), the optional stopping theorem applies, and we conclude again that
\[
\mathbb E[T]=a(c-a).
\]

So the lecture's first message is that OST is extremely powerful, but it must be justified with care.

\subsection{Motivation for uniform integrability}

The tail condition in OST has the form
\[
\mathbb E\bigl[|X_n|\mathbf 1_{\{T>n\}}\bigr]\to 0.
\]
This resembles a basic probability fact for a \emph{single} integrable random variable \(X\): if \(A_n\) is a sequence of events with
\[
\mathbb P(A_n)\to 0
\qquad \text{and} \qquad
\mathbb E[|X|]<\infty,
\]
then
\[
\mathbb E\bigl[|X|\mathbf 1_{A_n}\bigr]\to 0.
\]

The lecture asks for a version of this principle that works \emph{uniformly} over a whole sequence \((X_n)\). This leads to the notion of uniform integrability.

\subsection{Definition of uniform integrability}

\begin{definition}[Uniform integrability]
A sequence of integrable random variables \((X_n)_{n\ge 0}\) is called \emph{uniformly integrable} if for every \(\varepsilon>0\) there exists \(K>0\) such that
\[
\mathbb E\bigl[|X_n|\mathbf 1_{\{|X_n|>K\}}\bigr]\le \varepsilon
\qquad \text{for all } n.
\]
\end{definition}

The important point is that the same cutoff \(K\) must work for \emph{every} \(n\).

\begin{remark}
Uniform integrability is much stronger than the statement that for each fixed \(n\),
\[
\mathbb E\bigl[|X_n|\mathbf 1_{\{|X_n|>K\}}\bigr]\to 0
\qquad \text{as } K\to\infty.
\]
That latter fact is automatic for a single integrable random variable. Uniform integrability asks for a bound that is simultaneous in \(n\).
\end{remark}

\subsection{Uniform integrability gives the OST tail condition}

\begin{theorem}
Let \((X_n)_{n\ge 0}\) be a uniformly integrable sequence, and let \(T\) be a stopping time such that
\[
\mathbb P(T<\infty)=1
\qquad \text{and} \qquad
\mathbb E[|X_T|]<\infty.
\]
Then
\[
\mathbb E\bigl[|X_n|\mathbf 1_{\{T>n\}}\bigr]\to 0.
\]
Consequently, if \((X_n)\) is a martingale, then the OST tail condition is satisfied.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
Let
\[
A_n:=\{T>n\}.
\]
Then \(\mathbb P(A_n)\to 0\) because \(T<\infty\) almost surely.

Fix \(\varepsilon>0\). By uniform integrability, choose \(K=K_\varepsilon\) such that
\[
\mathbb E\bigl[|X_n|\mathbf 1_{\{|X_n|>K\}}\bigr]\le \varepsilon
\qquad \text{for all } n.
\]
Now split according to whether \(|X_n|\le K\) or \(|X_n|>K\):
\[
\mathbb E\bigl[|X_n|\mathbf 1_{A_n}\bigr]
=
\mathbb E\bigl[|X_n|\mathbf 1_{A_n\cap\{|X_n|\le K\}}\bigr]
+
\mathbb E\bigl[|X_n|\mathbf 1_{A_n\cap\{|X_n|>K\}}\bigr].
\]
Hence
\[
\mathbb E\bigl[|X_n|\mathbf 1_{A_n}\bigr]
\le
K\mathbb P(A_n)
+
\mathbb E\bigl[|X_n|\mathbf 1_{\{|X_n|>K\}}\bigr]
\le
K\mathbb P(A_n)+\varepsilon.
\]
Taking \(n\to\infty\), we obtain
\[
\limsup_{n\to\infty}
\mathbb E\bigl[|X_n|\mathbf 1_{A_n}\bigr]
\le \varepsilon.
\]
Since \(\varepsilon>0\) was arbitrary, the limit is \(0\).
\end{proof}

\begin{remark}
In applications to optional stopping, it is enough to know that the stopped family
\[
(X_{n\wedge T})_{n\ge 0}
\]
is uniformly integrable.
\end{remark}

\subsection{A very useful sufficient condition: uniform \texorpdfstring{$L^2$}{L2}-bounds}

\begin{corollary}
If there exists a constant \(C<\infty\) such that
\[
\mathbb E[|X_n|^2]\le C
\qquad \text{for all } n,
\]
then \((X_n)\) is uniformly integrable.
\end{corollary}

\begin{proof}
For any \(K>0\), Cauchy--Schwarz gives
\[
\mathbb E\bigl[|X_n|\mathbf 1_{\{|X_n|>K\}}\bigr]
\le
\sqrt{\mathbb E[X_n^2]}
\sqrt{\mathbb P(|X_n|>K)}.
\]
By Markov's inequality applied to \(X_n^2\),
\[
\mathbb P(|X_n|>K)
\le
\frac{\mathbb E[X_n^2]}{K^2}
\le
\frac{C}{K^2}.
\]
Therefore
\[
\mathbb E\bigl[|X_n|\mathbf 1_{\{|X_n|>K\}}\bigr]
\le
\sqrt{C}\sqrt{\frac{C}{K^2}}
=
\frac{C}{K}.
\]
Since the right-hand side does not depend on \(n\), we can make it smaller than any prescribed \(\varepsilon>0\) by choosing \(K\) large enough. So \((X_n)\) is uniformly integrable.
\end{proof}

\begin{remark}
A first-moment bound alone is \emph{not} enough to imply uniform integrability. The lecture specifically warns about this.
\end{remark}

\subsection{Example and non-example}

A useful example is
\[
X_n=\sum_{j=1}^n \frac{1}{j}Z_j,
\]
where \(Z_j\) are i.i.d. random variables taking values \(\pm 1\) with probability \(1/2\) each. Then
\[
\mathbb E[X_n^2]=\sum_{j=1}^n \frac{1}{j^2}
\le
\sum_{j=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{j^2}
=
\frac{\pi^2}{6}<\infty.
\]
So \((X_n)\) is uniformly integrable.

The notes also give a non-example. Let \((S_n)\) be the one-dimensional symmetric simple random walk, let
\[
T=\inf\{n\ge 0:S_n=-1\},
\]
and define
\[
Y_n=1+S_{n\wedge T}.
\]
Then \((Y_n)\) is a nonnegative martingale with
\[
\mathbb E[Y_n]=\mathbb E[Y_0]=1,
\]
but it is \emph{not} uniformly integrable. This example will later explain why nonnegative martingales converge almost surely without necessarily converging in \(L^1\).

\subsection{Wald's identity}

We now return to random walks with i.i.d. increments. Let
\[
X_n=\sum_{j=1}^n Z_j,
\]
where \((Z_j)_{j\ge 1}\) are i.i.d. and satisfy
\[
\mathbb E[|Z_1|]<\infty,
\qquad
\mathbb E[Z_1]=m.
\]
Then
\[
X_n-mn
\]
is a martingale.

\begin{theorem}[Wald's identity]
Let \(T\) be a stopping time with
\[
\mathbb E[T]<\infty.
\]
Then
\[
\mathbb E[X_T]=m\,\mathbb E[T].
\]
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
Since \(n\wedge T\le n\), the bounded-time version of optional stopping applies to the martingale \((X_n-mn)\). Therefore, for every \(n\),
\[
\mathbb E[X_{n\wedge T}]=m\,\mathbb E[n\wedge T].
\]
Because \(T\) is integrable,
\[
\mathbb E[n\wedge T]\to \mathbb E[T].
\]
So it remains to prove
\[
\mathbb E[X_{n\wedge T}]\to \mathbb E[X_T].
\]

We estimate the truncation error:
\[
\bigl|\mathbb E[X_{n\wedge T}]-\mathbb E[X_T]\bigr|
\le
\mathbb E\bigl[|X_{n\wedge T}-X_T|\bigr].
\]
Now on the event \(\{T>n\}\),
\[
X_T-X_{n\wedge T}=X_T-X_n=\sum_{m=n+1}^T Z_m,
\]
so
\[
\mathbb E\bigl[|X_{n\wedge T}-X_T|\bigr]
\le
\mathbb E\left[\sum_{m=n+1}^{\infty}|Z_m|\mathbf 1_{\{T\ge m\}}\right].
\]
By Tonelli's theorem,
\[
\mathbb E\bigl[|X_{n\wedge T}-X_T|\bigr]
\le
\sum_{m=n+1}^{\infty}
\mathbb E\bigl[|Z_m|\mathbf 1_{\{T\ge m\}}\bigr].
\]

The key observation is that the event \(\{T\ge m\}\) is determined by
\[
Z_1,Z_2,\dots,Z_{m-1},
\]
so it is independent of \(Z_m\). Therefore,
\[
\mathbb E\bigl[|Z_m|\mathbf 1_{\{T\ge m\}}\bigr]
=
\mathbb E[|Z_m|]\,\mathbb P(T\ge m)
=
\mathbb E[|Z_1|]\,\mathbb P(T\ge m).
\]
Hence
\[
\mathbb E\bigl[|X_{n\wedge T}-X_T|\bigr]
\le
\mathbb E[|Z_1|]\sum_{m=n+1}^{\infty}\mathbb P(T\ge m).
\]
Finally, for any nonnegative integer-valued random variable \(T\),
\[
\mathbb E[T]=\sum_{m=1}^{\infty}\mathbb P(T\ge m).
\]
Since \(\mathbb E[T]<\infty\), the tail sum tends to zero. Thus
\[
\mathbb E\bigl[|X_{n\wedge T}-X_T|\bigr]\to 0,
\]
which implies
\[
\mathbb E[X_T]=m\,\mathbb E[T].
\]
\end{proof}

\begin{keyformula}
If \(X_n=\sum_{j=1}^n Z_j\) with i.i.d. increments of mean \(m\), and if \(T\) is an integrable stopping time, then
\[
\mathbb E[X_T]=m\,\mathbb E[T].
\]
\end{keyformula}

\subsection{Doob's maximal inequality: the nonnegative case}

The next application of OST is a maximal bound for nonnegative martingales.

\begin{theorem}[Doob's maximal inequality]
Let \((X_n)_{n\ge 0}\) be a nonnegative martingale. Then for every \(\lambda>0\) and every integer \(n\ge 0\),
\[
\mathbb P\!\left(\max_{1\le t\le n} X_t\ge \lambda\right)
\le
\frac{\mathbb E[X_0]}{\lambda}.
\]
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
Define the first hitting time of level \(\lambda\):
\[
T:=\inf\{t>0:X_t\ge \lambda\}.
\]
Then
\[
\left\{\max_{1\le t\le n}X_t\ge \lambda\right\}=
\{T\le n\}.
\]

Because \(T\wedge n\le n\), the bounded-time version of optional stopping gives
\[
\mathbb E[X_{T\wedge n}]=\mathbb E[X_0].
\]
On the other hand, since \(X_{T\wedge n}\ge 0\),
\[
\mathbb E[X_{T\wedge n}]
=
\mathbb P(T>n)\,\mathbb E[X_{T\wedge n}\mid T>n]
+
\mathbb P(T\le n)\,\mathbb E[X_{T\wedge n}\mid T\le n].
\]
If \(T\le n\), then by definition of \(T\),
\[
X_{T\wedge n}=X_T\ge \lambda.
\]
Therefore
\[
\mathbb E[X_{T\wedge n}]\ge \lambda\,\mathbb P(T\le n).
\]
Combining the two displays,
\[
\lambda\,\mathbb P(T\le n)\le \mathbb E[X_0].
\]
This is exactly the desired inequality.
\end{proof}

\begin{remark}
This is the martingale analogue of Markov's inequality, but now it controls the \emph{entire path up to time \(n\)}, not just the single random variable \(X_n\).
\end{remark}

\subsection{Martingale convergence: what should it mean?}

The lecture then turns to the long-run behavior of martingales.

This is different from Markov-chain convergence. For a Markov chain one often studies limits such as
\[
P_{ij}^{(n)}\to \pi_j.
\]
For martingales, the natural question is whether the random variables themselves converge:
\[
X_n\to X_\infty
\qquad \text{almost surely.}
\]

The notes motivate this with two examples:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item in gambler's ruin, the stopped martingale \((X_{n\wedge T})\) converges to
    \[
    X_\infty=
    \begin{cases}
    c, & \text{with probability } a/c,\\
    0, & \text{with probability } 1-a/c;
    \end{cases}
    \]
    \item the series
    \[
    \sum_{j=1}^{\infty}\frac{Z_j}{j}
    \]
    converges, whereas the unsigned harmonic series diverges. In a very real sense, the randomness creates cancellation.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Martingale convergence theorem}

\begin{theorem}[Martingale convergence theorem]
Let \((X_n)_{n\ge 0}\) be a martingale. If there exists a constant \(C<\infty\) such that
\[
\mathbb E[|X_n|]\le C
\qquad \text{for all } n,
\]
then there exists a random variable \(X_\infty\) such that
\[
X_n\to X_\infty
\qquad \text{almost surely.}
\]
\end{theorem}

\begin{remark}
This hypothesis is strictly weaker than uniform integrability. It gives almost sure convergence, but not automatically \(L^1\)-convergence.
\end{remark}

\subsection{The up-crossing idea}

The proof is based on a simple but powerful idea.

Fix an interval \([a,b]\) with \(a<b\). If a sample path fails to converge, then it must keep oscillating. In particular, there must be some interval \([a,b]\) that the path crosses from below to above infinitely many times.

This leads to the notion of \emph{up-crossings}.

\begin{definition}[Up-crossings]
Let \((x_n)\) be a real sequence and let \(a<b\). An \emph{up-crossing} of \([a,b]\) is completed whenever the sequence first goes to \(\le a\) and later reaches \(\ge b\). We write
\[
U_n(a,b)
\]
for the number of completed up-crossings of \([a,b]\) up to time \(n\).
\end{definition}

If a path makes infinitely many up-crossings of some interval, then it cannot converge.
Conversely, if a real sequence does not converge, then there exist rational numbers \(a<b\) such that the sequence makes infinitely many up-crossings of \([a,b]\).

So to prove almost sure convergence, it is enough to show that for every rational pair \(a<b\),
\[
U_\infty(a,b)<\infty
\qquad \text{almost surely.}
\]

\subsection{A trading strategy attached to an interval}

Fix \(a<b\). Interpret \(X_n\) as the price of a stock, and use the following strategy:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item buy one unit when the price is at or below \(a\);
    \item hold the stock while waiting for the price to rise;
    \item sell when the price reaches or exceeds \(b\);
    \item then repeat the procedure.
\end{itemize}

Let \(B_j\in\{0,1\}\) denote whether we are holding the stock during step \(j\). The crucial point is that \(B_j\) is determined by the past, so it is \(\mathcal F_{j-1}\)-measurable.

Define the wealth process
\[
W_n:=\sum_{j=1}^n B_j(X_j-X_{j-1}).
\]

\begin{proposition}
If \((X_n)\) is a martingale, then \((W_n)\) is also a martingale.
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
Since
\[
W_{n+1}=W_n+B_{n+1}(X_{n+1}-X_n),
\]
and \(B_{n+1}\) is \(\mathcal F_n\)-measurable,
\[
\mathbb E[W_{n+1}\mid \mathcal F_n]
=
W_n+B_{n+1}\,\mathbb E[X_{n+1}-X_n\mid \mathcal F_n].
\]
Because \((X_n)\) is a martingale,
\[
\mathbb E[X_{n+1}-X_n\mid \mathcal F_n]=0.
\]
Therefore
\[
\mathbb E[W_{n+1}\mid \mathcal F_n]=W_n.
\]
\end{proof}

\subsection{The up-crossing inequality}

Every completed up-crossing earns at least \(b-a\). The only possible loss comes from an unfinished trade at time \(n\). Therefore
\[
W_n\ge (b-a)U_n(a,b)-|X_n-a|.
\]
Taking expectations and using \(\mathbb E[W_n]=\mathbb E[W_0]=0\), we obtain
\[
0=\mathbb E[W_n]
\ge
(b-a)\mathbb E[U_n(a,b)]-\mathbb E[|X_n-a|].
\]
Hence
\[
\mathbb E[U_n(a,b)]
\le
\frac{\mathbb E[|X_n-a|]}{b-a}
\le
\frac{\mathbb E[|X_n|]+|a|}{b-a}.
\]
If \(\mathbb E[|X_n|]\le C\) for all \(n\), then
\[
\mathbb E[U_n(a,b)]
\le
\frac{C+|a|}{b-a},
\]
and the right-hand side does not depend on \(n\).

\begin{keyformula}
For every interval \([a,b]\) with \(a<b\),
\[
\mathbb E[U_n(a,b)]
\le
\frac{\mathbb E[|X_n-a|]}{b-a}
\le
\frac{C+|a|}{b-a}
\qquad \text{if } \mathbb E[|X_n|]\le C.
\]
\end{keyformula}

\subsection{From bounded expected up-crossings to almost sure convergence}

Because \(U_n(a,b)\) is nondecreasing in \(n\), monotone convergence gives
\[
\mathbb E[U_\infty(a,b)]
=
\lim_{n\to\infty}\mathbb E[U_n(a,b)]
\le
\frac{C+|a|}{b-a}<\infty.
\]
So for every fixed interval \([a,b]\),
\[
\mathbb P(U_\infty(a,b)=\infty)=0.
\]

Now restrict to rational endpoints. Since there are only countably many pairs \((a,b)\in\mathbb Q^2\) with \(a<b\),
\[
\mathbb P\bigl(\exists a,b\in\mathbb Q,\ a<b,\ U_\infty(a,b)=\infty\bigr)=0.
\]
But if a real sequence does not converge, then one can find rational numbers
\[
a<b
\]
strictly between its liminf and limsup, and this forces infinitely many up-crossings of \([a,b]\). Therefore the event of nonconvergence has probability zero.

This proves the martingale convergence theorem.

\subsection{Summary}

\begin{summarybox}
Lecture 7 develops three major themes.

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item \textbf{Careful optional stopping:} for gambler's ruin, OST works once we verify the tail condition using an exponential bound on the hitting time.
    \item \textbf{Uniform integrability:} UI is the right tool for proving tail conditions such as
    \[
    \mathbb E\bigl[|X_n|\mathbf 1_{\{T>n\}}\bigr]\to 0,
    \]
    and a uniform \(L^2\)-bound implies UI.
    \item \textbf{Long-run martingale behavior:} Wald's identity and Doob's maximal inequality are useful applications of OST, and the up-crossing method proves that any martingale with
    \[
    \sup_n \mathbb E[|X_n|]<\infty
    \]
    converges almost surely.
\end{itemize}
\end{summarybox}

