\begin{enumerate}[label=(\arabic*)]
    \item \textbf{Statement.} For a discrete-time stochastic process \((X_n)_{n=0,1,2,\dots}\), if \(T_1\) and \(T_2\) are both stopping times, then \(T_1\cdot T_2\) is a stopping time.

    \textbf{Answer: True.}

    \textbf{Explanation.} In discrete time we can write, for each integer \(n\ge 0\),
    \[
    \{T_1T_2\le n\}
    =
    \{T_1=0\}\cup \{T_2=0\}
    \cup
    \bigcup_{k=1}^n \Bigl(\{T_1=k\}\cap \{T_2\le \lfloor n/k\rfloor\}\Bigr).
    \]
    Since \(T_1\) and \(T_2\) are stopping times, each event on the right is in \(\mathcal F_n\). Hence \(\{T_1T_2\le n\}\in \mathcal F_n\), so \(T_1T_2\) is a stopping time.

    \item \textbf{Statement.} For a Brownian motion \((B_t)_{t\ge 0}\), if \(T_1\) and \(T_2\) are both stopping times, then \(T_1\cdot T_2\) is a stopping time.

    \textbf{Answer: False.}

    \textbf{Explanation.} In continuous time, products of stopping times are \emph{not} one of the standard closure operations. The classes that are stable are things like \(T_1\wedge T_2\), \(T_1\vee T_2\), and \(T_1+c\) for deterministic \(c\ge 0\). In general, the event \(\{T_1T_2\le t\}\) can depend on information from times strictly larger than \(t\), so it need not lie in \(\mathcal F_t\).

    \item \textbf{Statement.} Let \((X_n)_{n\ge 0}\) be a discrete-time martingale. For any stopping time \(T\) such that \(\mathbb P(T<\infty)=1\), we have
    \[
    \mathbb E[X_T]=\mathbb E[X_0].
    \]

    \textbf{Answer: False.}

    \textbf{Explanation.} Almost sure finiteness of \(T\) is \emph{not} enough for optional stopping. One also needs an extra condition such as boundedness of \(T\), uniform integrability of the martingale, bounded increments together with \(\mathbb E[T]<\infty\), and so on. A standard counterexample is a simple random walk stopped at its hitting time of \(0\): the stopped process is a martingale, the stopping time is finite almost surely, but the expectation drops.

    \item \textbf{Statement.} Let \((X_n)_{n\ge 0}\) be a discrete-time martingale. If for every fixed \(n\ge 0\),
    \[
    \lim_{K\to\infty}\mathbb E\bigl[|X_n|\mathbf 1_{\{|X_n|\ge K\}}\bigr]=0,
    \]
    then \((X_n)_{n\ge 0}\) is uniformly integrable.

    \textbf{Answer: False.}

    \textbf{Explanation.} The displayed limit for a \emph{fixed} \(n\) is just ordinary integrability of \(X_n\). Uniform integrability requires the tail bound to hold \emph{uniformly in \(n\)}:
    \[
    \lim_{K\to\infty} \sup_{n\ge 0}
    \mathbb E\bigl[|X_n|\mathbf 1_{\{|X_n|\ge K\}}\bigr]=0.
    \]
    The statement forgets the essential supremum over \(n\).

    \item \textbf{Statement.} Let \((X_n)_{n\ge 0}\) be a discrete-time irreducible and aperiodic Markov chain on a countably infinite state space \(S\subseteq \mathbb R\). If \((X_n)_{n\ge 0}\) is also a non-negative martingale that converges almost surely to some \(X_\infty\), then the chain has a stationary distribution \(\pi\), and \(X_\infty\sim \pi\).

    \textbf{Answer: False.}

    \textbf{Explanation.} Convergence of a non-negative martingale only tells us that a limit random variable exists almost surely. It does \emph{not} imply that the Markov chain is positive recurrent, and positive recurrence is what is needed for existence of a stationary distribution on a countable irreducible chain. Also, even if a stationary distribution existed, it would not automatically follow that the limit law is that stationary distribution unless the chain were actually converging to equilibrium under the hypotheses of the Markov chain convergence theorem.

    \item \textbf{Statement.} If \((X_t)_{t\ge 0}\) is a martingale and \(T\) is a stopping time, then \((X_{t\wedge T})_{t\ge 0}\) is also a martingale.

    \textbf{Answer: True.}

    \textbf{Explanation.} This is the standard stopped-martingale theorem. For \(s\le t\),
    \[
    \mathbb E[X_{t\wedge T}\mid \mathcal F_s]=X_{s\wedge T},
    \]
    provided the original martingale is integrable. Intuitively, once time \(T\) is reached the process just freezes, and before time \(T\) it behaves exactly like the original martingale.

    \item \textbf{Statement.} Let \((B_t)_{t\ge 0}\) be a Brownian motion and
    \[
    T:=\inf\{t>0:B_t=0\}.
    \]
    Then \(T=0\) with probability \(1\).

    \textbf{Answer: True.}

    \textbf{Explanation.} Brownian motion returns to \(0\) infinitely often, and in fact the zero set has no isolated points almost surely. So even if we ask for the \emph{first positive} time at which the process comes back to \(0\), that infimum is still \(0\) almost surely.

    \item \textbf{Statement.} Let \((B_t)_{t\ge 0}\) be a Brownian motion and let \(f\) be continuously differentiable. Then
    \[
    \mathbb E[f(B_t)] = \mathbb E\!\left[\int_0^t f'(B_s)\,dB_s\right].
    \]

    \textbf{Answer: False.}

    \textbf{Explanation.} The expectation of an It\^o integral is \(0\) whenever the integral is well-defined, so the right-hand side is typically \(0\). But the left-hand side is usually not \(0\). For example, if \(f(x)=x^2\), then
    \[
    \mathbb E[f(B_t)] = \mathbb E[B_t^2]=t,
    \qquad
    \mathbb E\!\left[\int_0^t 2B_s\,dB_s\right]=0.
    \]
    The correct It\^o formula is
    \[
    f(B_t)=f(0)+\int_0^t f'(B_s)\,dB_s + \frac12\int_0^t f''(B_s)\,ds
    \]
    when \(f\in C^2\).

    \item \textbf{Statement.} Let \((X_t)_{t\ge 0}\) be a two-dimensional standard Brownian motion. With probability \(1\), for any \(t>0\), there exists \(t'>t\) such that
    \[
    \left\|X_{t'}-\begin{bmatrix}100\\100\end{bmatrix}\right\|_2\le 10^{-2}.
    \]

    \textbf{Answer: True.}

    \textbf{Explanation.} Two-dimensional Brownian motion is recurrent. In particular, every open ball is hit infinitely many times almost surely. The ball of radius \(10^{-2}\) centered at \((100,100)\) is an open set, so after any time \(t\) the process will almost surely enter that ball at some later time.

    \item \textbf{Statement.} If \((B_t)_{t\ge 0}\) is a Brownian motion, then
    \[
    \int_0^t B_s^2\,dB_s
    \]
    is normally distributed.

    \textbf{Answer: False.}

    \textbf{Explanation.} An It\^o integral is automatically Gaussian only when the integrand is deterministic. Here the integrand \(B_s^2\) is random. In fact, It\^o's formula gives
    \[
    d(B_t^3)=3B_t^2\,dB_t+3B_t\,dt,
    \]
    so
    \[
    \int_0^t B_s^2\,dB_s
    =
    \frac13 B_t^3 - \int_0^t B_s\,ds,
    \]
    which is not Gaussian.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection*{Question 2 \hfill [9 points]}
Give an example of a martingale \((X_t)_{t\ge 0}\) such that
\[
\sup_{t\ge 0}\mathbb E[|X_t|]\le C<\infty,
\qquad
X_t\to X_\infty \text{ a.s. as } t\to\infty,
\qquad
\text{but } \mathbb E[X_0]\ne \mathbb E[X_\infty].
\]

\textbf{Example.} Let \((S_n)_{n\ge 0}\) be the one-dimensional simple symmetric random walk started from \(S_0=1\), and let
\[
\tau:=\inf\{n\ge 0:S_n=0\}.
\]
Define
\[
X_n:=S_{n\wedge \tau}.
\]

\textbf{Why this works.}
\begin{enumerate}[label=(\roman*)]
    \item \textbf{Martingale.} Since \((S_n)\) is a martingale and \(\tau\) is a stopping time, the stopped process \((S_{n\wedge \tau})\) is also a martingale.

    \item \textbf{Uniform \(L^1\) bound.} We have \(X_n\ge 0\) because before hitting \(0\), the walk started from \(1\) cannot jump below \(0\) without first visiting \(0\). Therefore
    \[
    \mathbb E[|X_n|]=\mathbb E[X_n]=\mathbb E[X_0]=1
    \qquad \text{for all } n,
    \]
    so we may take \(C=1\).

    \item \textbf{Almost sure convergence.} One-dimensional simple random walk is recurrent, so \(\tau<\infty\) almost surely. Hence for all large enough \(n\),
    \[
    X_n=S_{n\wedge \tau}=S_\tau=0.
    \]
    Thus \(X_n\to X_\infty=0\) almost surely.

    \item \textbf{Expectation drops in the limit.} We have
    \[
    \mathbb E[X_0]=1,
    \qquad
    \mathbb E[X_\infty]=0.
    \]
    So indeed
    \[
    \mathbb E[X_0]\ne \mathbb E[X_\infty].
    \]
\end{enumerate}

This example is the classical warning that an a.s.-convergent martingale with bounded first moments need \emph{not} be uniformly integrable.

\begin{summarybox}
\textbf{Grading note from the solution sheet.} Any valid example with a complete justification deserves full credit. The stopped simple random walk above is exactly the example suggested in the handwritten solution.
\end{summarybox}

\subsection*{Question 3 \hfill [20 points]}
Consider a box with \(N\) balls, each coloured red or blue. At each round, we sample \(N\) times independently \emph{with replacement} from the current box, and then replace the entire box by the sampled composition. Let \(X_t\) be the number of red balls after round \(t\). Then
\[
X_{t+1}=\sum_{j=1}^N Z_{t+1,j},
\qquad
Z_{t+1,j}\mid X_t \stackrel{\text{i.i.d.}}{\sim} \mathrm{Ber}(X_t/N),
\]
with fixed initial state \(X_0=x\in\{1,2,\dots,N-1\}.\)

\paragraph{Part (1) \hfill [10 pts]}
Show that \((X_t)_{t\ge 0}\) is a martingale, and compute
\[
\mathbb P\!\left(\lim_{t\to\infty} X_t=0\right).
\]

\textbf{Solution.}
Conditioning on \(\mathcal F_t\), each \(Z_{t+1,j}\) has mean \(X_t/N\). Therefore
\[
\mathbb E[X_{t+1}\mid \mathcal F_t]
=
\sum_{j=1}^N \mathbb E[Z_{t+1,j}\mid \mathcal F_t]
=
N\cdot \frac{X_t}{N}
=
X_t.
\]
So \((X_t)\) is a martingale.

Also,
\[
0\le X_t\le N
\qquad \text{for all } t,
\]
so the martingale is bounded. Hence it is uniformly integrable, and therefore there exists a random variable \(X_\infty\) such that
\[
X_t\to X_\infty \quad \text{a.s. and in } L^1.
\]

Now each \(X_t\) is integer-valued. A convergent integer-valued sequence must eventually be constant, so the limit can only be a state at which the chain can remain forever. The only absorbing states are \(0\) and \(N\). Indeed, if \(1\le m\le N-1\), then conditional on \(X_t=m\), the law of \(X_{t+1}\) is \(\mathrm{Bin}(N,m/N)\), which is not degenerate, so the chain cannot stay forever at \(m\).

Thus
\[
X_\infty\in\{0,N\}
\qquad \text{a.s.}
\]
Since convergence also holds in \(L^1\),
\[
\mathbb E[X_\infty]=\mathbb E[X_0]=x.
\]
Write \(p=\mathbb P(X_\infty=N)\). Then
\[
\mathbb E[X_\infty]=Np+0\cdot (1-p)=Np=x,
\]
so
\[
\mathbb P(X_\infty=N)=\frac{x}{N},
\qquad
\mathbb P(X_\infty=0)=1-\frac{x}{N}.
\]
Therefore
\[
\mathbb P\!\left(\lim_{t\to\infty} X_t=0\right)=1-\frac{x}{N}.
\]

\paragraph{Part (2) \hfill [10 pts]}
Show that for every \(t\ge 0\) and \(x\in\{1,2,\dots,N-1\}\),
\[
\mathbb P_x(1\le X_t\le N-1)
\le
x(N-x)\left(1-\frac1N\right)^t.
\]

\textbf{Hint from the exam.} Study the process
\[
H_t:=X_t(N-X_t).
\]

\textbf{Solution.}
Conditionally on \(X_t\), the random variable \(X_{t+1}\) is \(\mathrm{Bin}(N,p)\) with \(p=X_t/N\). Hence
\[
\mathbb E[X_{t+1}\mid \mathcal F_t]=X_t,
\qquad
\mathrm{Var}(X_{t+1}\mid \mathcal F_t)=Np(1-p)=X_t-\frac{X_t^2}{N}.
\]
Therefore
\[
\mathbb E[X_{t+1}^2\mid \mathcal F_t]
=
\mathrm{Var}(X_{t+1}\mid \mathcal F_t)+\bigl(\mathbb E[X_{t+1}\mid \mathcal F_t]\bigr)^2
=
X_t+\left(1-\frac1N\right)X_t^2.
\]
Now compute
\begin{align*}
\mathbb E[H_{t+1}\mid \mathcal F_t]
&=
\mathbb E[X_{t+1}(N-X_{t+1})\mid \mathcal F_t]\\
&=
N\mathbb E[X_{t+1}\mid \mathcal F_t]-\mathbb E[X_{t+1}^2\mid \mathcal F_t]\\
&=
NX_t-\left(X_t+\left(1-\frac1N\right)X_t^2\right)\\
&=
\left(1-\frac1N\right)X_t(N-X_t)\\
&=
\left(1-\frac1N\right)H_t.
\end{align*}
Taking expectations recursively gives
\[
\mathbb E[H_t]=\left(1-\frac1N\right)^t H_0
=\left(1-\frac1N\right)^t x(N-x).
\]

Finally, because \(X_t\) is integer-valued,
\[
1\le X_t\le N-1
\quad \Longleftrightarrow \quad
H_t=X_t(N-X_t)\ge 1.
\]
So by Markov's inequality,
\[
\mathbb P_x(1\le X_t\le N-1)
=
\mathbb P_x(H_t\ge 1)
\le
\mathbb E_x[H_t]
=
x(N-x)\left(1-\frac1N\right)^t.
\]
This is exactly the desired bound.

\begin{summarybox}
\textbf{Key idea.} The quantity \(H_t=X_t(N-X_t)\) measures how far the chain is from the absorbing states \(0\) and \(N\). The computation shows that its expectation decays geometrically, so the probability of still being in a non-absorbing state also decays geometrically.
\end{summarybox}

\subsection*{Question 4 \hfill [25 points]}
Let \((B_t)_{t\ge 0}\) be a Brownian motion.

\paragraph{Part (1) \hfill [5 pts]}
Let \(\lambda\) be a deterministic constant. If
\[
M_t:=e^{\lambda B_t}-1-\int_0^t f(B_s)\,ds
\]
is a martingale, determine \(f\), and write \(M_t\) as an It\^o integral.

\textbf{Solution.}
Apply It\^o's formula to \(g(x)=e^{\lambda x}\). Since
\[
g'(x)=\lambda e^{\lambda x},
\qquad
 g''(x)=\lambda^2 e^{\lambda x},
\]
we get
\[
d(e^{\lambda B_t})
=
lambda e^{\lambda B_t}\,dB_t + \frac{\lambda^2}{2}e^{\lambda B_t}\,dt.
\]
So
\[
e^{\lambda B_t}-1-\int_0^t \frac{\lambda^2}{2}e^{\lambda B_s}\,ds
=
\int_0^t \lambda e^{\lambda B_s}\,dB_s.
\]
Therefore the required choice is
\[
f(x)=\frac{\lambda^2}{2}e^{\lambda x},
\]
and the martingale can be written as
\[
M_t=\int_0^t \lambda e^{\lambda B_s}\,dB_s.
\]

\paragraph{Part (2) \hfill [10 pts]}
Compute
\[
\mathbb P\!\left(\max_{0\le t\le 1} B_t\ge 1,\; B_1\le 0\right).
\]

\textbf{Solution.}
Let
\[
\tau:=\inf\{t\ge 0:B_t=1\}.
\]
Then
\[
\left\{\max_{0\le t\le 1}B_t\ge 1,\; B_1\le 0\right\}
=
\{\tau\le 1,\; B_1\le 0\}.
\]
Now reflect the Brownian path after time \(\tau\). Under this reflection, the terminal value transforms by
\[
B_1 \longmapsto 2-B_1.
\]
Hence paths with \(\tau\le 1\) and \(B_1\le 0\) are in one-to-one correspondence with paths satisfying \(B_1\ge 2\). This is exactly the reflection principle in this form. Therefore
\[
\mathbb P\!\left(\max_{0\le t\le 1} B_t\ge 1,\; B_1\le 0\right)
=
\mathbb P(B_1\ge 2).
\]
Since \(B_1\sim N(0,1)\),
\[
\mathbb P(B_1\ge 2)
=
\int_2^{\infty}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}}e^{-x^2/2}\,dx.
\]
So the answer is
\[
\boxed{\int_2^{\infty}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}}e^{-x^2/2}\,dx.}
\]

\paragraph{Part (3) \hfill [10 pts]}
Let
\[
\tau:=\inf\{t\ge 0:|B_t|\ge 1\}.
\]
Compute \(\mathrm{var}(\tau)\).

\textbf{Solution.}
The hint suggests starting from
\[
Z_t:=B_t^4-6tB_t^2.
\]
Using It\^o's formula,
\[
d(B_t^4)=4B_t^3\,dB_t+6B_t^2\,dt,
\]
and
\[
d(6tB_t^2)=6B_t^2\,dt+12tB_t\,dB_t+6t\,dt.
\]
Subtracting,
\[
dZ_t=(4B_t^3-12tB_t)\,dB_t-6t\,dt.
\]
Therefore
\[
Z_t+3t^2
=
B_t^4-6tB_t^2+3t^2
\]
is a martingale.

Now stop at \(\tau\). Since \(|B_\tau|=1\), we have
\[
B_\tau^2=1,
\qquad
B_\tau^4=1.
\]
Applying optional stopping to the martingale above gives
\[
\mathbb E\bigl[B_\tau^4-6\tau B_\tau^2+3\tau^2\bigr]=0,
\]
so
\[
1-6\mathbb E[\tau]+3\mathbb E[\tau^2]=0.
\]
We also know from the standard martingale \(B_t^2-t\) that
\[
\mathbb E[\tau]=1.
\]
Substituting this into the previous identity gives
\[
1-6+3\mathbb E[\tau^2]=0
\quad\Longrightarrow\quad
3\mathbb E[\tau^2]=5
\quad\Longrightarrow\quad
\mathbb E[\tau^2]=\frac53.
\]
Hence
\[
\mathrm{var}(\tau)
=
\mathbb E[\tau^2]-(\mathbb E[\tau])^2
=
\frac53-1
=
\frac23.
\]
So
\[
\boxed{\mathrm{var}(\tau)=\frac23.}
\]

\subsection*{Question 5 \hfill [16 points]}

\paragraph{Part (1) \hfill [8 pts]}
Let \((B_t)_{t\ge 0}\) be a standard Brownian motion, and suppose \((X_t)_{t\ge 0}\) starts from \(X_0=x\) and satisfies
\[
dX_t=-X_t\,dt+dB_t.
\]
Show that \(X_t\) is normally distributed for every \(t>0\), and compute its mean and variance.

\textbf{Solution.}
Introduce the integrating factor
\[
Z_t:=e^t X_t.
\]
Since \(e^t\) is deterministic, It\^o's product rule gives
\[
dZ_t=e^t\,dX_t+e^tX_t\,dt=e^t(-X_t\,dt+dB_t)+e^tX_t\,dt=e^t\,dB_t.
\]
Integrating from \(0\) to \(t\),
\[
Z_t=x+\int_0^t e^s\,dB_s.
\]
Therefore
\[
X_t=e^{-t}x+e^{-t}\int_0^t e^s\,dB_s
=e^{-t}x+\int_0^t e^{-(t-s)}\,dB_s.
\]

Now the stochastic integral on the right has a \emph{deterministic} integrand, so it is Gaussian with mean \(0\) and variance
\[
\int_0^t e^{-2(t-s)}\,ds
=e^{-2t}\int_0^t e^{2s}\,ds
=e^{-2t}\cdot \frac{e^{2t}-1}{2}
=
\frac12\bigl(1-e^{-2t}\bigr).
\]
Hence \(X_t\) is Gaussian with
\[
\mathbb E[X_t]=e^{-t}x,
\qquad
\mathrm{Var}(X_t)=\frac12\bigl(1-e^{-2t}\bigr).
\]
So the final description is
\[
X_t\sim N\!\left(e^{-t}x,\; \frac12(1-e^{-2t})\right).
\]

\paragraph{Part (2) \hfill [8 pts]}
Let \((X_n)_{n\ge 0}\) be a discrete-time stochastic process such that \(\mathbb E[|X_n|]<\infty\) and
\[
\mathbb E[X_{n+1}\mid \mathcal F_n]\le X_n
\qquad \text{for all } n.
\]
So \((X_n)\) is a supermartingale. Assume also that \(X_n\ge 0\) almost surely for every \(n\). Prove that
\[
X_n\to X_\infty \qquad \text{almost surely}
\]
for some random variable \(X_\infty\).

\textbf{Solution by upcrossings.}
Because \((X_n)\) is a nonnegative supermartingale,
\[
\mathbb E[X_n]\le \mathbb E[X_0]\qquad \text{for all } n,
\]
so the process is bounded in \(L^1\).

Fix rational numbers \(0<a<b<\infty\), and let \(U_n[a,b]\) be the number of upcrossings of the interval \([a,b]\) completed by time \(n\). As in the proof of the martingale convergence theorem, construct the usual predictable betting strategy that holds one unit of stock while trying to complete an upcrossing from \(a\) to \(b\). Let \(G_n\) be the associated gains process. Since \((X_n)\) is a supermartingale, this gains process is also a supermartingale, so
\[
\mathbb E[G_n]\le 0.
\]
On the other hand, pathwise one has the standard lower bound
\[
G_n\ge (b-a)U_n[a,b]-(X_n-a)^+.
\]
Taking expectations yields
\[
(b-a)\,\mathbb E[U_n[a,b]]
\le
\mathbb E[(X_n-a)^+]
\le
\mathbb E[X_n]
\le
\mathbb E[X_0].
\]
Thus
\[
\sup_{n\ge 0}\mathbb E[U_n[a,b]]<\infty.
\]
Therefore the total number of upcrossings of every rational interval \([a,b]\) is finite almost surely.

Now suppose \(\liminf X_n < \limsup X_n\) on some event of positive probability. Then there exist rationals \(a<b\) such that the sample path makes infinitely many upcrossings of \([a,b]\), contradicting the previous conclusion. Hence
\[
\liminf_{n\to\infty} X_n = \limsup_{n\to\infty} X_n
\qquad \text{a.s.}
\]
so \(X_n\) converges almost surely to some extended random variable \(X_\infty\in [0,\infty]\).

Finally, Fatou's lemma gives
\[
\mathbb E\bigl[\liminf_{n\to\infty} X_n\bigr]
\le
\liminf_{n\to\infty}\mathbb E[X_n]
\le
\mathbb E[X_0]<\infty.
\]
Therefore \(X_\infty<\infty\) almost surely. So there exists a finite random variable \(X_\infty\) such that
\[
X_n\to X_\infty
\qquad \text{a.s.}
\]
which is exactly what we wanted to prove.

\begin{summarybox}
\textbf{Big picture.} This is the supermartingale version of the martingale convergence theorem. Nonnegativity gives a uniform \(L^1\) bound from above, and the upcrossing argument forces the sample paths to settle down to a limit.
\end{summarybox}

