\subsection*{Question 1 \hfill [30 points]}
Mark each statement True or False.

\begin{enumerate}[label=(\arabic*)]

\item \textbf{Statement.} For a discrete-time stochastic process \((X_n)_{n=0,1,2,\dots}\), if \(T_1\) and \(T_2\) are both stopping times, then \(T_1T_2\) is a stopping time.

\textbf{Answer: True.}

\textbf{Explanation.}
In discrete time, to check that \(T_1T_2\) is a stopping time, it is enough to show that
\[
\{T_1T_2\le n\}\in \mathcal F_n
\qquad \text{for every } n\in \mathbb N.
\]
But
\[
\{T_1T_2\le n\}
=
\bigcup_{k=0}^n \Bigl(\{T_1=k\}\cap \{T_2\le \lfloor n/k\rfloor\}\Bigr),
\]
with the obvious harmless adjustment when \(k=0\).
Since \(T_1\) and \(T_2\) are stopping times, the events \(\{T_1=k\}\) and \(\{T_2\le m\}\) are measurable with respect to \(\mathcal F_k\) and \(\mathcal F_m\), and both sigma-fields are contained in \(\mathcal F_n\). Hence the whole union belongs to \(\mathcal F_n\).

\item \textbf{Statement.} For a Brownian motion \((B_t)_{t\ge 0}\), if \(T_1\) and \(T_2\) are both stopping times, then \(T_1T_2\) is a stopping time.

\textbf{Answer: False.}

\textbf{Explanation.}
The discrete-time argument above uses the fact that there are only finitely many time indices up to \(n\). In continuous time, that argument breaks down. A standard counterexample is to take a nontrivial stopping time \(\tau\) and look at \(\tau^2\). Then
\[
\{\tau^2\le t\}=\{\tau\le \sqrt t\},
\]
and when \(0<t<1\), this event depends on the Brownian path up to time \(\sqrt t>t\), so it need not be \(\mathcal F_t\)-measurable. Thus the product of two stopping times need not be a stopping time in continuous time.

\item \textbf{Statement.} Let \((X_n)_{n\ge 0}\) be a discrete-time martingale. For any stopping time \(T\) such that \(\mathbb P(T<\infty)=1\), we have
\[
\mathbb E[X_T]=\mathbb E[X_0].
\]

\textbf{Answer: False.}

\textbf{Explanation.}
Almost sure finiteness of \(T\) is not enough for optional stopping. One also needs extra assumptions such as boundedness of \(T\), uniform integrability, or suitable integrability bounds on the stopped process.
A standard counterexample is the simple random walk \(S_n\) started from \(0\), with
\[
T=\inf\{n\ge 0:S_n=1\}.
\]
Then \(T<\infty\) almost surely by recurrence, but
\[
\mathbb E[S_T]=1\neq 0=\mathbb E[S_0].
\]

\item \textbf{Statement.} Let \((X_n)_{n\ge 0}\) be a discrete-time martingale. If for every fixed \(n\),
\[
\lim_{K\to\infty}\mathbb E\!\bigl[|X_n|\mathbf 1_{\{|X_n|\ge K\}}\bigr]=0,
\]
then \((X_n)_{n\ge 0}\) is uniformly integrable.

\textbf{Answer: False.}

\textbf{Explanation.}
Uniform integrability requires a bound that is uniform in \(n\):
\[
\lim_{K\to\infty}\sup_n \mathbb E\!\bigl[|X_n|\mathbf 1_{\{|X_n|\ge K\}}\bigr]=0.
\]
The condition in the statement only says that each \emph{individual} random variable \(X_n\) is integrable.
A standard martingale counterexample is
\[
X_n=S_{n\wedge T},
\qquad
T=\inf\{m\ge 0:S_m=1\},
\]
where \(S_n\) is a simple random walk started from \(0\). For each fixed \(n\), \(X_n\) is bounded, so the displayed limit holds. But the martingale is not uniformly integrable, because \(X_n\to 1\) almost surely while \(\mathbb E[X_n]=0\) for all \(n\).

\item \textbf{Statement.} Let \((X_n)_{n\ge 0}\) be a discrete-time irreducible and aperiodic Markov chain on a countably infinite state space \(S\subseteq \mathbb R\). If \((X_n)\) is also a nonnegative martingale that converges almost surely to \(X_\infty\), then the chain has a stationary distribution \(\pi\), and \(X_\infty\sim \pi\).

\textbf{Answer: False.}

\textbf{Explanation.}
There are two problems here. First, an irreducible countably infinite chain need not have a stationary distribution at all: it may be null recurrent or transient. Second, even if a stationary distribution exists, the limit law \(X_\infty\) need not equal \(\pi\) unless the chain is started in stationarity.
So the conclusion is too strong and is not implied by the hypotheses.

\item \textbf{Statement.} If \((X_t)_{t\ge 0}\) is a martingale and \(T\) is a stopping time, then \((X_{t\wedge T})_{t\ge 0}\) is also a martingale.

\textbf{Answer: True.}

\textbf{Explanation.}
This is exactly the stopped-martingale theorem: stopping a martingale at a stopping time preserves the martingale property (under the standard integrability assumptions that are built into the course definition).

\item \textbf{Statement.} Let \((B_t)_{t\ge 0}\) be a Brownian motion and let
\[
T:=\inf\{t>0:B_t=0\}.
\]
Then \(T=0\) with probability \(1\).

\textbf{Answer: True.}

\textbf{Explanation.}
Brownian motion starts at \(0\), and with probability \(1\) it returns to \(0\) arbitrarily soon after time \(0\). Therefore the first strictly positive return time has infimum \(0\), so \(T=0\) almost surely.

\item \textbf{Statement.} Let \((B_t)_{t\ge 0}\) be a Brownian motion and let \(f\) be continuously differentiable. Then
\[
\mathbb E[f(B_t)]
=
\mathbb E\!\left[\int_0^t f'(B_s)\,dB_s\right].
\]

\textbf{Answer: False.}

\textbf{Explanation.}
The right-hand side is the expectation of an It\^o integral, so it equals \(0\). In general the left-hand side is not \(0\). For example, if \(f(x)=x^2\), then
\[
\mathbb E[f(B_t)]=\mathbb E[B_t^2]=t,
\]
while
\[
\mathbb E\!\left[\int_0^t 2B_s\,dB_s\right]=0.
\]
The correct identity comes from It\^o's formula and involves a second-derivative term.

\item \textbf{Statement.} Let \((X_t)_{t\ge 0}\) be a two-dimensional standard Brownian motion. With probability \(1\), for every \(t>0\), there exists \(t'>t\) such that
\[
\left\|X_{t'}-\begin{pmatrix}100\\100\end{pmatrix}\right\|^2\le 10^{-2}.
\]

\textbf{Answer: True.}

\textbf{Explanation.}
Two-dimensional Brownian motion is recurrent: almost surely it visits every open ball infinitely many times. The set
\[
\left\{x\in \mathbb R^2:\left\|x-\begin{pmatrix}100\\100\end{pmatrix}\right\|^2\le 10^{-2}\right\}
\]
is just a small ball centered at \((100,100)\), so Brownian motion will enter it again after any given time \(t\), almost surely.

\item \textbf{Statement.} If \((B_t)_{t\ge 0}\) is a Brownian motion, then
\[
\int_0^t B_s^2\,dB_s
\]
is normally distributed.

\textbf{Answer: False.}

\textbf{Explanation.}
An It\^o integral is automatically centered, but it is Gaussian only in special cases, for example when the integrand is deterministic. Here the integrand \(B_s^2\) is random and depends on the same Brownian motion.
Using It\^o's formula for \(B_t^3\),
\[
d(B_t^3)=3B_t^2\,dB_t+3B_t\,dt,
\]
so
\[
\int_0^t B_s^2\,dB_s
=
\frac13 B_t^3-\int_0^t B_s\,ds,
\]
which is not a normal random variable.
\end{enumerate}

\begin{summarybox}
Official answer pattern: \(T,F,F,F,F,T,T,F,T,F\).
\end{summarybox}

\subsection*{Question 2 \hfill [9 points]}
Give an example of a martingale \((X_t)_{t\ge 0}\) such that
\[
\sup_{t\ge 0}\mathbb E[|X_t|]\le C
\qquad \text{for some } C<\infty,
\]
and \(X_t\to X_\infty\) almost surely as \(t\to\infty\), but
\[
\mathbb E[X_0]\neq \mathbb E[X_\infty].
\]

\textbf{A valid example.}
Let \((S_n)_{n\ge 0}\) be a one-dimensional simple random walk started from \(S_0=1\), and define
\[
\tau:=\inf\{n\ge 0:S_n=0\}.
\]
Now set
\[
X_n:=S_{n\wedge \tau}.
\]

\textbf{Step 1: \(X_n\) is a martingale.}
The simple random walk \(S_n\) is a martingale. Since \(\tau\) is a stopping time, the stopped process \((S_{n\wedge \tau})\) is also a martingale. Hence \((X_n)\) is a martingale.

\textbf{Step 2: the \(L^1\) norms are uniformly bounded.}
Because the process is stopped when it hits \(0\), we have
\[
X_n\ge 0
\qquad \text{for all } n.
\]
Since \((X_n)\) is a martingale and \(X_0=1\),
\[
\mathbb E[|X_n|]=\mathbb E[X_n]=1
\qquad \text{for every } n.
\]
So we may take \(C=1\).

\textbf{Step 3: almost sure convergence.}
One-dimensional simple random walk is recurrent, so
\[
\mathbb P(\tau<\infty)=1.
\]
Therefore for all sufficiently large \(n\), we have \(n\ge \tau\) and hence
\[
X_n=S_\tau=0.
\]
So
\[
X_n\to X_\infty=0
\qquad \text{almost surely.}
\]

\textbf{Step 4: the expectations do not match.}
We have
\[
\mathbb E[X_0]=1,
\qquad
\mathbb E[X_\infty]=0.
\]
Thus
\[
\mathbb E[X_0]\neq \mathbb E[X_\infty].
\]

\begin{summarybox}
This example shows exactly why \(L^1\)-boundedness and almost sure convergence do \emph{not} by themselves imply preservation of expectation at the limit. The missing ingredient is uniform integrability.
\end{summarybox}

\subsection*{Question 3 \hfill [20 points]}
Consider a box of \(N\) balls in two colours (red and blue). At each round we draw with replacement from the box \(N\) times independently, and we replace the box by the composition of these \(N\) draws. Let \(X_t\) be the number of red balls in round \(t\). Then
\[
X_{t+1}=\sum_{j=1}^N Z_{t+1,j},
\qquad
Z_{t+1,j}\mid X_t \overset{\text{i.i.d.}}{\sim} \mathrm{Ber}(X_t/N).
\]
Assume \(X_0=x\in\{1,2,\dots,N-1\}\).

\paragraph{Part (1) \hfill [10 points]}
Show that \((X_t)_{t\ge 0}\) is a martingale, and compute
\[
\mathbb P\!\left(\lim_{t\to\infty}X_t=0\right).
\]

\textbf{Step 1: martingale property.}
Conditioning on \(X_t\),
\[
\mathbb E[X_{t+1}\mid X_t]
=
\sum_{j=1}^N \mathbb E[Z_{t+1,j}\mid X_t]
=
N\cdot \frac{X_t}{N}
=
X_t.
\]
So \((X_t)\) is a martingale.

\textbf{Step 2: bounded martingale convergence.}
Since \(0\le X_t\le N\) always, the martingale is bounded in \(L^\infty\), hence uniformly integrable. Therefore
\[
X_t\to X_\infty
\qquad \text{almost surely and in } L^1.
\]

\textbf{Step 3: identify the only possible limits.}
Each \(X_t\) takes values in the finite set \(\{0,1,\dots,N\}\). If a sequence of integers converges, then it must eventually be constant. But the only absorbing states of the chain are \(0\) and \(N\). Therefore
\[
X_\infty\in\{0,N\}
\qquad \text{almost surely.}
\]

\textbf{Step 4: use expectation to compute the probability.}
Since the martingale is uniformly integrable,
\[
\mathbb E[X_\infty]=\mathbb E[X_0]=x.
\]
Write
\[
\mathbb P(X_\infty=N)=p.
\]
Then
\[
x=\mathbb E[X_\infty]=0\cdot (1-p)+N\cdot p=Np,
\]
so
\[
p=\frac{x}{N}.
\]
Hence
\[
\mathbb P(X_\infty=0)=1-\frac{x}{N}.
\]

Therefore
\[
\boxed{\mathbb P\!\left(\lim_{t\to\infty}X_t=0\right)=1-\frac{x}{N}.}
\]

\textbf{Rubric note from the posted solution.}
A correct answer without full rigorous justification would still receive almost full credit; showing only the martingale property earns partial credit.

\paragraph{Part (2) \hfill [10 points]}
Show that for every \(t\ge 0\),
\[
\mathbb P_x(1\le X_t\le N-1)
\le
x(N-x)\left(1-\frac1N\right)^t.
\]

\textbf{Hint used in the official solution:} study
\[
H_t:=X_t(N-X_t).
\]

\textbf{Step 1: compute the conditional expectation of \(H_{t+1}\).}
Given \(X_t\), the random variable \(X_{t+1}\) is binomial:
\[
X_{t+1}\mid X_t \sim \mathrm{Bin}\!\left(N,\frac{X_t}{N}\right).
\]
So
\[
\mathbb E[X_{t+1}\mid X_t]=X_t,
\qquad
\operatorname{Var}(X_{t+1}\mid X_t)=X_t\left(1-\frac{X_t}{N}\right).
\]
Now
\[
H_{t+1}
=
X_{t+1}(N-X_{t+1})
=
N X_{t+1}-X_{t+1}^2.
\]
Therefore
\[
\mathbb E[H_{t+1}\mid X_t]
=
N\mathbb E[X_{t+1}\mid X_t]-\mathbb E[X_{t+1}^2\mid X_t].
\]
Using
\[
\mathbb E[X_{t+1}^2\mid X_t]
=
\operatorname{Var}(X_{t+1}\mid X_t)+\bigl(\mathbb E[X_{t+1}\mid X_t]\bigr)^2,
\]
we get
\begin{align*}
\mathbb E[H_{t+1}\mid X_t]
&=
N X_t-\left[X_t\left(1-\frac{X_t}{N}\right)+X_t^2\right] \\
&=
N X_t-X_t+\frac{X_t^2}{N}-X_t^2 \\
&=
\left(1-\frac1N\right)X_t(N-X_t) \\
&=
\left(1-\frac1N\right)H_t.
\end{align*}

\textbf{Step 2: iterate the recursion.}
Taking expectations gives
\[
\mathbb E[H_{t+1}]
=
\left(1-\frac1N\right)\mathbb E[H_t].
\]
By induction,
\[
\mathbb E[H_t]
=
\left(1-\frac1N\right)^t H_0
=
\left(1-\frac1N\right)^t x(N-x).
\]

\textbf{Step 3: relate \(H_t\) to the event of interest.}
We have
\[
1\le X_t\le N-1
\quad \Longleftrightarrow \quad
H_t=X_t(N-X_t)\ge 1.
\]
Hence by Markov's inequality,
\[
\mathbb P_x(1\le X_t\le N-1)
=
\mathbb P_x(H_t\ge 1)
\le
\mathbb E_x[H_t].
\]
Substituting the formula above gives
\[
\boxed{
\mathbb P_x(1\le X_t\le N-1)
\le
x(N-x)\left(1-\frac1N\right)^t.
}
\]

\begin{summarybox}
The process \(H_t=X_t(N-X_t)\) measures how far the chain is from the absorbing states \(0\) and \(N\). The recursion
\[
\mathbb E[H_{t+1}\mid X_t]=\left(1-\frac1N\right)H_t
\]
shows that this quantity decays geometrically on average.
\end{summarybox}

\subsection*{Question 4 \hfill [25 points]}
Let \((B_t)_{t\ge 0}\) be a Brownian motion.

\paragraph{Part (1) \hfill [5 points]}
Let \(\lambda\in \mathbb R\) be deterministic. Suppose
\[
M_t:=e^{\lambda B_t}-1-\int_0^t f(B_s)\,ds
\]
is a martingale. Find \(f\), and rewrite \(M_t\) as an It\^o integral.

\textbf{Solution.}
Apply It\^o's formula to \(g(x)=e^{\lambda x}\). Since
\[
g'(x)=\lambda e^{\lambda x},
\qquad
g''(x)=\lambda^2 e^{\lambda x},
\]
we obtain
\[
d(e^{\lambda B_t})
=
\lambda e^{\lambda B_t}\,dB_t
+
\frac{\lambda^2}{2}e^{\lambda B_t}\,dt.
\]
Integrating from \(0\) to \(t\) and using \(B_0=0\) gives
\[
e^{\lambda B_t}-1
=
\int_0^t \lambda e^{\lambda B_s}\,dB_s
+
\int_0^t \frac{\lambda^2}{2}e^{\lambda B_s}\,ds.
\]
So the drift term must be exactly cancelled by \(\int_0^t f(B_s)\,ds\). Therefore
\[
\boxed{f(x)=\frac{\lambda^2}{2}e^{\lambda x}.}
\]
Then
\[
\boxed{
M_t
=
\int_0^t \lambda e^{\lambda B_s}\,dB_s.
}
\]

\paragraph{Part (2) \hfill [10 points]}
Compute
\[
\mathbb P\!\left(\max_{0\le t\le 1} B_t\ge 1,\; B_2\le 0\right).
\]
It is acceptable to leave the answer as an integral.

\textbf{Step 1: introduce the first hitting time.}
Let
\[
\tau:=\inf\{t\ge 0:B_t=1\}.
\]
Then the event \(\{\max_{0\le t\le 1}B_t\ge 1\}\) is exactly \(\{\tau\le 1\}\). So
\[
\mathbb P\!\left(\max_{0\le t\le 1} B_t\ge 1,\; B_2\le 0\right)
=
\mathbb P(\tau\le 1,\; B_2\le 0).
\]

\textbf{Step 2: condition on \(\tau\).}
On \(\{\tau\le 1\}\), we know \(B_\tau=1\). By the strong Markov property,
\[
B_2-B_\tau
\mid \tau
\sim \mathcal N(0,\,2-\tau).
\]
Hence
\[
\mathbb P(B_2\le 0\mid \tau)
=
\mathbb P(B_2-B_\tau\le -1\mid \tau)
=
\Phi\!\left(-\frac{1}{\sqrt{2-\tau}}\right),
\]
where \(\Phi\) denotes the standard normal cdf. Therefore
\[
\mathbb P(\tau\le 1,\; B_2\le 0)
=
\mathbb E\!\left[
\mathbf 1_{\{\tau\le 1\}}
\Phi\!\left(-\frac{1}{\sqrt{2-\tau}}\right)
\right].
\]

\textbf{Step 3: use the reflection principle to identify the density of \(\tau\).}
For Brownian motion, the first passage time to level \(1\) has density
\[
f_\tau(t)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi t^3}}e^{-1/(2t)},
\qquad t>0.
\]
This density is derived from the reflection principle. Therefore
\[
\mathbb P\!\left(\max_{0\le t\le 1} B_t\ge 1,\; B_2\le 0\right)
=
\int_0^1
\Phi\!\left(-\frac{1}{\sqrt{2-t}}\right)
\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi t^3}}e^{-1/(2t)}\,dt.
\]

So one acceptable final answer is
\[
\boxed{
\mathbb P\!\left(\max_{0\le t\le 1} B_t\ge 1,\; B_2\le 0\right)
=
\int_0^1
\Phi\!\left(-\frac{1}{\sqrt{2-t}}\right)
\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi t^3}}e^{-1/(2t)}\,dt.
}
\]

\textbf{Comment.}
The essential ideas are:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item convert the maximum event into a hitting-time event;
    \item use the strong Markov property after the first hit;
    \item use the reflection principle to describe the law of the hitting time.
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{Part (3) \hfill [10 points]}
Let
\[
\tau:=\inf\{t\ge 0:|B_t|\ge 1\}.
\]
Compute \(\operatorname{Var}(\tau)\).

\textbf{Step 1: first compute \(\mathbb E[\tau]\).}
Apply optional stopping to the martingale
\[
B_t^2-t.
\]
Since \(B_\tau^2=1\), we obtain
\[
\mathbb E[B_\tau^2-\tau]=\mathbb E[B_0^2]=0,
\]
hence
\[
1-\mathbb E[\tau]=0,
\qquad\text{so}\qquad
\mathbb E[\tau]=1.
\]

\textbf{Step 2: construct the fourth-order martingale.}
By It\^o's formula,
\[
d(B_t^4)=4B_t^3\,dB_t+6B_t^2\,dt.
\]
A short calculation then shows that
\[
M_t:=B_t^4-6tB_t^2+3t^2
\]
is a martingale. Indeed,
\[
dM_t
=
4(B_t^3-3tB_t)\,dB_t.
\]

\textbf{Step 3: stop at \(\tau\).}
At time \(\tau\), we have \(B_\tau^2=1\) and \(B_\tau^4=1\). Optional stopping gives
\[
\mathbb E[M_\tau]=\mathbb E[M_0]=0.
\]
Therefore
\[
\mathbb E\!\left[1-6\tau+3\tau^2\right]=0.
\]
Using \(\mathbb E[\tau]=1\), this becomes
\[
1-6+3\mathbb E[\tau^2]=0,
\]
so
\[
3\mathbb E[\tau^2]=5,
\qquad
\mathbb E[\tau^2]=\frac53.
\]

\textbf{Step 4: compute the variance.}
Thus
\[
\operatorname{Var}(\tau)
=
\mathbb E[\tau^2]-(\mathbb E[\tau])^2
=
\frac53-1
=
\boxed{\frac23.}
\]

\begin{summarybox}
A very standard workflow for Brownian stopping-time moments is:
\[
\text{choose the right polynomial martingale} \;\longrightarrow\; \text{stop it at } \tau \;\longrightarrow\; \text{plug in } B_\tau.
\]
Here \(B_\tau^2=1\) makes everything collapse nicely.
\end{summarybox}

\subsection*{Question 5 \hfill [16 points]}
Prove the following statements.

\paragraph{Part (1) \hfill [8 points]}
Let \((B_t)_{t\ge 0}\) be standard Brownian motion. Suppose \(X_t\) starts from \(X_0=x\) and satisfies
\[
dX_t=-X_t\,dt+dB_t.
\]
Show that \(X_t\) is normally distributed for every \(t>0\), and compute its mean and variance.

\textbf{Step 1: solve the SDE explicitly.}
This is a linear SDE, so multiply by \(e^t\):
\[
d(e^t X_t)=e^t\,dX_t+e^t X_t\,dt=e^t\,dB_t.
\]
Integrating gives
\[
e^t X_t=x+\int_0^t e^s\,dB_s,
\]
hence
\[
\boxed{
X_t=x e^{-t}+\int_0^t e^{-(t-s)}\,dB_s.
}
\]

\textbf{Step 2: identify the distribution.}
The stochastic integral
\[
\int_0^t e^{-(t-s)}\,dB_s
\]
has a deterministic integrand, so it is a centered Gaussian random variable. Therefore \(X_t\) is Gaussian as the sum of a constant and a Gaussian variable.

\textbf{Step 3: compute the mean.}
Since the It\^o integral has mean \(0\),
\[
\mathbb E[X_t]
=
x e^{-t}.
\]

\textbf{Step 4: compute the variance.}
By It\^o isometry,
\[
\operatorname{Var}(X_t)
=
\mathbb E\!\left[\left(\int_0^t e^{-(t-s)}\,dB_s\right)^2\right]
=
\int_0^t e^{-2(t-s)}\,ds.
\]
Compute the integral:
\[
\int_0^t e^{-2(t-s)}\,ds
=
\int_0^t e^{-2u}\,du
=
\frac{1-e^{-2t}}{2}.
\]

So
\[
\boxed{
X_t\sim \mathcal N\!\left(x e^{-t},\;\frac{1-e^{-2t}}{2}\right).
}
\]

\paragraph{Part (2) \hfill [8 points]}
Let \((X_n)_{n\ge 0}\) be a discrete-time process such that \(\mathbb E[|X_n|]<\infty\) and
\[
\mathbb E[X_{n+1}\mid \mathcal F_n]\le X_n
\qquad \text{for all } n.
\]
So \((X_n)\) is a supermartingale. Assume also that \(X_n\ge 0\) almost surely for every \(n\). Prove that there exists a random variable \(X_\infty\) such that
\[
X_n\to X_\infty
\qquad \text{almost surely.}
\]

\textbf{Idea.}
This is the supermartingale convergence theorem. Since the process is nonnegative, its expectations are automatically uniformly bounded:
\[
0\le \mathbb E[X_n]\le \mathbb E[X_0].
\]
That is exactly the condition needed for the upcrossing argument.

\textbf{Detailed proof via upcrossings.}
Fix rational numbers \(0\le a<b\). Let \(U_n[a,b]\) be the number of upcrossings of \([a,b]\) completed by the path \(X_0,X_1,\dots,X_n\).

For a nonnegative supermartingale, the upcrossing inequality gives
\[
(b-a)\,\mathbb E[U_n[a,b]]
\le
\mathbb E[(X_n-a)^-]+\mathbb E[(X_0-a)^+].
\]
Because \(X_n\ge 0\), we have \((X_n-a)^-\le a\), while \((X_0-a)^+\le X_0\). Therefore
\[
(b-a)\,\mathbb E[U_n[a,b]]
\le
a+\mathbb E[X_0].
\]
The right-hand side does not depend on \(n\), so
\[
\sup_n \mathbb E[U_n[a,b]]<\infty.
\]
Letting \(n\to\infty\) and using monotone convergence,
\[
\mathbb E[U_\infty[a,b]]<\infty,
\]
which implies
\[
U_\infty[a,b]<\infty
\qquad \text{almost surely.}
\]

Since this holds for every rational interval \([a,b]\), the sample paths cannot oscillate forever between two different levels. Hence \(X_n(\omega)\) must converge for almost every \(\omega\) to some limit in \([0,\infty]\). Call that limit \(X_\infty\).

Finally, Fatou's lemma gives
\[
\mathbb E[X_\infty]
\le
\liminf_{n\to\infty}\mathbb E[X_n]
\le
\mathbb E[X_0]
<
\infty.
\]
So \(X_\infty<\infty\) almost surely. Therefore
\[
\boxed{
X_n\to X_\infty
\qquad \text{almost surely for some finite random variable } X_\infty.
}
\]

\begin{summarybox}
The nonnegativity assumption is the key simplification:
\[
X_n\ge 0
\quad \Longrightarrow \quad
\mathbb E[X_n]\le \mathbb E[X_0].
\]
That uniform \(L^1\) bound feeds directly into the upcrossing argument and forces almost sure convergence.
\end{summarybox}

