\section{Lecture 8}

\subsection{From one-dimensional simple random walk to Brownian motion}

A useful way to motivate Brownian motion is to start from the one-dimensional simple random walk
\[
X_n=\sum_{i=1}^n \varepsilon_i,
\]
where
\[
\varepsilon_i=
\begin{cases}
+1, & \text{with probability } \frac12,\\[0.3em]
-1, & \text{with probability } \frac12.
\end{cases}
\]

The first basic scaling statement is the central limit theorem:
\[
\frac{X_n}{\sqrt n}\xrightarrow{d}\mathcal N(0,1).
\]

However, if we want a continuous-time limit, then convergence at a single time is not enough. We want the joint behavior of the process at several times.

Fix
\[
0\le t_1<t_2<\cdots<t_k<\infty,
\qquad
n_i=\lfloor nt_i\rfloor.
\]
Then
\[
X_{n_1},\quad X_{n_2}-X_{n_1},\quad \dots,\quad X_{n_k}-X_{n_{k-1}}
\]
are sums of disjoint blocks of i.i.d.\ increments, hence they are independent. After scaling by \(1/\sqrt n\), each block satisfies a central limit theorem:
\[
\frac{X_{n_1}}{\sqrt n}\xrightarrow{d}\mathcal N(0,t_1),
\qquad
\frac{X_{n_2}-X_{n_1}}{\sqrt n}\xrightarrow{d}\mathcal N(0,t_2-t_1),
\]
and similarly for the later increments.

Therefore,
\[
\frac{1}{\sqrt n}
\begin{pmatrix}
X_{n_1}\\
X_{n_2}-X_{n_1}\\
\vdots\\
X_{n_k}-X_{n_{k-1}}
\end{pmatrix}
\xrightarrow{d}
\mathcal N\!\left(
0,
\begin{pmatrix}
t_1 & 0 & \cdots & 0\\
0 & t_2-t_1 & \cdots & 0\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
0 & 0 & \cdots & t_k-t_{k-1}
\end{pmatrix}
\right).
\]

Equivalently, the vector
\[
\frac{1}{\sqrt n}
\bigl(X_{\lfloor nt_1\rfloor},X_{\lfloor nt_2\rfloor},\dots,X_{\lfloor nt_k\rfloor}\bigr)
\]
should converge to a centered Gaussian vector whose covariance is determined by
\[
\operatorname{Cov}(B_s,B_t)=\min\{s,t\}.
\]

This leads to the heuristic scaling-limit picture
\[
\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt n}X_{\lfloor nt\rfloor}:0\le t\le T\right)
\leadsto
(B_t:0\le t\le T),
\]
where the limit process is Brownian motion.

\begin{keyformula}
Brownian motion can be viewed heuristically as the scaling limit of simple random walk:
\[
\frac{1}{\sqrt n}X_{\lfloor nt\rfloor}\leadsto B_t.
\]
Its covariance structure is
\[
\operatorname{Cov}(B_s,B_t)=\min\{s,t\}.
\]
\end{keyformula}

\subsection{Descriptive definition of Brownian motion}

\begin{definition}[Brownian motion / Wiener process]
A stochastic process \((B_t)_{t\ge 0}\) is called a \emph{Brownian motion} if:
\begin{enumerate}[label=\arabic*.]
    \item
    \[
    B_0=0.
    \]
    \item For every \(t_1,\dots,t_k\ge 0\), the random vector
    \[
    (B_{t_1},B_{t_2},\dots,B_{t_k})
    \]
    is multivariate normal.
    \item For every \(t>s\),
    \[
    B_t-B_s\sim \mathcal N(0,t-s),
    \]
    and \(B_t-B_s\) is independent of the past process
    \[
    (B_r)_{0\le r\le s}.
    \]
    \item The sample paths \(t\mapsto B_t(\omega)\) are continuous almost surely.
\end{enumerate}
\end{definition}

A process satisfying property (2) is called a \emph{Gaussian process}. Brownian motion is the most important example.

Condition (3) says two things at once:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item increments over a time interval of length \(t-s\) are Gaussian with mean \(0\) and variance \(t-s\);
    \item increments after time \(s\) are independent of everything observed up to time \(s\).
\end{itemize}

The existence of such a process can be proved using the Kolmogorov extension theorem together with a continuity theorem, but in these notes Brownian motion is taken as a fundamental object.

\subsection{Brownian motion is Markov and strong Markov}

Let
\[
\mathcal F_t=\sigma(B_s:0\le s\le t)
\]
be the natural filtration generated by Brownian motion.

\begin{proposition}[Markov property]
For every fixed \(t\ge 0\),
\[
(B_r:r>t)\ \perp\!\!\!\perp\ (B_r:0\le r\le t)\mid B_t.
\]
Equivalently, conditional on the present value \(B_t\), the future is independent of the past.
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}[Idea]
For every \(r>t\),
\[
B_r=B_t+(B_r-B_t).
\]
The increment \(B_r-B_t\) is independent of \(\mathcal F_t\) by independent increments. Thus the future process can be written as the current position plus a fresh independent Brownian increment process.
\end{proof}

In fact the same statement still holds when the deterministic time \(t\) is replaced by a stopping time. This is the \emph{strong Markov property}.

\begin{remark}
The strong Markov property is the key tool in the reflection principle and many hitting-time arguments. Intuitively, if we stop Brownian motion at a random time determined by the past, then after that time the process restarts like a fresh Brownian motion, independent of what came before.
\end{remark}

\subsection{Brownian motion is a martingale}

\begin{proposition}
\((B_t)_{t\ge 0}\) is a martingale with respect to \((\mathcal F_t)\).
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
First,
\[
\mathbb E[|B_t|]<\infty
\]
for every \(t\ge 0\), because \(B_t\sim\mathcal N(0,t)\).

Now let \(0\le s<t\). Since
\[
B_t=B_s+(B_t-B_s),
\]
and \(B_t-B_s\) is independent of \(\mathcal F_s\) with mean \(0\), we get
\[
\mathbb E[B_t\mid \mathcal F_s]
=
B_s+\mathbb E[B_t-B_s\mid \mathcal F_s]
=
B_s.
\]
So \((B_t)\) is a martingale.
\end{proof}

\subsection{Continuous-time stopping times}

The continuous-time version of a stopping time is the natural analogue of the discrete-time one.

\begin{definition}[Stopping time]
A random time \(T\) is called a \emph{stopping time} with respect to \((\mathcal F_t)\) if for every \(t\ge 0\),
\[
\{T\le t\}\in \mathcal F_t.
\]
\end{definition}

This means that by looking only at the information available up to time \(t\), one can decide whether the random time \(T\) has already occurred.

Typical examples for Brownian motion are hitting times such as
\[
T_a=\inf\{t\ge 0:B_t\ge a\},
\]
or
\[
T=\inf\{t\ge 0:B_t=-a\text{ or }B_t=b\}.
\]

The main properties of stopping times from discrete time extend to the continuous-time setting.

\subsection{Continuous-time optional stopping theorem}

\begin{theorem}[Continuous-time OST]
Let \((X_t)_{t\ge 0}\) be a continuous-time martingale with continuous sample paths, and let \(T\) be a stopping time such that
\[
\mathbb P(T<\infty)=1.
\]
Suppose:
\begin{enumerate}[label=(\roman*)]
    \item
    \[
    \mathbb E[|X_T|]<\infty,
    \]
    \item
    \[
    \lim_{t\to\infty}\mathbb E\!\left[|X_t|\,\mathbf 1_{\{T\ge t\}}\right]=0.
    \]
\end{enumerate}
Then
\[
\mathbb E[X_T]=\mathbb E[X_0].
\]
\end{theorem}

A common sufficient substitute for the tail condition is uniform integrability. In applications one typically constructs a convenient martingale and then checks the hypotheses for a carefully chosen stopping time.

\subsection{Application: continuous-time gambler's ruin for Brownian motion}

Let \((B_t)_{t\ge 0}\) be Brownian motion, and fix \(a,b>0\). Define
\[
T=\inf\{t\ge 0:B_t=-a\text{ or }B_t=b\}.
\]

This is the continuous-time analogue of gambler's ruin: starting from \(0\), the process moves continuously until it first hits one of the two barriers \(-a\) or \(b\).

Because Brownian paths are continuous, at time \(T\) we must have
\[
B_T\in\{-a,b\}.
\]

\subsubsection{The hitting probability}

Before time \(T\), the path stays inside \((-a,b)\), hence
\[
|B_t|\le a\vee b
\qquad \text{for all } t\le T.
\]
So the stopped process \((B_{t\wedge T})\) is bounded, and therefore optional stopping applies to the martingale \(B_t\). We get
\[
\mathbb E[B_T]=\mathbb E[B_0]=0.
\]

Let
\[
p=\mathbb P(B_T=b).
\]
Then
\[
\mathbb P(B_T=-a)=1-p,
\]
and therefore
\[
0=\mathbb E[B_T]=b\,p-a(1-p).
\]
Solving,
\[
bp-a+ap=0
\quad\Longrightarrow\quad
(a+b)p=a.
\]
Hence
\[
\mathbb P(B_T=b)=\frac{a}{a+b},
\qquad
\mathbb P(B_T=-a)=\frac{b}{a+b}.
\]

\begin{keyformula}
For
\[
T=\inf\{t\ge 0:B_t=-a\text{ or }B_t=b\},
\]
one has
\[
\mathbb P(B_T=b)=\frac{a}{a+b},
\qquad
\mathbb P(B_T=-a)=\frac{b}{a+b}.
\]
\end{keyformula}

\subsubsection{A second martingale}

A second useful Brownian martingale is
\[
M_t=B_t^2-t.
\]

\begin{proposition}
\((B_t^2-t)_{t\ge 0}\) is a martingale.
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
Let \(0\le s<t\). Then
\[
B_t=B_s+(B_t-B_s),
\]
so
\[
B_t^2
=
B_s^2+2B_s(B_t-B_s)+(B_t-B_s)^2.
\]
Taking conditional expectation given \(\mathcal F_s\), and using independence of \(B_t-B_s\) from \(\mathcal F_s\), mean \(0\), and variance \(t-s\), we obtain
\[
\mathbb E[B_t^2\mid \mathcal F_s]
=
B_s^2+0+(t-s).
\]
Therefore
\[
\mathbb E[B_t^2-t\mid \mathcal F_s]
=
B_s^2-s.
\]
\end{proof}

\subsubsection[Why OST applies to Mt]{Why OST applies to \texorpdfstring{$M_t$}{Mt}}

To use optional stopping for \(M_t\), we need to check a tail condition. On the event \(\{t\le T\}\), the process has not yet hit either boundary by time \(t\), so
\[
|B_t|\le a\vee b.
\]
Hence on \(\{t\le T\}\),
\[
|M_t|
=
|B_t^2-t|
\le
(a\vee b)^2+t
\le
(a\vee b)^2+T.
\]
Thus
\[
\mathbb E\!\left[|M_t|\,\mathbf 1_{\{T\ge t\}}\right]
\le
\mathbb E\!\left[\bigl((a\vee b)^2+T\bigr)\mathbf 1_{\{T\ge t\}}\right].
\]

So it is enough to show \(\mathbb E[T]<\infty\). The lecture notes indicate the same geometric/block argument as in the discrete-time Markov chain case: there exist constants \(c>0\) and \(t_0>0\) such that
\[
\mathbb P(T\ge k t_0)\le (1-c)^k
\qquad \text{for all } k\ge 1.
\]
Indeed, starting from any point \(x\in(-a,b)\), there is a strictly positive probability, uniformly bounded below, that Brownian motion hits either \(-a\) or \(b\) within time \(t_0\). Iterating this over time blocks gives an exponential tail bound. Consequently
\[
\mathbb E[T]<\infty.
\]
This implies
\[
\mathbb E\!\left[T\,\mathbf 1_{\{T\ge t\}}\right]\to 0
\qquad \text{as } t\to\infty,
\]
so the OST hypotheses are satisfied for \(M_t\).

\begin{proposition}[Exponential tail bound for the exit time]
Let
\[
T:=\inf\{t\ge 0:B_t\notin(-a,b)\},
\]
and for \(x\in(-a,b)\), write \(\mathbb P_x\) and \(\mathbb E_x\) for probability and expectation conditional on \(B_0=x\). Then there exist constants \(c>0\) and \(t_0>0\), depending only on \(a\) and \(b\), such that for every \(x\in(-a,b)\) and every \(k\ge 1\),
\[
\mathbb P_x(T\ge k t_0)\le (1-c)^k.
\]
In particular,
\[
\mathbb E_x[T]<\infty,
\qquad
\mathbb E_x\!\left[T\,\mathbf 1_{\{T\ge t\}}\right]\to 0
\quad \text{as } t\to\infty.
\]
Consequently,
\[
\mathbb E\!\left[|M_t|\,\mathbf 1_{\{T\ge t\}}\right]\to 0,
\]
so the optional stopping hypotheses are satisfied for \(M_t=B_t^2-t\).
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
Fix \(t_0>0\), and set
\[
L:=a+b.
\]
If \(|B_{t_0}-x|\ge L\), then \(B_{t_0}\notin(-a,b)\). Indeed, if \(B_{t_0}-x\ge a+b\), then
\[
B_{t_0}\ge x+a+b>-a+a+b=b,
\]
while if \(B_{t_0}-x\le -(a+b)\), then
\[
B_{t_0}\le x-(a+b)< b-(a+b)=-a.
\]
Since Brownian paths are continuous, the event \(\{B_{t_0}\notin(-a,b)\}\) implies \(\{T\le t_0\}\). Therefore, for every \(x\in(-a,b)\),
\[
\mathbb P_x(T\le t_0)
\ge
\mathbb P_x\bigl(|B_{t_0}-x|\ge a+b\bigr).
\]
But under \(\mathbb P_x\), the increment \(B_{t_0}-x\) has distribution \(N(0,t_0)\), so
\[
\mathbb P_x\bigl(|B_{t_0}-x|\ge a+b\bigr)
=
\mathbb P\bigl(|N(0,t_0)|\ge a+b\bigr)
=:c>0.
\]
Hence
\[
\inf_{x\in(-a,b)}\mathbb P_x(T\le t_0)\ge c,
\qquad
\sup_{x\in(-a,b)}\mathbb P_x(T> t_0)\le 1-c.
\]

Now let \(k\ge 0\). By the Markov property at time \(k t_0\),
\begin{align*}
\mathbb P_x\bigl(T>(k+1)t_0\bigr)
&=
\mathbb E_x\!\left[
\mathbf 1_{\{T>k t_0\}}
\mathbb P_x\bigl(T>(k+1)t_0 \mid \mathcal F_{k t_0}\bigr)
\right] \\
&=
\mathbb E_x\!\left[
\mathbf 1_{\{T>k t_0\}}
\mathbb P_{B_{k t_0}}(T>t_0)
\right].
\end{align*}
On the event \(\{T>k t_0\}\), we have \(B_{k t_0}\in(-a,b)\), so
\[
\mathbb P_{B_{k t_0}}(T>t_0)\le 1-c.
\]
Thus
\[
\mathbb P_x\bigl(T>(k+1)t_0\bigr)
\le
(1-c)\,\mathbb P_x(T>k t_0).
\]
Iterating gives
\[
\mathbb P_x(T>k t_0)\le (1-c)^k,
\]
and therefore also
\[
\mathbb P_x(T\ge k t_0)\le (1-c)^k.
\]

To show integrability, use the tail formula:
\[
\mathbb E_x[T]
=
\int_0^\infty \mathbb P_x(T>t)\,dt.
\]
Splitting the integral into blocks of length \(t_0\),
\begin{align*}
\mathbb E_x[T]
&=
\sum_{k=0}^\infty \int_{k t_0}^{(k+1)t_0}\mathbb P_x(T>t)\,dt \\
&\le
\sum_{k=0}^\infty t_0\,\mathbb P_x(T>k t_0) \\
&\le
t_0\sum_{k=0}^\infty (1-c)^k
=
\frac{t_0}{c}
<\infty.
\end{align*}

Since \(T\in L^1\), dominated convergence gives
\[
\mathbb E_x\!\left[T\,\mathbf 1_{\{T\ge t\}}\right]\to 0
\qquad \text{as } t\to\infty.
\]

Finally, on \(\{t\le T\}\) we have already shown that
\[
|M_t|
=
|B_t^2-t|
\le
(a\vee b)^2+T.
\]
Therefore
\[
\mathbb E\!\left[|M_t|\,\mathbf 1_{\{T\ge t\}}\right]
\le
(a\vee b)^2\,\mathbb P(T\ge t)
+
\mathbb E\!\left[T\,\mathbf 1_{\{T\ge t\}}\right].
\]
The first term tends to \(0\) by the exponential tail bound, and the second tends to \(0\) by the previous paragraph. Hence
\[
\mathbb E\!\left[|M_t|\,\mathbf 1_{\{T\ge t\}}\right]\to 0.
\]
So the optional stopping theorem applies to \(M_t\).
\end{proof}

\subsubsection[Computing E[T]]{Computing \texorpdfstring{$\mathbb E[T]$}{E[T]}}

Applying optional stopping to \(M_t=B_t^2-t\) at time \(T\), we get
\[
0=\mathbb E[M_0]=\mathbb E[M_T]=\mathbb E[B_T^2]-\mathbb E[T].
\]
Hence
\[
\mathbb E[T]=\mathbb E[B_T^2].
\]

But \(B_T\) takes only the values \(-a\) and \(b\), so
\[
\mathbb E[B_T^2]
=
b^2\,\mathbb P(B_T=b)+(-a)^2\,\mathbb P(B_T=-a).
\]
Substituting the probabilities found earlier,
\[
\mathbb E[B_T^2]
=
b^2\frac{a}{a+b}+a^2\frac{b}{a+b}
=
\frac{ab(a+b)}{a+b}
=
ab.
\]
Therefore
\[
\mathbb E[T]=ab.
\]

\begin{keyformula}
For
\[
T=\inf\{t\ge 0:B_t=-a\text{ or }B_t=b\},
\]
we have
\[
\mathbb E[T]=ab.
\]
\end{keyformula}

\begin{remark}
The lecture notes also point out that one can go further and compute moments or Laplace transforms such as
\[
\mathbb E[e^{-\lambda T}],
\]
although that is not developed here.
\end{remark}

\subsection{Reflection principle}

Let \(a>0\), and define the first hitting time of level \(a\) by
\[
T_a=\inf\{t\ge 0:B_t\ge a\}.
\]

We want to compute the distribution of \(T_a\), i.e.
\[
\mathbb P(T_a\le t)
\qquad \text{for } t>0.
\]

Because Brownian paths are continuous,
\[
\{T_a\le t\}
=
\left\{\max_{0\le s\le t} B_s\ge a\right\}.
\]

\subsubsection{Decomposing the event}

The event \(\{T_a\le t\}\) can be split into two disjoint cases:
\[
\{T_a\le t\}
=
\{T_a\le t,\ B_t<a\}
\cup
\{T_a\le t,\ B_t\ge a\}.
\]
Since \(B_t\) has a continuous distribution,
\[
\mathbb P(B_t=a)=0,
\]
so there is no ambiguity at the boundary.

The second case is simply
\[
\{B_t\ge a\},
\]
because if the endpoint is already above \(a\), the path must have hit \(a\) somewhere before time \(t\). Thus
\[
\mathbb P(T_a\le t,\ B_t\ge a)=\mathbb P(B_t\ge a).
\]

The reflection argument shows that the first case has the same probability as the second case.

\subsubsection{A rigorous argument using strong Markov}

We compute
\[
\mathbb P(B_t\ge a)
=
\mathbb P(T_a\le t)\,\mathbb P(B_t\ge a\mid T_a\le t).
\]
To evaluate the conditional probability, note that on the event \(\{T_a\le t\}\), we have \(B_{T_a}=a\). Therefore
\[
\{B_t\ge a\}
=
\{B_t-B_{T_a}\ge 0\}.
\]
By the strong Markov property, conditional on \(\{T_a\le t\}\), the process
\[
(B_{T_a+u}-B_{T_a})_{u\ge 0}
\]
is a fresh Brownian motion, independent of the past. So
\[
\mathbb P(B_t-B_{T_a}\ge 0\mid T_a\le t)=\frac12.
\]
Hence
\[
\mathbb P(B_t\ge a)=\frac12\,\mathbb P(T_a\le t),
\]
which implies
\[
\mathbb P(T_a\le t)=2\,\mathbb P(B_t\ge a).
\]

Since \(B_t\sim\mathcal N(0,t)\),
\[
\mathbb P(B_t\ge a)
=
\mathbb P\!\left(\frac{B_t}{\sqrt t}\ge \frac{a}{\sqrt t}\right)
=
1-\Phi\!\left(\frac{a}{\sqrt t}\right)
=
\Phi\!\left(-\frac{a}{\sqrt t}\right).
\]
Therefore
\[
\mathbb P(T_a\le t)=2\Phi\!\left(-\frac{a}{\sqrt t}\right).
\]

\begin{keyformula}
For every \(a>0\) and \(t>0\),
\[
\mathbb P(T_a\le t)
=
2\,\mathbb P(B_t\ge a)
=
2\Phi\!\left(-\frac{a}{\sqrt t}\right).
\]
Equivalently,
\[
\mathbb P\!\left(\max_{0\le s\le t} B_s\ge a\right)
=
2\mathbb P(B_t\ge a).
\]
\end{keyformula}

\subsubsection{A more detailed joint-distribution identity}

The reflection principle can be sharpened to compute the joint distribution of \((T_a,B_t)\). Fix \(b<a\). Then
\[
\mathbb P(T_a\le t,\ B_t\le b)
=
\mathbb P(B_t\ge 2a-b).
\]

Here is the calculation. Start with
\[
\mathbb P(T_a\le t,\ B_t\le b)
=
\mathbb P(T_a\le t)\,\mathbb P(B_t\le b\mid T_a\le t).
\]
Since \(B_{T_a}=a\),
\[
\{B_t\le b\}
=
\{B_t-B_{T_a}\le -(a-b)\}.
\]
By symmetry of Brownian increments,
\[
\mathbb P(B_t-B_{T_a}\le -(a-b)\mid T_a\le t)
=
\mathbb P(B_t-B_{T_a}\ge a-b\mid T_a\le t).
\]
Again by the strong Markov property, the increment after \(T_a\) is a fresh Brownian motion, so
\[
\mathbb P(B_t-B_{T_a}\ge a-b\mid T_a\le t)
=
\mathbb P(T_a\le t,\ B_t\ge 2a-b)\Big/\mathbb P(T_a\le t).
\]
Hence
\[
\mathbb P(T_a\le t,\ B_t\le b)
=
\mathbb P(T_a\le t,\ B_t\ge 2a-b).
\]
But the event \(\{B_t\ge 2a-b\}\) already implies \(\{T_a\le t\}\), because \(2a-b>a\). Therefore
\[
\mathbb P(T_a\le t,\ B_t\ge 2a-b)
=
\mathbb P(B_t\ge 2a-b).
\]
So we conclude
\[
\mathbb P(T_a\le t,\ B_t\le b)=\mathbb P(B_t\ge 2a-b),
\qquad b<a.
\]

\subsubsection{A corollary}

Taking \(b\uparrow a\) in the preceding identity gives
\[
\mathbb P(T_a\le t)=2\mathbb P(B_t\ge a).
\]
This can also be written as
\[
\mathbb P(T_a\le t)=\mathbb P(|B_t|\ge a).
\]
Since
\[
\{T_a\le t\}
=
\left\{\max_{0\le s\le t}B_s\ge a\right\},
\]
we obtain
\[
\mathbb P\!\left(\max_{0\le s\le t} B_s\ge a\right)
=
\mathbb P(|B_t|\ge a)
\qquad (\forall a>0).
\]
Hence
\[
\max_{0\le s\le t} B_s
\overset{d}=|B_t|.
\]

\begin{keyformula}
A standard corollary of the reflection principle is
\[
\max_{0\le s\le t} B_s \overset{d}= |B_t|.
\]
\end{keyformula}

\subsubsection{Formal Statement of Reflection Principle}

\begin{theorem}[Reflection Principle]
Let \((B_t)_{t\ge 0}\) be a standard Brownian motion, and let \(a>0\). Then for every \(t>0\) and every \(x\le a\),
\[
\mathbb P\!\left(\max_{0\le s\le t} B_s \ge a,\; B_t\le x\right)
=
\mathbb P(B_t\ge 2a-x).
\]
In particular,
\[
\mathbb P\!\left(\max_{0\le s\le t} B_s \ge a\right)
=
2\,\mathbb P(B_t\ge a).
\]
\end{theorem}

\begin{corollary}[Distribution of the First Hitting Time]
Let
\[
T_a=\inf\{t\ge 0:B_t\ge a\}, \qquad a>0.
\]
Then for every \(t>0\),
\[
\mathbb P(T_a\le t)
=
\mathbb P\!\left(\max_{0\le s\le t} B_s\ge a\right)
=
2\,\mathbb P(B_t\ge a).
\]
Since \(B_t\sim N(0,t)\), it follows that
\[
\mathbb P(T_a\le t)
=
2\left(1-\Phi\!\left(\frac{a}{\sqrt t}\right)\right),
\]
where \(\Phi\) denotes the standard normal distribution function.
Equivalently,
\[
\mathbb P(T_a>t)
=
2\Phi\!\left(\frac{a}{\sqrt t}\right)-1.
\]
\end{corollary}

\begin{proof}
Because Brownian paths are continuous,
\[
\{T_a\le t\}
=
\left\{\max_{0\le s\le t} B_s\ge a\right\}.
\]
Therefore, by the reflection principle,
\[
\mathbb P(T_a\le t)
=
\mathbb P\!\left(\max_{0\le s\le t} B_s\ge a\right)
=
2\,\mathbb P(B_t\ge a).
\]
Finally, since \(B_t\sim N(0,t)\),
\[
\mathbb P(B_t\ge a)
=
1-\Phi\!\left(\frac{a}{\sqrt t}\right),
\]
which gives
\[
\mathbb P(T_a\le t)
=
2\left(1-\Phi\!\left(\frac{a}{\sqrt t}\right)\right).
\]
\end{proof}


\subsection{Stochastic calculus: why ordinary calculus breaks down}

The goal is to make sense of a ``calculus'' for Brownian motion. A first difficulty is that Brownian paths are far too rough for ordinary differentiation.

For small \(\Delta t>0\),
\[
B_{t+\Delta t}-B_t\sim \mathcal N(0,\Delta t),
\]
so
\[
\frac{B_{t+\Delta t}-B_t}{\Delta t}
\sim
\mathcal N\!\left(0,\frac{1}{\Delta t}\right).
\]
Therefore the variance of the difference quotient blows up as \(\Delta t\to 0\):
\[
\operatorname{Var}\!\left(\frac{B_{t+\Delta t}-B_t}{\Delta t}\right)=\frac{1}{\Delta t}\to\infty.
\]
So Brownian motion is not differentiable in the ordinary sense. In fact, almost surely Brownian paths are continuous everywhere but differentiable nowhere.

\subsection[The practical problem: defining the stochastic integral]{The practical problem: define \texorpdfstring{$\int_0^t Y_s\,dB_s$}{the stochastic integral}}

In practice we want to define
\[
\int_0^t Y_s\,dB_s,
\]
where \((Y_t)_{t\ge 0}\) is an adapted stochastic process, meaning that \(Y_t\) is determined by the Brownian path up to time \(t\).

For an ordinary Riemann integral,
\[
\int_0^T f(t)\,dt
=
\lim_{\Delta t\to 0}
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1} f(\xi_i)\Delta t,
\]
and the limit is independent of the sample points \(\xi_i\).

For an ordinary Stieltjes integral with a sufficiently nice integrator \(g\),
\[
\int_0^T f(t)\,dg(t)
=
\lim_{\Delta t\to 0}
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}
f(\xi_i)\bigl(g((i+1)\Delta t)-g(i\Delta t)\bigr),
\]
again with a limit independent of the sample-point choice.

The lecture notes emphasize that for Brownian motion this independence fails:
\[
\int_0^T Y_s\,dB_s
\neq
\lim_{\Delta t\to 0}
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}
Y_{\xi_i}\bigl(B_{(i+1)\Delta t}-B_{i\Delta t}\bigr)
\]
unless we specify \emph{how} the sample points \(\xi_i\) are chosen.

\subsection{Detailed example: \(Y_t=B_t\)}

Consider
\[
Y_t=B_t
\qquad (\forall t),
\]
and the candidate integral
\[
\int_0^T B_t\,dB_t.
\]
Take the Riemann-type sum
\[
S_N(\xi)
=
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}
\bigl(B_{(i+1)\Delta t}-B_{i\Delta t}\bigr)\,B_{\xi_i},
\qquad
\Delta t=\frac{T}{N}.
\]

We now compare different choices of the sample points \(\xi_i\).

\subsubsection{Decomposition of the sum}

For each interval \([i\Delta t,(i+1)\Delta t]\), write
\[
B_{\xi_i}
=
B_{i\Delta t}+\bigl(B_{\xi_i}-B_{i\Delta t}\bigr).
\]
Then
\[
S_N(\xi)
=
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}
\bigl(B_{(i+1)\Delta t}-B_{i\Delta t}\bigr)B_{i\Delta t}
+
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}
\bigl(B_{(i+1)\Delta t}-B_{i\Delta t}\bigr)\bigl(B_{\xi_i}-B_{i\Delta t}\bigr).
\]
Call the two pieces
\[
S_N(\xi)=\text{Term 1}+\text{Term 2}.
\]

\subsubsection{Left-endpoint choice}

If we choose the left endpoint
\[
\xi_i=i\Delta t,
\]
then
\[
B_{\xi_i}-B_{i\Delta t}=0,
\]
so
\[
\text{Term 2}=0.
\]
Thus the left-endpoint sum is
\[
S_N^{\mathrm{left}}
=
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}
B_{i\Delta t}\bigl(B_{(i+1)\Delta t}-B_{i\Delta t}\bigr).
\]

This is the It\^o choice.

\subsubsection{Midpoint choice}

Now choose the midpoint
\[
\xi_i=\left(i+\frac12\right)\Delta t.
\]
Then
\[
\text{Term 2}
=
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}
\bigl(B_{(i+1)\Delta t}-B_{i\Delta t}\bigr)
\bigl(B_{(i+\frac12)\Delta t}-B_{i\Delta t}\bigr).
\]

Write
\[
A_i=B_{(i+\frac12)\Delta t}-B_{i\Delta t},
\qquad
C_i=B_{(i+1)\Delta t}-B_{(i+\frac12)\Delta t}.
\]
Then
\[
B_{(i+1)\Delta t}-B_{i\Delta t}=A_i+C_i,
\]
so the \(i\)-th summand in Term 2 is
\[
(A_i+C_i)A_i=A_i^2+A_iC_i.
\]

Because Brownian increments over disjoint subintervals are independent,
\[
A_i\sim \mathcal N\!\left(0,\frac{\Delta t}{2}\right),
\qquad
C_i\sim \mathcal N\!\left(0,\frac{\Delta t}{2}\right),
\qquad
A_i \perp C_i.
\]
Hence
\[
\mathbb E[A_iC_i]=0,
\qquad
\mathbb E[A_i^2]=\frac{\Delta t}{2}.
\]
Therefore the expectation of each summand is
\[
\mathbb E[(A_i+C_i)A_i]=\frac{\Delta t}{2}.
\]

The lecture notes then use the strong law of large numbers: the terms in the summation are i.i.d., each with mean \(\Delta t/2\), so summing \(N\) such terms gives approximately
\[
N\cdot \frac{\Delta t}{2}
=
N\cdot \frac{T}{2N}
=
\frac{T}{2}.
\]
Thus
\[
\text{Term 2}\to \frac{T}{2}
\qquad \text{(in the sense indicated in the notes)},
\]
not \(0\).

So the midpoint rule and the left-endpoint rule do \emph{not} lead to the same limit.

\begin{keyformula}
For the example \(Y_t=B_t\),
\[
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1} B_{\xi_i}\bigl(B_{(i+1)\Delta t}-B_{i\Delta t}\bigr)
\]
depends on the choice of \(\xi_i\). In particular:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item left endpoints give one limit;
    \item midpoints produce an extra contribution of size \(T/2\).
\end{itemize}
So different sampling rules lead to different stochastic integrals.
\end{keyformula}

\begin{remark}
This is the fundamental reason one must specify a convention in stochastic calculus. The It\^o convention uses left endpoints. Another important convention, leading to the Stratonovich integral, uses symmetric or midpoint-type approximations.
\end{remark}

\subsection{Why choose left endpoints? Martingale and \(L^2\)-isometry}

The lecture motivates the left-endpoint rule by analogy with discrete-time martingales and betting strategies.

Suppose \((X_t)_{t\ge 0}\) is a discrete-time martingale, and \((Y_t)_{t\ge 0}\) is an adapted process (a ``betting strategy''). Define
\[
M_t=\sum_{k=0}^{t-1}Y_k(X_{k+1}-X_k).
\]
Then \(M_t\) is again a martingale, because the multiplier \(Y_k\) is chosen using information available at time \(k\), before the increment \(X_{k+1}-X_k\) occurs.

Moreover, in the simple random walk case,
\[
\mathbb E[M_t^2]
=
\sum_{k=0}^{t-1}\mathbb E\!\left[Y_k^2(X_{k+1}-X_k)^2\right].
\]
So using left endpoints naturally preserves two very useful properties:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item the martingale property;
    \item an \(L^2\)-isometry.
\end{itemize}

The It\^o integral is designed to preserve exactly these two features.

\subsection{Roadmap for defining the It\^o integral}

We proceed in two steps:
\begin{enumerate}[label=\arabic*.]
    \item Define the integral for piecewise-constant adapted processes.
    \item Extend the definition to more general adapted continuous processes by \(L^2\)-approximation.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Step 1: piecewise-constant adapted processes}

Let
\[
0=t_0<t_1<\cdots<t_n
\]
be deterministic times, and let
\[
Y_t=Y^{(i)}
\qquad \text{for } t\in [t_i,t_{i+1}),
\]
where each random variable \(Y^{(i)}\) is \(\mathcal F_{t_i}\)-measurable.

So \(Y\) is piecewise constant, and on each interval \([t_i,t_{i+1})\), its value is chosen using only information available at the left endpoint \(t_i\).

For such a process, define
\[
\int_0^T Y_t\,dB_t
:=
\sum_{t_{i+1}\le T} Y^{(i)}(B_{t_{i+1}}-B_{t_i})
+
Y^{(i_0)}(B_T-B_{t_{i_0}}),
\]
where
\[
i_0=\max\{i:t_i\le T\}.
\]

This is exactly the left-endpoint construction.

\subsubsection{Martingale property}

For piecewise-constant adapted \(Y\), the process
\[
\left(\int_0^t Y_s\,dB_s\right)_{t\ge 0}
\]
is a martingale.

The reason is the same as in discrete time: on each interval, the coefficient multiplying the increment is measurable with respect to the past, while the Brownian increment has conditional mean \(0\).

\subsubsection{It\^o isometry for simple processes}

For piecewise-constant adapted \(Y\),
\[
\mathbb E\!\left[\left(\int_0^T Y_t\,dB_t\right)^2\right]
=
\int_0^T \mathbb E[Y_t^2]\,dt.
\]

\begin{proof}[Computation]
Write
\[
\int_0^T Y_t\,dB_t
=
\sum_{i=0}^{n-1} Y^{(i)}(B_{t_{i+1}}-B_{t_i}).
\]
Squaring gives
\[
\left(\sum_{i=0}^{n-1} Y^{(i)}\Delta B_i\right)^2
=
\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}(Y^{(i)})^2(\Delta B_i)^2
+
2\sum_{i<j} Y^{(i)}Y^{(j)}\Delta B_i\Delta B_j,
\]
where
\[
\Delta B_i=B_{t_{i+1}}-B_{t_i}.
\]
The cross terms vanish in expectation because disjoint Brownian increments are independent and centered. Thus
\[
\mathbb E\!\left[\left(\int_0^T Y_t\,dB_t\right)^2\right]
=
\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}\mathbb E\!\left[(Y^{(i)})^2(\Delta B_i)^2\right].
\]
Since \(Y^{(i)}\) is \(\mathcal F_{t_i}\)-measurable and \(\Delta B_i\) is independent of \(\mathcal F_{t_i}\) with variance \(t_{i+1}-t_i\),
\[
\mathbb E\!\left[(Y^{(i)})^2(\Delta B_i)^2\right]
=
\mathbb E[(Y^{(i)})^2](t_{i+1}-t_i).
\]
So
\[
\mathbb E\!\left[\left(\int_0^T Y_t\,dB_t\right)^2\right]
=
\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}\mathbb E[(Y^{(i)})^2](t_{i+1}-t_i)
=
\int_0^T \mathbb E[Y_t^2]\,dt.
\]
\end{proof}

\begin{keyformula}
For piecewise-constant adapted \(Y\),
\[
\left(\int_0^t Y_s\,dB_s\right)_{t\ge 0}
\text{ is a martingale,}
\]
and
\[
\mathbb E\!\left[\left(\int_0^T Y_t\,dB_t\right)^2\right]
=
\int_0^T \mathbb E[Y_t^2]\,dt.
\]
\end{keyformula}

\subsection{Step 2: extension to adapted continuous processes}

Now let \((Y_t)_{t\ge 0}\) be an adapted process with continuous sample paths.

Fix \(T>0\), and for each \(n\ge 1\), let
\[
\Delta t=\frac{T}{n}.
\]
Define the piecewise-constant approximation
\[
Y_t^{(n)}=Y_{i\Delta t}
\qquad \text{for } t\in [i\Delta t,(i+1)\Delta t).
\]

Since \(Y\) is continuous, piecewise-constant functions are dense in the relevant \(L^2\) sense:
\[
\lim_{n\to\infty}\int_0^T \mathbb E\!\left[\left|Y_t-Y_t^{(n)}\right|^2\right]dt=0.
\]

Therefore,
\[
\lim_{m,n\to\infty}\int_0^T \mathbb E\!\left[\left|Y_t^{(m)}-Y_t^{(n)}\right|^2\right]dt=0.
\]
Using the isometry for simple processes,
\[
\mathbb E\!\left[
\left|
\int_0^T Y_t^{(m)}\,dB_t
-
\int_0^T Y_t^{(n)}\,dB_t
\right|^2
\right]
=
\int_0^T \mathbb E\!\left[\left|Y_t^{(m)}-Y_t^{(n)}\right|^2\right]dt
\to 0.
\]
So the sequence
\[
\left(\int_0^T Y_t^{(n)}\,dB_t\right)_{n\ge 1}
\]
is Cauchy in \(L^2\), and therefore converges in \(L^2\).

\begin{definition}[It\^o integral]
We define
\[
\int_0^T Y_t\,dB_t
\]
to be the \(L^2\)-limit of the integrals of piecewise-constant adapted approximations \(Y^{(n)}\).
\end{definition}

This limit is called the \emph{It\^o integral}.

\subsection{Basic properties of the It\^o integral}

The properties valid for the approximating simple processes pass to the limit.

\begin{theorem}[Basic properties of the It\^o integral]
Let \(Y\) be adapted with continuous sample paths and
\[
\int_0^T \mathbb E[Y_t^2]\,dt<\infty.
\]
Then:
\begin{enumerate}[label=\arabic*.]
    \item The process
    \[
    \left(\int_0^t Y_s\,dB_s\right)_{t\ge 0}
    \]
    is a martingale.
    \item The It\^o isometry holds:
    \[
    \mathbb E\!\left[\left(\int_0^T Y_s\,dB_s\right)^2\right]
    =
    \int_0^T \mathbb E[Y_s^2]\,ds.
    \]
    \item The integral is linear:
    \[
    \int_0^t (aY_s^{(1)}+bY_s^{(2)})\,dB_s
    =
    a\int_0^t Y_s^{(1)}\,dB_s
    +
    b\int_0^t Y_s^{(2)}\,dB_s.
    \]
\end{enumerate}
\end{theorem}

\begin{remark}
The lecture notes emphasize that the left-endpoint convention is not arbitrary. It is chosen specifically because it preserves the martingale property and the \(L^2\)-isometry, which are the continuous-time analogues of the key discrete-time betting-strategy identities.
\end{remark}

\subsection{Summary}

\begin{summarybox}
Lecture 8 introduces Brownian motion and the first ideas of stochastic calculus.

Main points:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item Brownian motion is motivated as the scaling limit of one-dimensional simple random walk.
    \item Brownian motion is a Gaussian process with independent increments and continuous sample paths.
    \item It is Markov, strong Markov, and a martingale.
    \item Continuous-time stopping times and optional stopping allow one to solve hitting problems.
    \item For
    \[
    T=\inf\{t\ge 0:B_t=-a\text{ or }B_t=b\},
    \]
    we have
    \[
    \mathbb P(B_T=b)=\frac{a}{a+b},
    \qquad
    \mathbb E[T]=ab.
    \]
    \item The reflection principle gives
    \[
    \mathbb P(T_a\le t)=2\mathbb P(B_t\ge a)=2\Phi\!\left(-\frac{a}{\sqrt t}\right),
    \]
    and more generally
    \[
    \mathbb P(T_a\le t,\ B_t\le b)=\mathbb P(B_t\ge 2a-b)
    \qquad (b<a).
    \]
    \item Consequently,
    \[
    \max_{0\le s\le t} B_s \overset{d}= |B_t|.
    \]
    \item Ordinary Riemann--Stieltjes ideas fail for Brownian motion because the limit can depend on sample-point choices.
    \item In the example \(Y_t=B_t\), midpoint and left-endpoint rules differ by an extra contribution of size \(T/2\).
    \item The It\^o integral is defined using left endpoints, first for piecewise-constant adapted processes, then extended by \(L^2\)-approximation.
    \item The resulting integral preserves the martingale property, linearity, and the It\^o isometry
    \[
    \mathbb E\!\left[\left(\int_0^T Y_t\,dB_t\right)^2\right]
    =
    \int_0^T \mathbb E[Y_t^2]\,dt.
    \]
\end{itemize}
\end{summarybox}

