\section{Lecture 9}

\subsection{Recall from Lecture 8: the It\^o integral}

Recall that in the previous lecture we defined
\[
\int_0^T Y_t\,dB_t
\]
for adapted continuous processes \((Y_t)_{t\ge 0}\) by first defining the integral for piecewise-constant adapted processes and then taking an \(L^2\)-limit.

The key properties established there were:

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item if \((Y_t)_{t\ge 0}\) is adapted and continuous, then
    \[
    \left(\int_0^t Y_s\,dB_s\right)_{t\ge 0}
    \]
    is a martingale;
    \item the It\^o isometry:
    \[
    \mathbb E\!\left[\left(\int_0^t Y_s\,dB_s\right)^2\right]
    =
    \int_0^t \mathbb E[Y_s^2]\,ds;
    \]
    \item linearity:
    \[
    \int_0^t \bigl(aY_s^{(1)}+bY_s^{(2)}\bigr)\,dB_s
    =
    a\int_0^t Y_s^{(1)}\,dB_s
    +
    b\int_0^t Y_s^{(2)}\,dB_s.
    \]
\end{itemize}

The question for Lecture 9 is: what is the stochastic analogue of the fundamental theorem of calculus and the differential-chain-rule formalism?

\subsection{Why the ordinary fundamental theorem of calculus fails}

In ordinary calculus, if \(f\) is differentiable, then
\[
\int_a^b f'(x)\,dx=f(b)-f(a),
\]
and in differential form one writes
\[
df(x)=f'(x)\,dx.
\]

A natural guess would be that for Brownian motion one should have
\[
\int_0^T f'(B_t)\,dB_t
\overset{?}{=}
f(B_T)-f(B_0).
\]
Lecture 9 begins by explaining that this is false for the It\^o integral.

\subsection{Counterexample: \(f(x)=\tfrac12 x^2\)}

Take
\[
f(x)=\frac12 x^2,
\qquad
f'(x)=x.
\]
If the ordinary chain rule were valid, then we would expect
\[
\int_0^T f'(B_t)\,dB_t
=
\int_0^T B_t\,dB_t
=
f(B_T)-f(B_0)
=
\frac12 B_T^2-\frac12 B_0^2
=
\frac12 B_T^2.
\]

But this cannot be correct. Indeed, from the previous lecture we know that
\[
\left(\int_0^t B_s\,dB_s\right)_{t\ge 0}
\]
is a martingale. In particular,
\[
\mathbb E\!\left[\int_0^T B_t\,dB_t\right]=0.
\]
On the other hand,
\[
\mathbb E\!\left[\frac12 B_T^2\right]
=
\frac12 \mathbb E[B_T^2]
=
\frac12 T
>
0.
\]
So the identity
\[
\int_0^T B_t\,dB_t=\frac12 B_T^2
\]
cannot hold.

This shows that the stochastic chain rule must contain an extra term.

\subsection{Statement of It\^o's formula for Brownian motion}

\begin{theorem}[It\^o's formula for \(f(B_t)\)]
Suppose \(f\in C^2(\mathbb R)\). Then for every \(T\ge 0\),
\[
f(B_T)-f(B_0)
=
\int_0^T f'(B_t)\,dB_t
+
\frac12\int_0^T f''(B_t)\,dt.
\]
Equivalently, in differential form,
\[
df(B_t)=f'(B_t)\,dB_t+\frac12 f''(B_t)\,dt.
\]
\end{theorem}

So the It\^o chain rule differs from the ordinary chain rule by the correction term
\[
\frac12 f''(B_t)\,dt.
\]

\subsection{Checking the counterexample again}

Take
\[
f(x)=\frac12 x^2.
\]
Then
\[
f'(x)=x,
\qquad
f''(x)=1.
\]
So It\^o's formula gives
\[
\frac12 B_T^2-\frac12 B_0^2
=
\int_0^T B_t\,dB_t+\frac12\int_0^T 1\,dt.
\]
Since \(B_0=0\), this becomes
\[
\frac12 B_T^2
=
\int_0^T B_t\,dB_t+\frac12 T.
\]
Therefore
\[
\int_0^T B_t\,dB_t
=
\frac12 B_T^2-\frac12 T.
\]

This agrees with the fact already verified in Lecture 8 that
\[
(B_t^2-t)_{t\ge 0}
\]
is a martingale.

\begin{keyformula}
For \(f(x)=\frac12 x^2\),
\[
\int_0^T B_t\,dB_t=\frac12 B_T^2-\frac12 T.
\]
So the missing term in the naive chain rule is exactly \(-T/2\).
\end{keyformula}

\subsection{Systematic martingale construction from It\^o's formula}

A major consequence of It\^o's formula is that for every \(f\in C^2(\mathbb R)\),
\[
\left(
f(B_t)-f(B_0)-\frac12\int_0^t f''(B_s)\,ds
\right)_{t\ge 0}
\]
is a martingale, because it equals the It\^o integral
\[
\int_0^t f'(B_s)\,dB_s.
\]

For example, if
\[
f(x)=e^x,
\]
then
\[
f'(x)=e^x,
\qquad
f''(x)=e^x.
\]
Therefore
\[
d(e^{B_t})=e^{B_t}\,dB_t+\frac12 e^{B_t}\,dt,
\]
and hence
\[
\left(
e^{B_t}-\frac12\int_0^t e^{B_s}\,ds
\right)_{t\ge 0}
\]
is a martingale.

\subsection{Remark on midpoint sums and the Stratonovich integral}

Lecture 9 also recalls the remark from Lecture 8 that if one defines the stochastic integral using midpoint choices
\[
\xi_i=\frac{t_i+t_{i+1}}{2}
\]
instead of left endpoints, then one gets a different object, the \emph{Stratonovich integral}. For that integral one has the ordinary chain rule:
\[
\int_0^T f'(B_t)\circ dB_t=f(B_T)-f(B_0).
\]

However, the martingale property that makes the It\^o integral so useful is then lost. So:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item It\^o integration preserves martingale structure and produces the correction term;
    \item Stratonovich integration restores the ordinary chain rule but sacrifices that martingale structure.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Proof idea of It\^o's formula for \(f(B_t)\)}

We now explain the proof idea from the notes.

Take a partition
\[
0=t_0<t_1<\cdots<t_N=T,
\qquad
t_{i+1}-t_i=\Delta t=\frac{T}{N}.
\]
Then
\[
f(B_T)-f(B_0)
=
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}\bigl(f(B_{t_{i+1}})-f(B_{t_i})\bigr).
\]

Since \(f\in C^2\), Taylor expansion gives
\[
f(B_{t_{i+1}})-f(B_{t_i})
=
f'(B_{t_i})(B_{t_{i+1}}-B_{t_i})
+
\frac12 f''(B_{t_i})(B_{t_{i+1}}-B_{t_i})^2
+
o\!\left(|B_{t_{i+1}}-B_{t_i}|^2\right).
\]

Summing over \(i\), we obtain
\[
f(B_T)-f(B_0)
=
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1} f'(B_{t_i})(B_{t_{i+1}}-B_{t_i})
+
\frac12\sum_{i=0}^{N-1} f''(B_{t_i})(B_{t_{i+1}}-B_{t_i})^2
+
R_N,
\]
where the remainder \(R_N\to 0\) in the relevant sense as \(N\to\infty\).

The first sum is precisely the left-endpoint stochastic integral approximation to
\[
\int_0^T f'(B_t)\,dB_t.
\]

So the key issue is the second-order term. In ordinary calculus one would discard it because \((\Delta x)^2\) is negligible. For Brownian motion it is not negligible, because Brownian increments are of order \(\sqrt{\Delta t}\), so their squares are of order \(\Delta t\).

\subsection{The key step: Brownian quadratic variation}

The crucial fact is
\[
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}(B_{t_{i+1}}-B_{t_i})^2 \to T
\qquad \text{as } N\to\infty.
\]

In the special case
\[
f(x)=\frac12 x^2,
\]
this gives
\[
\frac12\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}(B_{t_{i+1}}-B_{t_i})^2\to \frac12 T.
\]

This is the Brownian \emph{quadratic variation}. Since the increments are independent with
\[
B_{t_{i+1}}-B_{t_i}\sim \mathcal N(0,\Delta t),
\]
their squares behave like i.i.d.\ variables with mean \(\Delta t\). Summing over \(N\) intervals yields a total of order
\[
N\Delta t=T.
\]

Thus the second-order term does not vanish. It converges to
\[
\frac12\int_0^T f''(B_t)\,dt.
\]

\begin{proposition}[Weighted quadratic variation]
Let \((B_t)_{0\le t\le T}\) be a standard Brownian motion, and let
\[
t_i=\frac{iT}{N},\qquad \Delta t=\frac{T}{N},\qquad \Delta_i B:=B_{t_{i+1}}-B_{t_i}.
\]
Assume \(f\in C^2(\mathbb R)\) and that \(f''\) is bounded. Then
\[
\frac12\sum_{i=0}^{N-1} f''(B_{t_i})(\Delta_i B)^2
\;\xrightarrow[N\to\infty]{\mathbb P}\;
\frac12\int_0^T f''(B_t)\,dt.
\]
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
Set
\[
S_N:=\sum_{i=0}^{N-1} f''(B_{t_i})(\Delta_i B)^2.
\]
Add and subtract the Riemann sum \(\sum_{i=0}^{N-1} f''(B_{t_i})\Delta t\):
\[
S_N-\int_0^T f''(B_t)\,dt
=
A_N+M_N,
\]
where
\[
A_N:=\sum_{i=0}^{N-1} f''(B_{t_i})\Delta t-\int_0^T f''(B_t)\,dt
\]
and
\[
M_N:=\sum_{i=0}^{N-1} f''(B_{t_i})\big((\Delta_i B)^2-\Delta t\big).
\]

Since Brownian paths are continuous, the function
\[
t\longmapsto f''(B_t)
\]
is almost surely continuous on \([0,T]\). Therefore \(A_N\to 0\) almost surely by ordinary Riemann-sum convergence.

It remains to show that \(M_N\to 0\) in \(L^2\). Write
\[
\eta_i:=(\Delta_i B)^2-\Delta t.
\]
Then
\[
M_N=\sum_{i=0}^{N-1} f''(B_{t_i})\eta_i.
\]
Hence
\[
\mathbb E[M_N^2]
=
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}\mathbb E\!\left[f''(B_{t_i})^2\eta_i^2\right]
+
2\sum_{0\le i<j\le N-1}\mathbb E\!\left[f''(B_{t_i})f''(B_{t_j})\eta_i\eta_j\right].
\]

We claim that all cross terms vanish. Indeed, if \(i<j\), then
\[
f''(B_{t_i})f''(B_{t_j})\eta_i
\]
is \(\mathcal F_{t_j}\)-measurable, while \(\Delta_j B\) is independent of \(\mathcal F_{t_j}\). Therefore
\[
\mathbb E[\eta_j\mid \mathcal F_{t_j}]
=
\mathbb E[(\Delta_j B)^2-\Delta t\mid \mathcal F_{t_j}]
=
0,
\]
and so
\[
\mathbb E\!\left[f''(B_{t_i})f''(B_{t_j})\eta_i\eta_j\right]
=
\mathbb E\!\left[
f''(B_{t_i})f''(B_{t_j})\eta_i\,
\mathbb E(\eta_j\mid \mathcal F_{t_j})
\right]
=
0.
\]
Thus
\[
\mathbb E[M_N^2]
=
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}\mathbb E\!\left[f''(B_{t_i})^2\eta_i^2\right].
\]

Since \(f''\) is bounded,
\[
\mathbb E[M_N^2]
\le
\|f''\|_\infty^2
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}\mathbb E[\eta_i^2].
\]
Now \(\Delta_i B\sim N(0,\Delta t)\). Writing \(\Delta_i B=\sqrt{\Delta t}\,Z\) with \(Z\sim N(0,1)\), we get
\[
\mathbb E[\eta_i^2]
=
\mathbb E\!\left[\big((\Delta_i B)^2-\Delta t\big)^2\right]
=
(\Delta t)^2\mathbb E[(Z^2-1)^2]
=
2(\Delta t)^2.
\]
Hence
\[
\mathbb E[M_N^2]
\le
2\|f''\|_\infty^2\,N(\Delta t)^2
=
2\|f''\|_\infty^2\,T\,\Delta t
\longrightarrow 0.
\]
So \(M_N\to 0\) in \(L^2\), and therefore in probability.

Combining this with \(A_N\to 0\) almost surely, we conclude that
\[
S_N \xrightarrow{\mathbb P} \int_0^T f''(B_t)\,dt.
\]
Multiplying by \(1/2\) gives
\[
\frac12\sum_{i=0}^{N-1} f''(B_{t_i})(\Delta_i B)^2
\;\xrightarrow{\mathbb P}\;
\frac12\int_0^T f''(B_t)\,dt.
\]
\end{proof}

\begin{remark}
The boundedness of \(f''\) is used only in the \(L^2\) estimate above. In a full proof of It\^o's formula, one usually first proves the result under this boundedness assumption and then extends it to general \(f\in C^2\) by a localization argument.
\end{remark}

This explains why the stochastic chain rule differs from the ordinary one.

\begin{keyformula}
For Brownian motion,
\[
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}(B_{t_{i+1}}-B_{t_i})^2 \to T.
\]
This is why the second derivative term survives in It\^o's formula.
\end{keyformula}

\subsection{Extending from \(B_t\) to general It\^o processes}

The lecture then moves to the more general situation
\[
dZ_t=X_t\,dt+Y_t\,dB_t,
\]
that is,
\[
Z_t=Z_0+\int_0^t X_s\,ds+\int_0^t Y_s\,dB_s.
\]

Here \(X_t\) and \(Y_t\) are adapted processes, typically continuous. This is the general form of a one-dimensional It\^o process in these notes.

The goal is to compute \(df(Z_t)\), and more generally \(df(t,Z_t)\).

\subsection{General It\^o formula: time-homogeneous version}

\begin{definition}[Quadratic variation]
Let \(Z=(Z_t)_{0\le t\le T}\) be a continuous process. Its quadratic variation on \([0,t]\) is defined by
\[
\langle Z\rangle_t
:=
\lim_{\|\Pi\|\to 0}\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}\bigl(Z_{t_{i+1}}-Z_{t_i}\bigr)^2,
\]
provided the limit exists in probability, where
\[
\Pi=\{0=t_0<t_1<\cdots<t_n=t\}
\]
is a partition of \([0,t]\), and \(\|\Pi\|=\max_i (t_{i+1}-t_i)\).
\end{definition}

\begin{proposition}[Quadratic variation of an It\^o process]
Let
\[
Z_t=Z_0+\int_0^t X_s\,ds+\int_0^t Y_s\,dB_s,
\]
where \(X\) and \(Y\) are adapted continuous processes on \([0,T]\), and assume \(Y\) is bounded. Then for every \(t\in[0,T]\),
\[
\langle Z\rangle_t=\int_0^t Y_s^2\,ds.
\]
Equivalently, in differential notation,
\[
d\langle Z\rangle_t=Y_t^2\,dt.
\]
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
Write
\[
A_t:=\int_0^t X_s\,ds,
\qquad
M_t:=\int_0^t Y_s\,dB_s,
\]
so that \(Z_t=Z_0+A_t+M_t\).

Fix \(t\in[0,T]\), and consider the uniform partition
\[
t_i=\frac{it}{N},\qquad i=0,1,\dots,N.
\]
Set
\[
\Delta_i A:=A_{t_{i+1}}-A_{t_i},
\qquad
\Delta_i M:=M_{t_{i+1}}-M_{t_i},
\qquad
\Delta_i Z:=Z_{t_{i+1}}-Z_{t_i}.
\]
Then
\[
\Delta_i Z=\Delta_i A+\Delta_i M,
\]
hence
\[
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}(\Delta_i Z)^2
=
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}(\Delta_i A)^2
+
2\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}\Delta_i A\,\Delta_i M
+
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}(\Delta_i M)^2.
\]
We analyze these three terms separately.

\medskip
\noindent
\textbf{Step 1: The drift part has zero quadratic variation.}

Since \(A_t=\int_0^t X_s\,ds\) is continuously differentiable, it has finite variation on \([0,t]\). Therefore
\[
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}(\Delta_i A)^2
\le
\Big(\max_{0\le i\le N-1}|\Delta_i A|\Big)\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}|\Delta_i A|.
\]
Because \(A\) is continuous, \(\max_i |\Delta_i A|\to 0\) as \(N\to\infty\), and since \(A\) has finite variation,
\[
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}|\Delta_i A|
\le
\int_0^t |X_s|\,ds <\infty.
\]
Hence
\[
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}(\Delta_i A)^2 \to 0.
\]

\medskip
\noindent
\textbf{Step 2: The cross term vanishes.}

By Cauchy--Schwarz,
\[
\left|\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}\Delta_i A\,\Delta_i M\right|^2
\le
\left(\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}(\Delta_i A)^2\right)
\left(\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}(\Delta_i M)^2\right).
\]
From Step 1, the first factor tends to \(0\). The second factor will be shown below to converge in probability to \(\int_0^t Y_s^2\,ds\), hence it is bounded in probability. It follows that
\[
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}\Delta_i A\,\Delta_i M \xrightarrow{\mathbb P} 0.
\]

\medskip
\noindent
\textbf{Step 3: Quadratic variation of the martingale part.}

For each \(i\),
\[
\Delta_i M
=
\int_{t_i}^{t_{i+1}} Y_s\,dB_s
=
Y_{t_i}(B_{t_{i+1}}-B_{t_i})+R_i,
\]
where
\[
R_i:=\int_{t_i}^{t_{i+1}}(Y_s-Y_{t_i})\,dB_s.
\]
Therefore
\[
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}(\Delta_i M)^2
=
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}Y_{t_i}^2(B_{t_{i+1}}-B_{t_i})^2
+
2\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}Y_{t_i}(B_{t_{i+1}}-B_{t_i})R_i
+
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}R_i^2.
\]

We first handle the remainder term. By It\^o isometry,
\[
\mathbb E[R_i^2]
=
\mathbb E\int_{t_i}^{t_{i+1}}(Y_s-Y_{t_i})^2\,ds.
\]
Hence
\[
\mathbb E\left[\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}R_i^2\right]
=
\mathbb E\int_0^t (Y_s-Y_{\lfloor s\rfloor_N})^2\,ds,
\]
where \(\lfloor s\rfloor_N\) denotes the left endpoint of the partition interval containing \(s\).
Since \(Y\) is continuous and bounded, the integrand converges pointwise to \(0\) and is dominated by a constant. By dominated convergence,
\[
\mathbb E\left[\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}R_i^2\right]\to 0.
\]
Therefore
\[
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}R_i^2 \xrightarrow{L^1} 0,
\qquad\text{hence}\qquad
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}R_i^2 \xrightarrow{\mathbb P} 0.
\]

Next, for the mixed term, by Cauchy--Schwarz,
\[
\left|\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}Y_{t_i}(B_{t_{i+1}}-B_{t_i})R_i\right|
\le
\left(\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}Y_{t_i}^2(B_{t_{i+1}}-B_{t_i})^2\right)^{1/2}
\left(\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}R_i^2\right)^{1/2}.
\]
The second factor converges to \(0\) in probability, while the first one is bounded in probability, so
\[
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}Y_{t_i}(B_{t_{i+1}}-B_{t_i})R_i
\xrightarrow{\mathbb P} 0.
\]

Finally, by the weighted quadratic variation result,
\[
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}Y_{t_i}^2(B_{t_{i+1}}-B_{t_i})^2
\xrightarrow{\mathbb P}
\int_0^t Y_s^2\,ds.
\]
Combining the last three displays, we obtain
\[
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}(\Delta_i M)^2
\xrightarrow{\mathbb P}
\int_0^t Y_s^2\,ds.
\]

\medskip
\noindent
Putting Steps 1--3 together,
\[
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}(\Delta_i Z)^2
\xrightarrow{\mathbb P}
\int_0^t Y_s^2\,ds.
\]
By definition of quadratic variation,
\[
\langle Z\rangle_t=\int_0^t Y_s^2\,ds.
\]
Therefore, in differential notation,
\[
d\langle Z\rangle_t=Y_t^2\,dt.
\]
\end{proof}

\begin{theorem}[It\^o's formula for \(f(Z_t)\)]
Let
\[
dZ_t=X_t\,dt+Y_t\,dB_t,
\]
and suppose \(f\in C^2(\mathbb R)\). Then
\[
df(Z_t)
=
f'(Z_t)\,dZ_t+\frac12 f''(Z_t)\,d\langle Z\rangle_t.
\]
Equivalently, since \(dZ_t=X_t\,dt+Y_t\,dB_t\),
\[
df(Z_t)
=
\left(f'(Z_t)X_t+\frac12 f''(Z_t)Y_t^2\right)dt
+
f'(Z_t)Y_t\,dB_t.
\]
\end{theorem}

So the second-order correction is controlled by the quadratic variation process \(\langle Z\rangle_t\).

\subsection{Proof idea for the general formula}

Again take an equispaced partition
\[
t_i=\frac{iT}{N},\qquad i=0,1,\dots,N.
\]
Write
\[
f(Z_T)-f(Z_0)
=
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}\bigl(f(Z_{t_{i+1}})-f(Z_{t_i})\bigr).
\]
Taylor expansion gives
\[
f(Z_{t_{i+1}})-f(Z_{t_i})
=
f'(Z_{t_i})(Z_{t_{i+1}}-Z_{t_i})
+
\frac12 f''(Z_{t_i})(Z_{t_{i+1}}-Z_{t_i})^2
+
o\!\left(|Z_{t_{i+1}}-Z_{t_i}|^2\right).
\]

So there are two main terms:

\[
\text{Term 1}=
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1} f'(Z_{t_i})(Z_{t_{i+1}}-Z_{t_i}),
\]
and
\[
\text{Term 2}=
\frac12\sum_{i=0}^{N-1} f''(Z_{t_i})(Z_{t_{i+1}}-Z_{t_i})^2.
\]

For Term 1, use
\[
Z_{t_{i+1}}-Z_{t_i}
=
\int_{t_i}^{t_{i+1}} X_t\,dt
+
\int_{t_i}^{t_{i+1}} Y_t\,dB_t.
\]
Then
\[
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1} f'(Z_{t_i})\int_{t_i}^{t_{i+1}} X_t\,dt
\to
\int_0^T f'(Z_t)X_t\,dt,
\]
just like an ordinary Riemann sum.

For the stochastic part, define the piecewise-constant approximation
\[
g_t^{(N)}=f'(Z_{t_i})
\qquad \text{for } t\in[t_i,t_{i+1}).
\]
Then
\[
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1} f'(Z_{t_i})\int_{t_i}^{t_{i+1}} Y_t\,dB_t
=
\int_0^T g_t^{(N)}Y_t\,dB_t,
\]
and as \(N\to\infty\),
\[
\int_0^T g_t^{(N)}Y_t\,dB_t
\to
\int_0^T f'(Z_t)Y_t\,dB_t
\]
by the same \(L^2\)-approximation argument used in the definition of the It\^o integral.

Thus Term 1 converges to
\[
\int_0^T f'(Z_t)X_t\,dt
+
\int_0^T f'(Z_t)Y_t\,dB_t.
\]

For Term 2, one needs the quadratic variation of \(Z\), which the lecture defines next.

\subsection{Quadratic variation}

\begin{definition}[Quadratic variation]
Given a process \((Z_t)_{t\ge 0}\), define its quadratic variation process by
\[
\langle Z\rangle_t
=
\lim_{N\to\infty}
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}(Z_{t_{i+1}}-Z_{t_i})^2,
\qquad
t_i=\frac{it}{N},
\]
whenever the limit exists.
\end{definition}

This should be compared with total variation
\[
\lim_{N\to\infty}\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}|Z_{t_{i+1}}-Z_{t_i}|,
\]
which is a different object.

The notes emphasize:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item \(\langle Z\rangle_t\ge \langle Z\rangle_s\ge 0\) whenever \(0\le s<t\), so quadratic variation is nondecreasing;
    \item if \(Z_t\) has continuous sample paths, then \(\langle Z\rangle_t\) is also continuous.
\end{itemize}

Once quadratic variation is available, Term 2 becomes
\[
\frac12\int_0^T f''(Z_t)\,d\langle Z\rangle_t.
\]

\subsection{Quadratic variation of an It\^o process}

\begin{proposition}
If
\[
dZ_t=X_t\,dt+Y_t\,dB_t,
\]
then
\[
d\langle Z\rangle_t=Y_t^2\,dt,
\qquad\text{i.e.}\qquad
\langle Z\rangle_t=\int_0^t Y_s^2\,ds.
\]
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}[Idea from the notes]
Over a small interval \([t_i,t_{i+1}]\),
\[
Z_{t_{i+1}}-Z_{t_i}
=
\int_{t_i}^{t_{i+1}} X_t\,dt
+
\int_{t_i}^{t_{i+1}} Y_t\,dB_t.
\]
The first term is of order \(\Delta t\), while the second is of order \(\sqrt{\Delta t}\). Therefore
\[
(Z_{t_{i+1}}-Z_{t_i})^2
=
\left(\int_{t_i}^{t_{i+1}} Y_t\,dB_t\right)^2
+
O((\Delta t)^2)
+
O((\Delta t)^{3/2}).
\]
Summing over \(i\), the error terms vanish as \(N\to\infty\). Thus
\[
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}(Z_{t_{i+1}}-Z_{t_i})^2
\sim
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}
\left(\int_{t_i}^{t_{i+1}}Y_t\,dB_t\right)^2.
\]

Conditioning on \(\mathcal F_{t_i}\) and using the It\^o isometry,
\[
\mathbb E\!\left[
\left(\int_{t_i}^{t_{i+1}}Y_t\,dB_t\right)^2
\Bigm|\mathcal F_{t_i}
\right]
=
\int_{t_i}^{t_{i+1}}\mathbb E[Y_t^2\mid \mathcal F_{t_i}]\,dt.
\]
A martingale-difference argument then shows that
\[
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}
\left(\int_{t_i}^{t_{i+1}}Y_t\,dB_t\right)^2
\to
\int_0^T Y_t^2\,dt.
\]
Hence
\[
\langle Z\rangle_T=\int_0^T Y_t^2\,dt.
\]
\end{proof}

\begin{keyformula}
If
\[
dZ_t=X_t\,dt+Y_t\,dB_t,
\]
then
\[
d\langle Z\rangle_t=Y_t^2\,dt.
\]
So the quadratic variation comes entirely from the Brownian part.
\end{keyformula}

\subsection{Conclusion: general It\^o formula}

Putting the previous pieces together gives
\[
df(Z_t)
=
f'(Z_t)\,dZ_t+\frac12 f''(Z_t)\,d\langle Z\rangle_t.
\]
Since
\[
dZ_t=X_t\,dt+Y_t\,dB_t
\qquad\text{and}\qquad
d\langle Z\rangle_t=Y_t^2\,dt,
\]
we obtain
\[
df(Z_t)
=
\left(f'(Z_t)X_t+\frac12 f''(Z_t)Y_t^2\right)dt
+
f'(Z_t)Y_t\,dB_t.
\]

This is the one-dimensional It\^o formula for a general It\^o process.

\subsection{Time-inhomogeneous It\^o formula}

The notes then extend the formula to functions \(f(t,z)\) depending explicitly on time.

\begin{theorem}[Time-inhomogeneous It\^o formula]
Let
\[
dZ_t=X_t\,dt+Y_t\,dB_t,
\]
and suppose \(f\in C^{1,2}\), meaning once continuously differentiable in \(t\) and twice continuously differentiable in \(z\). Then
\[
df(t,Z_t)
=
\frac{\partial f}{\partial t}(t,Z_t)\,dt
+
\frac{\partial f}{\partial z}(t,Z_t)\,dZ_t
+
\frac12\frac{\partial^2 f}{\partial z^2}(t,Z_t)\,d\langle Z\rangle_t.
\]
Equivalently,
\[
df(t,Z_t)
=
\left(
\frac{\partial f}{\partial t}(t,Z_t)
+
X_t\frac{\partial f}{\partial z}(t,Z_t)
+
\frac12 Y_t^2\frac{\partial^2 f}{\partial z^2}(t,Z_t)
\right)dt
+
Y_t\frac{\partial f}{\partial z}(t,Z_t)\,dB_t.
\]
\end{theorem}

\subsection{Proof idea for the time-inhomogeneous version}

Write
\[
f(T,Z_T)-f(0,Z_0)
=
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}\bigl(f(t_{i+1},Z_{t_{i+1}})-f(t_i,Z_{t_i})\bigr).
\]
Then split each increment into two parts:
\[
f(t_{i+1},Z_{t_{i+1}})-f(t_i,Z_{t_i})
=
\bigl(f(t_{i+1},Z_{t_{i+1}})-f(t_i,Z_{t_{i+1}})\bigr)
+
\bigl(f(t_i,Z_{t_{i+1}})-f(t_i,Z_{t_i})\bigr).
\]

The first part is the pure time change, giving
\[
\frac{\partial f}{\partial t}(t_i,Z_{t_{i+1}})\Delta t
\]
in the limit.

The second part is treated exactly as before using Taylor expansion in the space variable:
\[
\frac{\partial f}{\partial z}(t_i,Z_{t_i})(Z_{t_{i+1}}-Z_{t_i})
+
\frac12
\frac{\partial^2 f}{\partial z^2}(t_i,Z_{t_i})(Z_{t_{i+1}}-Z_{t_i})^2.
\]

Combining the limits yields the formula.

\subsection{Example: the exponential martingale}

Take
\[
f(t,z)=\exp(at+bz),
\]
and choose \(Z_t=B_t\). Then
\[
\frac{\partial f}{\partial t}(t,z)=a e^{at+bz},
\qquad
\frac{\partial f}{\partial z}(t,z)=b e^{at+bz},
\qquad
\frac{\partial^2 f}{\partial z^2}(t,z)=b^2 e^{at+bz}.
\]

Since for \(Z_t=B_t\) we have
\[
dZ_t=dB_t
\qquad\text{and}\qquad
d\langle Z\rangle_t=dt,
\]
It\^o's formula gives
\[
d\,f(t,B_t)
=
a e^{at+bB_t}\,dt
+
b e^{at+bB_t}\,dB_t
+
\frac12 b^2 e^{at+bB_t}\,dt.
\]
Therefore
\[
d\,f(t,B_t)
=
\left(a+\frac{b^2}{2}\right)f(t,B_t)\,dt
+
b\,f(t,B_t)\,dB_t.
\]

Now choose
\[
a+\frac{b^2}{2}=0,
\qquad\text{i.e.}\qquad
a=-\frac{b^2}{2}.
\]
Then the drift term disappears, and we obtain
\[
d\left(e^{\,bB_t-\frac12 b^2 t}\right)
=
b\,e^{\,bB_t-\frac12 b^2 t}\,dB_t.
\]
Hence
\[
\left(e^{\,bB_t-\frac12 b^2 t}\right)_{t\ge 0}
\]
is a martingale.

\begin{keyformula}
For every \(b\in\mathbb R\),
\[
\left(e^{\,bB_t-\frac12 b^2 t}\right)_{t\ge 0}
\]
is a martingale.
\end{keyformula}

This is the \emph{exponential martingale}, one of the most important examples in stochastic calculus.

\subsection{Product rule in stochastic calculus}

In ordinary calculus,
\[
d(fg)=f\,dg+g\,df.
\]
In stochastic calculus there is an extra correction term.

Suppose
\[
dZ_t^{(i)}=X_t^{(i)}\,dt+Y_t^{(i)}\,dB_t,
\qquad i=1,2.
\]

First, from It\^o's formula applied to \(f(z)=z^2\), we get
\[
d\bigl((Z_t)^2\bigr)=2Z_t\,dZ_t+d\langle Z\rangle_t.
\]
Indeed,
\[
d\bigl((Z_t)^2\bigr)
=
2Z_t(X_t\,dt+Y_t\,dB_t)+Y_t^2\,dt.
\]

To derive the product rule for two different processes, use the polarization identity
\[
Z_t^{(1)}Z_t^{(2)}
=
\left(\frac{Z_t^{(1)}+Z_t^{(2)}}{2}\right)^2
-
\left(\frac{Z_t^{(1)}-Z_t^{(2)}}{2}\right)^2.
\]
Applying the square rule to both terms yields
\[
d\bigl(Z_t^{(1)}Z_t^{(2)}\bigr)
=
Z_t^{(1)}\,dZ_t^{(2)}
+
Z_t^{(2)}\,dZ_t^{(1)}
+
d\langle Z^{(1)},Z^{(2)}\rangle_t,
\]
where \(\langle Z^{(1)},Z^{(2)}\rangle_t\) is the \emph{cross variation}.

\subsection{Cross variation}

\begin{definition}[Cross variation]
Given two processes \(Z^{(1)}\) and \(Z^{(2)}\), define
\[
\langle Z^{(1)},Z^{(2)}\rangle_t
=
\lim_{N\to\infty}
\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}
\bigl(Z_{t_{i+1}}^{(1)}-Z_{t_i}^{(1)}\bigr)
\bigl(Z_{t_{i+1}}^{(2)}-Z_{t_i}^{(2)}\bigr),
\]
when the limit exists.
\end{definition}

For It\^o processes driven by the same Brownian motion,
\[
dZ_t^{(i)}=X_t^{(i)}\,dt+Y_t^{(i)}\,dB_t,
\]
the cross variation satisfies
\[
d\langle Z^{(1)},Z^{(2)}\rangle_t
=
Y_t^{(1)}Y_t^{(2)}\,dt.
\]

So the stochastic product rule becomes
\[
d\bigl(Z_t^{(1)}Z_t^{(2)}\bigr)
=
Z_t^{(1)}\,dZ_t^{(2)}
+
Z_t^{(2)}\,dZ_t^{(1)}
+
Y_t^{(1)}Y_t^{(2)}\,dt.
\]

\begin{keyformula}
If
\[
dZ_t^{(i)}=X_t^{(i)}\,dt+Y_t^{(i)}\,dB_t,\qquad i=1,2,
\]
then
\[
d\bigl(Z_t^{(1)}Z_t^{(2)}\bigr)
=
Z_t^{(1)}\,dZ_t^{(2)}
+
Z_t^{(2)}\,dZ_t^{(1)}
+
d\langle Z^{(1)},Z^{(2)}\rangle_t,
\]
with
\[
d\langle Z^{(1)},Z^{(2)}\rangle_t=Y_t^{(1)}Y_t^{(2)}\,dt.
\]
\end{keyformula}

\subsection{How Lecture 9 fits into the stochastic-calculus picture}

The main message of Lecture 9 is that the correct differential calculus for Brownian-driven processes is governed by quadratic variation:

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item ordinary calculus ignores \((\Delta x)^2\) terms;
    \item for Brownian motion, \((\Delta B)^2\) is of order \(\Delta t\), so these terms survive;
    \item the surviving second-order terms are encoded by \(d\langle Z\rangle_t\);
    \item this produces It\^o's formula, the stochastic chain rule.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Summary}

\begin{summarybox}
Lecture 9 develops the stochastic chain rule.

Main ideas:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item The naive identity
    \[
    \int_0^T f'(B_t)\,dB_t=f(B_T)-f(B_0)
    \]
    is false for the It\^o integral.
    \item For \(f(x)=\frac12 x^2\),
    \[
    \int_0^T B_t\,dB_t=\frac12 B_T^2-\frac12 T.
    \]
    \item The correct formula for \(f(B_t)\) is
    \[
    df(B_t)=f'(B_t)\,dB_t+\frac12 f''(B_t)\,dt.
    \]
    \item The extra term comes from Brownian quadratic variation:
    \[
    \sum (B_{t_{i+1}}-B_{t_i})^2\to T.
    \]
    \item For a general It\^o process
    \[
    dZ_t=X_t\,dt+Y_t\,dB_t,
    \]
    one has
    \[
    d\langle Z\rangle_t=Y_t^2\,dt,
    \]
    and
    \[
    df(Z_t)=f'(Z_t)\,dZ_t+\frac12 f''(Z_t)\,d\langle Z\rangle_t.
    \]
    \item The time-dependent version is
    \[
    df(t,Z_t)
    =
    \frac{\partial f}{\partial t}(t,Z_t)\,dt
    +
    \frac{\partial f}{\partial z}(t,Z_t)\,dZ_t
    +
    \frac12\frac{\partial^2 f}{\partial z^2}(t,Z_t)\,d\langle Z\rangle_t.
    \]
    \item A key example is the exponential martingale
    \[
    \left(e^{\,bB_t-\frac12 b^2 t}\right)_{t\ge 0}.
    \]
    \item The stochastic product rule includes a cross-variation correction:
    \[
    d(Z^{(1)}_tZ^{(2)}_t)
    =
    Z_t^{(1)}\,dZ_t^{(2)}
    +
    Z_t^{(2)}\,dZ_t^{(1)}
    +
    d\langle Z^{(1)},Z^{(2)}\rangle_t.
    \]
\end{itemize}
\end{summarybox}

