\subsection{Recall: one-dimensional It\^o formula}

From Lecture 9, if
\[
dZ_t=X_t\,dt+Y_t\,dB_t,
\]
and if $f\in C^{1,2}$, then
\[
df(t,Z_t)
=
\frac{\partial f}{\partial t}(t,Z_t)\,dt
+
\frac{\partial f}{\partial z}(t,Z_t)\,dZ_t
+
\frac12
\frac{\partial^2 f}{\partial z^2}(t,Z_t)\,Y_t^2\,dt.
\]
Equivalently,
\[
df(t,Z_t)
=
\left(
\frac{\partial f}{\partial t}(t,Z_t)
+
X_t\frac{\partial f}{\partial z}(t,Z_t)
+
\frac12 Y_t^2\frac{\partial^2 f}{\partial z^2}(t,Z_t)
\right)dt
+
Y_t\frac{\partial f}{\partial z}(t,Z_t)\,dB_t.
\]

A useful corollary is the stochastic product rule. If
\[
dZ_t^{(i)}=X_t^{(i)}\,dt+Y_t^{(i)}\,dB_t,
\qquad i=1,2,
\]
then
\[
d\bigl(Z_t^{(1)}Z_t^{(2)}\bigr)
=
Z_t^{(1)}\,dZ_t^{(2)}+Z_t^{(2)}\,dZ_t^{(1)}+d\langle Z^{(1)},Z^{(2)}\rangle_t,
\]
with
\[
d\langle Z^{(1)},Z^{(2)}\rangle_t=Y_t^{(1)}Y_t^{(2)}\,dt.
\]
So in differential notation,
\[
d\bigl(Z_t^{(1)}Z_t^{(2)}\bigr)
=
Z_t^{(1)}\,dZ_t^{(2)}+Z_t^{(2)}\,dZ_t^{(1)}+Y_t^{(1)}Y_t^{(2)}\,dt.
\]

\begin{keyformula}
For It\^o processes driven by the same Brownian motion,
\[
d\bigl(Z_t^{(1)}Z_t^{(2)}\bigr)
=
Z_t^{(1)}\,dZ_t^{(2)}+Z_t^{(2)}\,dZ_t^{(1)}+Y_t^{(1)}Y_t^{(2)}\,dt.
\]
This is the stochastic correction to the ordinary product rule.
\end{keyformula}

\subsection{Example 1: the Ornstein--Uhlenbeck process}

Consider the stochastic differential equation
\[
dZ_t=-Z_t\,dt+dB_t.
\]
Here the process is defined implicitly by an SDE, and the goal is to solve it explicitly.

The key idea is to use an integrating factor, exactly as in ordinary differential equations. Consider
\[
e^t Z_t.
\]
Using the stochastic product rule,
\[
d(e^t Z_t)=e^t\,dZ_t+e^t Z_t\,dt+0,
\]
since $e^t$ has finite variation and therefore has no quadratic covariation term with $Z_t$.
Substituting $dZ_t=-Z_t\,dt+dB_t$ gives
\[
d(e^t Z_t)=e^t(-Z_t\,dt+dB_t)+e^t Z_t\,dt=e^t\,dB_t.
\]
Integrating from $0$ to $t$,
\[
e^t Z_t-Z_0=\int_0^t e^s\,dB_s.
\]
Hence
\[
Z_t=e^{-t}\left(Z_0+\int_0^t e^s\,dB_s\right).
\]

Since the It\^o integral of a deterministic function against Brownian motion is Gaussian,
\[
\int_0^t e^s\,dB_s
\sim
\mathcal N\!\left(0,\int_0^t e^{2s}\,ds\right),
\]
it follows that, marginally,
\[
Z_t\sim
\mathcal N\!\left(e^{-t}Z_0,\ e^{-2t}\int_0^t e^{2s}\,ds\right).
\]
The variance can be simplified:
\[
e^{-2t}\int_0^t e^{2s}\,ds
=
\frac{1-e^{-2t}}{2}.
\]
Therefore
\[
Z_t\sim \mathcal N\!\left(e^{-t}Z_0,\frac{1-e^{-2t}}{2}\right).
\]

So as $t\to\infty$,
\[
e^{-t}Z_0\to 0,
\qquad
\frac{1-e^{-2t}}{2}\to \frac12,
\]
and thus
\[
Z_t\Longrightarrow \mathcal N\!\left(0,\frac12\right).
\]
This is the stationary law of the process.

\begin{keyformula}
The Ornstein--Uhlenbeck process
\[
dZ_t=-Z_t\,dt+dB_t
\]
has explicit solution
\[
Z_t=e^{-t}\left(Z_0+\int_0^t e^s\,dB_s\right),
\]
and converges in distribution to
\[
\mathcal N\!\left(0,\frac12\right).
\]
It is a basic example of a continuous-time Markov process with mean reversion.
\end{keyformula}

\subsection{Example 2: geometric Brownian motion}

Now consider
\[
dZ_t=rZ_t\,dt+bZ_t\,dB_t,
\qquad Z_0=1.
\]
A natural guess is that the solution should have exponential form. Suppose
\[
Z_t=\exp(at+kB_t).
\]
Applying It\^o's formula to $f(t,x)=e^{at+kx}$ with $x=B_t$ gives
\[
dZ_t=aZ_t\,dt+kZ_t\,dB_t+\frac12 k^2 Z_t\,dt.
\]
So
\[
dZ_t=\left(a+\frac12 k^2\right)Z_t\,dt+kZ_t\,dB_t.
\]
To match the target SDE, we need
\[
k=b,
\qquad
a+\frac12 b^2=r.
\]
Therefore
\[
a=r-\frac{b^2}{2}.
\]
So the solution is
\[
Z_t=\exp\!\left(\left(r-\frac{b^2}{2}\right)t+bB_t\right).
\]

This process is called \emph{geometric Brownian motion}. It is one of the most important models in stochastic calculus and mathematical finance.

A useful special case is $r=0$. Then
\[
Z_t=\exp\!\left(-\frac{b^2}{2}t+bB_t\right),
\]
which is exactly the exponential martingale from Lecture 9. In particular, when $r=0$, $(Z_t)_{t\ge 0}$ is a martingale.

\begin{keyformula}
The SDE
\[
dZ_t=rZ_t\,dt+bZ_t\,dB_t
\]
has solution
\[
Z_t=\exp\!\left(\left(r-\frac{b^2}{2}\right)t+bB_t\right).
\]
When $r=0$, geometric Brownian motion is a martingale.
\end{keyformula}

\subsection{Multivariate Brownian motion}

The lecture next turns to the multidimensional setting.
Let
\[
B_t=(B_t^{(1)},B_t^{(2)},\dots,B_t^{(d)})\in\mathbb R^d,
\]
where the coordinates $B_t^{(1)},\dots,B_t^{(d)}$ are independent one-dimensional Brownian motions.

If $f=f(t,x)$ with $x\in\mathbb R^d$, then the multidimensional It\^o formula for $f(t,B_t)$ is
\[
df(t,B_t)
=
\frac{\partial f}{\partial t}(t,B_t)\,dt
+
\nabla_x f(t,B_t)^T\,dB_t
+
\frac12\,\Delta_x f(t,B_t)\,dt,
\]
where
\[
\Delta_x f(t,x)=\sum_{j=1}^d \frac{\partial^2 f}{\partial x_j^2}(t,x)
\]
is the Laplacian.

Here
\[
\nabla_x f(t,B_t)^T\,dB_t
=
\sum_{j=1}^d \frac{\partial f}{\partial x_j}(t,B_t)\,dB_t^{(j)}.
\]

\subsection{General multidimensional It\^o formula}

More generally, let $Z_t\in\mathbb R^d$ satisfy
\[
dZ_t=X_t\,dt+Y_t\,dB_t,
\]
where
\[
X_t\in\mathbb R^d,
\qquad
Y_t\in\mathbb R^{d\times d},
\]
and $B_t\in\mathbb R^d$ is standard Brownian motion.
If $f\in C^{1,2}$, then
\[
df(t,Z_t)
=
\frac{\partial f}{\partial t}(t,Z_t)\,dt
+
\nabla f(t,Z_t)^T\,dZ_t
+
\frac12\,\mathrm{Tr}\!\left(Y_t^T\nabla_x^2 f(t,Z_t)Y_t\right)dt.
\]

Equivalently, substituting $dZ_t=X_t\,dt+Y_t\,dB_t$,
\[
df(t,Z_t)
=
\left(
\frac{\partial f}{\partial t}(t,Z_t)
+
\nabla f(t,Z_t)^T X_t
+
\frac12\,\mathrm{Tr}\!\left(Y_t^T\nabla_x^2 f(t,Z_t)Y_t\right)
\right)dt
+
\nabla f(t,Z_t)^T Y_t\,dB_t.
\]

So the one-dimensional second-derivative term $\frac12 f''Y_t^2$ becomes a Hessian term with a trace.

\begin{keyformula}
For $Z_t\in\mathbb R^d$ solving
\[
dZ_t=X_t\,dt+Y_t\,dB_t,
\]
the multidimensional It\^o formula is
\[
df(t,Z_t)
=
\frac{\partial f}{\partial t}(t,Z_t)\,dt
+
\nabla f(t,Z_t)^T\,dZ_t
+
\frac12\,\mathrm{Tr}\!\left(Y_t^T\nabla_x^2 f(t,Z_t)Y_t\right)dt.
\]
\end{keyformula}

\subsection{Continuous-time, discrete-space processes}

After stochastic calculus in continuous state space, the lecture moves to another major class of continuous-time processes: processes with discrete state space.

The first example is the Poisson process.

\subsection{Review: Poisson random variables}

A random variable $N$ has Poisson distribution with parameter $\lambda>0$ if
\[
\mathbb P(N=n)=e^{-\lambda}\frac{\lambda^n}{n!},
\qquad n=0,1,2,\dots.
\]
We write
\[
N\sim \mathrm{Poi}(\lambda).
\]

\subsection{The Poisson process}

A Poisson process may be described in terms of waiting times between successive events.
Let
\[
T_1,T_2,\dots
\]
be i.i.d. exponential random variables with rate $\lambda$:
\[
T_i\sim \mathrm{Exp}(\lambda),
\qquad
p_{T_i}(t)=
\begin{cases}
\lambda e^{-\lambda t}, & t\ge 0,\\
0, & t<0.
\end{cases}
\]
Then define
\[
N(t)=\#\{\text{events that have occurred by time }t\}.
\]
So $N(t)$ counts the number of marked points in $[0,t]$.

The exponential law appears naturally because it is the only continuous distribution with the memoryless property:
\[
\mathbb P(T_i>t+s\mid T_i>t)=\mathbb P(T_i>s).
\]
This matches the Markov property of the Poisson process.

\subsection{Basic facts about the Poisson process}

If $(N(t))_{t\ge 0}\sim \mathrm{PP}(\lambda)$, then:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item for each fixed $t\ge 0$,
    \[
    N(t)\sim \mathrm{Poi}(\lambda t);
    \]
    \item $(N(t))_{t\ge 0}$ is a Markov process;
    \item it has independent increments;
    \item more precisely, for $s,t\ge 0$,
    \[
    N(t+s)-N(t)\sim \mathrm{Poi}(\lambda s),
    \]
    and this increment is independent of the past up to time $t$.
\end{itemize}

A very useful martingale is
\[
(N(t)-\lambda t)_{t\ge 0}.
\]
Indeed, using independent increments,
\[
\mathbb E[N(t)-\lambda t\mid \mathcal F_s]
=
N(s)+\mathbb E[N(t)-N(s)]-\lambda t
=
N(s)+\lambda(t-s)-\lambda t
=
N(s)-\lambda s.
\]
So $(N(t)-\lambda t)$ is a martingale.

\begin{keyformula}
For a Poisson process of rate $\lambda$,
\[
N(t)\sim \mathrm{Poi}(\lambda t),
\qquad
N(t+s)-N(t)\sim \mathrm{Poi}(\lambda s),
\]
and
\[
(N(t)-\lambda t)_{t\ge 0}
\]
is a martingale.
\end{keyformula}

\subsection{Axiomatic characterization of the Poisson process}

The lecture also gives a more local, infinitesimal definition. A Poisson process $(N(t))_{t\ge 0}$ is a process taking values in the nonnegative integers such that:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item $N(t)$ is nondecreasing in $t$;
    \item for small $h>0$,
    \[
    \mathbb P\bigl(N(t+h)-N(t)=1\bigr)=\lambda h+o(h);
    \]
    \item for small $h>0$,
    \[
    \mathbb P\bigl(N(t+h)-N(t)\ge 2\bigr)=o(h).
    \]
\end{itemize}

So over a very small time interval, with probability about $\lambda h$ exactly one jump occurs, and the probability of two or more jumps is negligible compared with $h$.

This point of view leads to general jump processes with state-dependent intensity. For example, one may replace the constant rate $\lambda$ by a local intensity of the form
\[
\lambda(t,N_t),
\]
so that
\[
\mathbb P\bigl(N(t+h)-N(t)=1\mid \mathcal F_t\bigr)
=
\lambda(t,N_t)h+o(h),
\]
and
\[
\mathbb P\bigl(N(t+h)-N(t)\ge 2\mid \mathcal F_t\bigr)=o(h).
\]
This is the jump-process analogue of specifying an SDE in the diffusion setting.

\subsection{Poisson point processes}

The Poisson process extends naturally from time intervals to general subsets of space.
Let $S$ be a space equipped with an intensity function $\lambda(x)\ge 0$.
For a measurable set $A\subseteq S$, define
\[
N(A)=\#\{\text{marked points in }A\}.
\]
A Poisson point process satisfies:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item
    \[
    N(A)\sim \mathrm{Poi}\!\left(\int_A \lambda(x)\,dx\right);
    \]
    \item if $A$ and $B$ are disjoint, then $N(A)$ and $N(B)$ are independent.
\end{itemize}

A convenient construction is:
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item sample
    \[
    N\sim \mathrm{Poi}\!\left(\int_S \lambda(x)\,dx\right);
    \]
    \item conditional on $N$, sample $N$ i.i.d. points in $S$ with density
    \[
    p(x)=\frac{\lambda(x)}{\int_S \lambda(y)\,dy}.
    \]
\end{enumerate}

The ordinary Poisson process is the special case $S=[0,\infty)$ with constant intensity $\lambda(x)\equiv \lambda$.
On a finite interval $[0,T]$, the construction becomes especially simple:
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item sample
    \[
    N(T)\sim \mathrm{Poi}(\lambda T);
    \]
    \item conditional on $N(T)=n$, sample $n$ i.i.d. event locations uniformly on $[0,T]$;
    \item then define $N(t)$ as the number of sampled points falling in $[0,t]$.
\end{enumerate}

\paragraph{Explanation of the construction.}
In this construction, the interval \( [0,T] \) and the rate \( \lambda \) are fixed in advance; they are not random. The randomness begins only when we generate the process itself.

First, we sample
\[
N(T)\sim \mathrm{Poi}(\lambda T).
\]
This means that we first determine the \emph{total number of points} in the whole interval \( [0,T] \). Thus \(N(T)\) is a random variable taking values in \(\{0,1,2,\dots\}\), with mean
\[
\mathbb E[N(T)] = \lambda T.
\]
So this first step decides \emph{how many} events occur in total on \( [0,T] \).

Next, conditional on \(N(T)=n\), we know that there are exactly \(n\) event times in the interval. We then need to determine \emph{where} these \(n\) points are located. Since the intensity is constant on \( [0,T] \), all locations are equally likely, so the \(n\) event times are sampled independently and uniformly on \( [0,T] \).

In the general Poisson point process construction on a space \(S\) with intensity function \(\lambda(x)\), the point locations have density
\[
p(x)=\frac{\lambda(x)}{\int_S \lambda(y)\,dy}.
\]
This density \(p(x)\) is the probability density of the location of \emph{one sampled point}, conditional on the total number of points. It is \emph{not} the distribution of the counting variable \(N(t)\).

In the present case \(S=[0,T]\) and \(\lambda(x)\equiv \lambda\) is constant, so
\[
p(x)=\frac{\lambda}{\int_0^T \lambda\,dy}
=\frac{\lambda}{\lambda T}
=\frac1T,
\qquad 0\le x\le T.
\]
Thus, conditional on \(N(T)=n\), the \(n\) event times are i.i.d. uniform random variables on \( [0,T] \).

Finally, for each \(t\in[0,T]\), we define \(N(t)\) to be the number of sampled points that fall in the subinterval \( [0,t] \). Since each sampled point falls in \( [0,t] \) with probability
\[
\mathbb P(X_i\in[0,t])=\frac{t}{T},
\]
it follows that
\[
N(t)\mid N(T)=n \sim \mathrm{Binomial}\!\left(n,\frac{t}{T}\right).
\]

So there are two different objects here:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \(p(x)\) describes the density of the \emph{location of a single point};
    \item \(N(t)\mid N(T)=n\) describes the \emph{number of sampled points} that fall in \( [0,t] \), and this has a binomial distribution.
\end{itemize}

Thus the construction has two stages:
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item sample the total number of events on \( [0,T] \);
    \item given that number, sample their locations independently in time.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Superposition and thinning}

This construction immediately gives two extremely useful properties.

\paragraph{Superposition.}
If $(N_1(t))_{t\ge 0}$ and $(N_2(t))_{t\ge 0}$ are independent Poisson processes with rates $\lambda_1$ and $\lambda_2$, then
\[
(N_1(t)+N_2(t))_{t\ge 0}
\]
is a Poisson process with rate $\lambda_1+\lambda_2$.

\paragraph{Thinning.}
Suppose $(N(t))_{t\ge 0}\sim \mathrm{PP}(\lambda)$, and independently label each event as type $i$ with probability $p_i$, where $\sum_i p_i=1$.
Let
\[
N_i(t)=\#\{\text{type }i\text{ events in }[0,t]\}.
\]
Then the processes $(N_i(t))_{t\ge 0}$ are independent Poisson processes with rates $\lambda p_i$.

\begin{keyformula}
If a Poisson process of rate $\lambda$ is thinned independently with type probabilities $(p_i)$, then the type-counting processes are independent Poisson processes with rates $(\lambda p_i)$.
\end{keyformula}

\subsection{Continuous-time Markov chains}

The lecture then introduces general continuous-time Markov chains (CTMCs).
Let $S$ be a finite or countable state space, and let $\nu$ be the initial distribution on $S$.
A process $(X_t)_{t\ge 0}$ is a continuous-time Markov chain if, for every
\[
0<t_1<t_2<\cdots<t_n,
\]
and states $i_0,i_1,\dots,i_n\in S$,
\[
\mathbb P(X_0=i_0,X_{t_1}=i_1,\dots,X_{t_n}=i_n)
=
\nu_{i_0}
\,p_{i_0i_1}^{(t_1)}
\,p_{i_1i_2}^{(t_2-t_1)}\cdots
p_{i_{n-1}i_n}^{(t_n-t_{n-1})},
\]
where
\[
p_{ij}^{(t)}=\mathbb P(X_t=j\mid X_0=i)
\]
is the transition matrix at time $t$.

So, just as in discrete time, the future depends on the present state and not on the full past; the only difference is that the parameter is now continuous time $t\ge 0$.

\subsection{Example: the Poisson process as a CTMC}

The Poisson process is a CTMC on the state space $\mathbb N_0$.
Starting from state $i$, after time $t$ the process can only be in states $j\ge i$, and
\[
p_{ij}^{(t)}=
\begin{cases}
0, & j<i,\\[1ex]
e^{-\lambda t}\dfrac{(\lambda t)^{j-i}}{(j-i)!}, & j\ge i.
\end{cases}
\]

This is just the statement that the number of jumps in a time interval of length $t$ is Poisson with mean $\lambda t$.

\paragraph{Explanation.}
The Poisson process \((N_t)_{t\ge 0}\) is a continuous-time Markov chain on the state space
\[
\mathbb N_0=\{0,1,2,\dots\},
\]
because \(N_t\) records the total number of events that have occurred by time \(t\). Since this is a counting process, the state can never decrease: starting from state \(i\), the process can only move to states \(j\ge i\). Hence
\[
p_{ij}^{(t)}=0,\qquad j<i.
\]

Now suppose the process starts from state \(i\). Then after time \(t\), the state of the process is
\[
N_t=i+\bigl(N_t-N_0\bigr).
\]
Thus, in order for the process to be in state \(j\) at time \(t\), there must be exactly \(j-i\) new jumps during the time interval of length \(t\). Since the increments of a Poisson process are stationary and independent,
\[
N_t-N_0\sim \mathrm{Poi}(\lambda t).
\]
Therefore,
\[
p_{ij}^{(t)}
=
\mathbb P(N_t=j\mid N_0=i)
=
\mathbb P(N_t-N_0=j-i).
\]

If \(j\ge i\), this gives
\[
p_{ij}^{(t)}
=
e^{-\lambda t}\frac{(\lambda t)^{j-i}}{(j-i)!}.
\]
So the transition probabilities are
\[
p_{ij}^{(t)}=
\begin{cases}
0, & j<i,\\[6pt]
e^{-\lambda t}\dfrac{(\lambda t)^{j-i}}{(j-i)!}, & j\ge i.
\end{cases}
\]

In other words, the transition matrix of the Poisson process is obtained directly from the fact that the number of jumps in a time interval of length \(t\) has a Poisson distribution with mean \(\lambda t\). This shows that the Poisson process is one of the simplest examples of a continuous-time Markov chain.

\subsection{The generator of a CTMC}

The generator records the infinitesimal behavior of the chain.
For $i,j\in S$, define
\[
g_{ij}
=
\lim_{t\to 0^+}\frac{p_{ij}^{(t)}-\delta_{ij}}{t}
=
\left.\frac{d}{dt}p_{ij}^{(t)}\right|_{t=0},
\]
where
\[
\delta_{ij}=\mathbf 1_{\{i=j\}}.
\]
If the limit exists, the matrix
\[
G=(g_{ij})_{i,j\in S}
\]
is called the \emph{generator} of the chain.

Under mild conditions, the generator exists and has the following basic properties:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item
    \[
    g_{ii}\le 0;
    \]
    \item for $i\ne j$,
    \[
    g_{ij}\ge 0;
    \]
    \item the row sums are zero:
    \[
    \sum_{j\in S} g_{ij}=0.
    \]
\end{itemize}

The last identity follows from the fact that
\[
\sum_{j\in S} p_{ij}^{(t)}=1
\]
for every $t$, so differentiating at $t=0$ gives zero.

\subsection{From generator to transition semigroup}

The continuous-time analogue of repeated matrix multiplication is matrix exponentiation.
If $G$ is the generator, then the transition matrix at time $t$ is
\[
P^{(t)}=(p_{ij}^{(t)})_{i,j\in S}=e^{tG}.
\]
Recall the matrix exponential:
\[
e^{tG}=I+tG+\frac{t^2G^2}{2!}+\frac{t^3G^3}{3!}+\cdots.
\]

The proof idea is the following. By the Markov property,
\[
P^{(t)}=\Bigl(P^{(t/n)}\Bigr)^n.
\]
For small $t/n$,
\[
P^{(t/n)}=I+\frac{t}{n}G+o\!\left(\frac1n\right).
\]
Therefore
\[
P^{(t)}
=\left(I+\frac{t}{n}G+o\!\left(\frac1n\right)\right)^n
\longrightarrow e^{tG}.
\]

So the generator plays the same role in continuous time that the one-step transition matrix plays in discrete time.

\begin{keyformula}
For a CTMC with generator $G$,
\[
P^{(t)}=e^{tG}.
\]
Thus the whole continuous-time evolution is determined by the infinitesimal generator.
\end{keyformula}

\paragraph{Explanation.}
The generator \(G\) describes the infinitesimal behavior of the chain, while \(P(t)\) describes its evolution over a finite time interval of length \(t\). More precisely,
\[
P(t)=(p_{ij}^{(t)})_{i,j\in S},
\qquad
p_{ij}^{(t)}=\mathbb P(X_t=j\mid X_0=i),
\]
and for small \(h>0\), the transition matrix has the approximation
\[
P(h)=I+hG+o(h).
\]
This means that over a very short time interval, the chain is very likely to remain in its current state, and the first-order probabilities of jumping to other states are determined by the generator \(G\).

Now fix \(t>0\), and divide the interval \([0,t]\) into \(n\) equal pieces of length \(t/n\). By the Markov property and time-homogeneity,
\[
P(t)=\bigl(P(t/n)\bigr)^n.
\]
Using the small-time approximation,
\[
P(t/n)=I+\frac{t}{n}G+o\!\left(\frac1n\right),
\]
so
\[
P(t)=\left(I+\frac{t}{n}G+o\!\left(\frac1n\right)\right)^n.
\]
This is the matrix analogue of the classical limit
\[
\left(1+\frac{x}{n}\right)^n \to e^x.
\]
Hence, as \(n\to\infty\),
\[
P(t)\to e^{tG},
\]
where
\[
e^{tG}=I+tG+\frac{t^2G^2}{2!}+\frac{t^3G^3}{3!}+\cdots
\]
is the matrix exponential.

Therefore,
\[
P(t)=e^{tG}.
\]
So the generator \(G\) plays in continuous time the same role that the one-step transition matrix plays in discrete time: it completely determines the evolution of the Markov chain.

\subsection{Generator of the Poisson process}

For the Poisson process of rate $\lambda$ on $\mathbb N_0$, the generator is
\[
G=
\begin{pmatrix}
-\lambda & \lambda & 0 & 0 & \cdots \\
0 & -\lambda & \lambda & 0 & \cdots \\
0 & 0 & -\lambda & \lambda & \cdots \\
\vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots
\end{pmatrix}.
\]
So from each state $i$, the chain waits an exponential time of rate $\lambda$ and then jumps deterministically to $i+1$.

\paragraph{Explanation.}
For a continuous-time Markov chain, the generator matrix \(G=(g_{ij})\) records the instantaneous jump rates of the process. In the case of the Poisson process on the state space
\[
\mathbb N_0=\{0,1,2,\dots\},
\]
the only possible transition from state \(i\) is to state \(i+1\), and this occurs at rate \(\lambda\). Thus, for \(j\neq i\),
\[
g_{ij}=
\begin{cases}
\lambda, & j=i+1,\\
0, & \text{otherwise}.
\end{cases}
\]

The diagonal entries of a generator are determined by the requirement that each row sum to zero. Therefore,
\[
g_{ii}=-\sum_{j\neq i} g_{ij}=-\lambda.
\]
Hence the generator matrix is
\[
G=
\begin{pmatrix}
-\lambda & \lambda & 0 & 0 & \cdots\\
0 & -\lambda & \lambda & 0 & \cdots\\
0 & 0 & -\lambda & \lambda & \cdots\\
\vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\paragraph{Why this generator has this form.}
Recall that for a continuous-time Markov chain, the generator is defined by
\[
g_{ij}
=
\lim_{h\downarrow 0}\frac{p_{ij}(h)-\mathbf 1_{\{i=j\}}}{h}.
\]
In particular, for \(j\neq i\),
\[
g_{ij}
=
\lim_{h\downarrow 0}\frac{p_{ij}(h)}{h}.
\]

For the Poisson process, starting from state \(i\), the state after time \(h\) is
\[
N_h=i+\text{(number of jumps in an interval of length }h).
\]
Since the increment over an interval of length \(h\) has distribution \(\mathrm{Poi}(\lambda h)\), we compute as follows.

If \(j=i+1\), then exactly one jump must occur, so
\[
p_{i,i+1}(h)
=
\mathbb P(\text{exactly one jump in }[0,h])
=
e^{-\lambda h}(\lambda h).
\]
Therefore
\[
g_{i,i+1}
=
\lim_{h\downarrow 0}\frac{e^{-\lambda h}\lambda h}{h}
=
\lambda.
\]

If \(j>i+1\), then at least two jumps must occur in time \(h\). Thus
\[
p_{ij}(h)
=
e^{-\lambda h}\frac{(\lambda h)^{j-i}}{(j-i)!},
\qquad j-i\ge 2.
\]
Since this is of order \(h^2\), we get
\[
g_{ij}
=
\lim_{h\downarrow 0}\frac{p_{ij}(h)}{h}
=
0.
\]

If \(j<i\), then the transition is impossible because the Poisson process is nondecreasing. Hence
\[
p_{ij}(h)=0,
\qquad\text{so}\qquad
g_{ij}=0.
\]

Therefore, for \(j\neq i\),
\[
g_{ij}
=
\begin{cases}
\lambda, & j=i+1,\\[4pt]
0, & \text{otherwise}.
\end{cases}
\]
Finally, the diagonal entries are chosen so that each row sums to zero:
\[
g_{ii}
=
-\sum_{j\neq i}g_{ij}
=
-\lambda.
\]

This matrix reflects the small-time behavior of the Poisson process. Indeed, for small \(h>0\),
\[
p_{ii}(h)\approx 1-\lambda h,
\qquad
p_{i,i+1}(h)\approx \lambda h,
\qquad
p_{ij}(h)\approx 0 \quad \text{for } j\neq i,i+1.
\]
So, over a very short time interval, the process either stays in the same state or jumps upward by exactly one.

Equivalently, when the process is in state \(i\), it waits for an exponential holding time with parameter \(\lambda\), and then jumps deterministically to state \(i+1\). This is exactly the behavior of the Poisson process: the waiting times between successive jumps are i.i.d. exponential random variables with rate \(\lambda\), and each jump increases the count by \(1\).

\subsection{Constructive description of a CTMC}

The lecture ends with a very concrete description of how to build a CTMC from its generator.
Suppose $G=(g_{xy})_{x,y\in S}$ is given.
Define
\[
q_x:=-g_{xx}=\sum_{y\ne x} g_{xy}.
\]
Then, conditional on the current state being $x$:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item the holding time in state $x$ is exponential with rate $q_x$:
    \[
    \tau\sim \mathrm{Exp}(q_x);
    \]
    \item after that holding time, the chain jumps to a new state $y\ne x$ with probability
    \[
    \mathbb P(x\to y)=\frac{g_{xy}}{q_x}.
    \]
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{Why the jump probability is \(\boldsymbol{g_{xy}/q_x}\).}
Suppose the chain is currently in state \(x\). For a small time interval of length \(h\), the generator definition gives
\[
\mathbb P(X_{t+h}=y\mid X_t=x)=g_{xy}h+o(h), \qquad y\neq x.
\]
Thus the probability of a jump specifically from \(x\) to \(y\) in a short interval is approximately \(g_{xy}h\).

If we sum over all possible destinations \(z\neq x\), then the probability that \emph{some} jump occurs from \(x\) during \([t,t+h]\) is
\[
\sum_{z\neq x}\bigl(g_{xz}h+o(h)\bigr)
=
q_x h+o(h),
\]
where
\[
q_x=\sum_{z\neq x}g_{xz}.
\]

Therefore, conditioning on the event that a jump occurs, we obtain
\[
\mathbb P(\text{jump goes to }y \mid \text{a jump occurs from }x)
=
\frac{g_{xy}h+o(h)}{q_x h+o(h)}.
\]
Letting \(h\downarrow 0\), this converges to
\[
\mathbb P(x\to y)=\frac{g_{xy}}{q_x}.
\]

So \(g_{xy}/q_x\) is simply the proportion of the total leaving rate from \(x\) that corresponds to jumps from \(x\) to \(y\).

If $q_x=0$, then the state $x$ is absorbing.

So the chain may be viewed as follows:
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item start at $\bar X_0$ sampled from the initial law $\nu$;
    \item if the current state is $\bar X_k=x$, wait for a time
    \[
    \tau_{k+1}\sim \mathrm{Exp}(q_x);
    \]
    \item then jump to a new state $\bar X_{k+1}=y\ne x$ with probability $g_{xy}/q_x$;
    \item repeat independently at each new state.
\end{enumerate}

If the successive jump states are
\[
\bar X_0,\bar X_1,\bar X_2,\dots,
\]
and the successive holding times are
\[
\tau_1,\tau_2,\tau_3,\dots,
\]
then the continuous-time chain is obtained by keeping the state constant between jumps:
\[
X_t=\bar X_k
\qquad
\text{for }t\in\left[\sum_{i=1}^k \tau_i,\sum_{i=1}^{k+1}\tau_i\right).
\]

This gives a clean decomposition of a CTMC into:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item an \emph{embedded discrete-time Markov chain} $(\bar X_k)$ that records the jump destinations;
    \item random exponential holding times that determine how long the process stays in each state.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Relation with discrete-time Markov chains}

Because of this decomposition, many discrete-time ideas transfer directly to continuous time:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item recurrence and transience;
    \item convergence to stationarity;
    \item long-run averages.
\end{itemize}

The one extra feature in continuous time is that states are not visited for one time step each. Instead, the chain spends an exponential amount of time in each state, and the mean holding time depends on the current state through $q_x=-g_{xx}$.
So when studying time averages, one must weight states according to how long the process typically remains there.

